12	Austria	creation of contingent of yearly granted residence permits	1992	Residence Law 1992 (Aufenthaltsgesetz) - established an annual quota of resident permits granted to new immigrants from EU countries and third countries > In contrast to the quota used for the issuing of work permits, the quota for residence permits defined the absolute number of permits that would be issued in any single year. The quota was divided into sub-quota for students, family members and until April 1995 children born to foreign parents in Austria.	MPI 2003; Bauboeck and Perchinig 2003: 14	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Quota/target	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
13	Austria	access to permanent residency restricted?	1992	Residence Law 1992 (Aufenthaltsgesetz) - introduced a permanent residency permit for migrants with five years of stay. However, this permit could be retrieved in cases of unemployment or financial constraint. > First-time immigrants got a residence permit for six months which could be extended for another six months and then for another two years. Only after five years were they entitled to an unlimited stay. As soon as third country immigrants lost their employment or their accommodation and were not able to find something new in a short period of time, the residence permit expired  a situation that could possibly lead to cases of hardship, as they could be forced to leave the country. A higher level security of residence for long-term immigrants was only introduced with the reform of 1997. Before that residence permits had to be withdrawn if e.g. maintenance or a customary accomodation could not be proved, no matter how long someone had legally resided in Austria.	http://medienservicestelle.at/migration_bewegt/2011/05/25/neue-osterreichische-migrationsgeschichte/ [accessed on 01.07.2013]	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to permanent residency	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
14	Austria	restricted access to immigration visa	1993	Aliens' Act (Fremdengesetz) 1993 reforming the Residence Law and the Asylum Law - ends the existing possibility to transfer from a tourist status to immigration and herewith introduces a distinction between tourist visa and immigration visa, which can only be applied for from the country of origin.	http://medienservicestelle.at/migration_bewegt/2011/05/25/neue-osterreichische-migrationsgeschichte/ [accessed on 01.07.2013]	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
