265	Belgium	simplifying employment of foreign workers	1999	Act of 30 April 1999 revises the legislation governing the employment of foreigners - clarifying and simplifying the provisions on the employment of foreign workers, bringing them into line with other legislation in force in EU countries and ensuring better legal protection for employers.	SOPEMI 2003b: 168-9	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
266	Belgium	Second regularisation	2000	Government declaration passed on December 22, 1999 - initiated a legalization campaign lasting three weeks (Second regularisation since 1974) > In order to be regularized, applicants were required to fulfill one of the following four conditions: having been engaged in the asylum procedure for an abnormally long period without having been informed of a decision (4 years in general, 3 years for families with minor children); not having the objective possibility of returning to one's country due to, for example, a war; suffering a serious illness; or having lived at least six years in the country without having received any official notification to leave the country during the last five years.	MPI 2003; Martiniello 2003: 230	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Regularisation	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
267	Belgium	big reform of the nationality code to facilitate naturalisation	2000	Amendments to the 1984 nationality code came into force in May 2000 (commonly known as 'snel-Belg-wet' or accelerated naturalisation law) - simplifyed the procedure and relaxed basic requirements for naturalisation by eliminating the desire to be integrated as a criterion for nationalisation and by reducing the residence period required before requesting naturalisation has been reduced from five to three years (and two for refugees). Also, there is now the possibility to become Belgian by a mere declaration after seven years of residence. > Belgium has now one of the most liberal legislations on nationality in the European Union.	SOPEMI 2003b: 168-9; SOPEMI 2005: 164; Martiniello 2003: 231; Folbets et al 2013: 2	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
