313	Belgium	resettlement of iraqis	2009	Belgium engaged in an ad-hoc resettlement initiatives in 2009  - as a response to the November 2008 EU Council Conclusions calling for EU countries to resettle displaced Iraqis.	http://www.resettlement.eu//country/belgium [accessed on 30.09.0213]	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Resettlement programmes	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	Specific nationalities	Iraq	Less restrictive		
314	Belgium	asylum seeker reception crisis continued	2009	The saturation of the reception centers for asylum seekers that started in 2008, continued and even aggravated throughout 2009.  > At a certain moment there were no more places available, new arrivals had to be offered a hotel room or to spend the night outside. On 09 July 2009, Fedasil was sentenced by the Labour Tribunal of Brussels to pay a 500/day penalty per asylum seeker if it failed to provide accommodation and appropriate reception conditions as guaranteed by law. The judge decision was the result of legal action by 38 asylum seekers. Because the dispatching service of Fedasil closed on 8 and 9 July 2009, these asylum seekers could not be offered a bed in reception centers. Fedasil had unfruitfully invoked in this case the material impossibility to accommodate more people. In October 2009, Fedasil was again condemned by the Labour Tribunal to pay a 250/day penalty per asylum seeker, following legal action of about 55 asylum seekers. Other legal actions followed. In April 2010, the General Director of Fedasil, and her deputy, resigned from their positions. The position of General Director of Fedasil is still (15 March 2011) vacant.	EMN 2009: 18, 19; EMN 2010: 16	N/A	N/A	Border and land control	Institutional capacities	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
315	Belgium	free access to labour market for EU8	2009	On 1 May 2009, transitory provisions concerning the eight new member countries of the European Union were lifted - citizens of these countries acquired the right to free circulation and employment in Belgium.  > On the other hand, transitory provisions for Bulgarians and Romanians remain in place.	SOPEMI 2010: 192	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Free mobility rights/agreements	All migrant workers	EU citizens	Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, Poland, Slovakia and Slovenia	Less restrictive		
316	Belgium	Third regularisation	2009	A regularisation programme for irregular migrants began in late 2009, with applications accepted from 15 September through 15 December 2009 - It is estimated that some 25 000 persons are eligible according to all these criteria. > Eligible persons include persons residing in Belgium since 2007 and able to present a work contract or prove that they are self-employed; asylum seekers waiting for a decision and having lived in Belgium for 4 years (3 years for women with children); and asylum seekers having lived more than 5 years in Belgium and having appealed to the State Council. The regularisation campaign was a reaction to continued debate in 2007 and in 2008, 2009 on regularisation of irregular migrants for economic or humanitarian reasons. In the first semester of 2009, protest marchs, hunger strikes and actions by activists supporting migrants followed one another.	SOPEMI 2009; SOPEMI 2010: 192; EMN 2009: 9	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Regularisation	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
317	Belgium	exemption of work permits extended to CEOs	2009	Royal Decree of 29 May 2009  - adapts the categories of foreign workers who are exempted of work permit by extending the exemption of senior staff members to « members of the direction» (CEOs)	SOPEMI 2010: 192; EMN 2009 25	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Investors, entrepreneurs and business people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
318	Belgium	material aid for asylum seekers reformed	2010	Amendment of the 2007 Reception Law on 12 January 2010 -  changed in reaction to the reception crisis the right of reception and/or material aid for certain categories of asylum seekers and other foreigners > 1) Fedasil may exclude asylum seekers, who applied for asylum the third or further times 2) the end terms of material aid for asylum seekers and certain other categories of foreigners is specified: if an asylum claim is henceforth concluded with a negative decision of the appeal instance or the Court of Cassation, the material aid is ending after a term of five days after the issue date of the decision (with some exceptions). 3) in exceptional circumstances it is allowed to assign asylum seekers to a local Public Centre for Social Welfare (OCMW/CPAS) for inscription.	EMN 2010: 35	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to social benefits and socio-economic rights	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
319	Belgium	partners of workers now free access to labour market	2011	Royal Decree of 13 March 2011 - adapted the existing law on employment of foreign workers: Since family reunification is in Belgium possible not only for spouses but also for other legally recognized forms of partnership, the legal rules for work permits were adapted >  The concept of spouse has been broadened to include registered partners, who are now placed on an equal footing with spouses regard to access to the labour market.	EMN 2011: 20	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Integration	Work visa/permit	Family members	EU citizens	EU member states at that time	Less restrictive		
320	Belgium	family reunification restricted	2011	New law on family reunification from 8 July 2011, entered into force on 22 September 2011 - restricted the previously flexible law: now,  the sponsor must prove that he or she possesses sufficient and independent income (120 percent of minimum wage), housing, and health insurance. Only partners and minor children qualify for family reunification, and the time period for demonstrating a stable relationship has doubled from one to two years. In addition, applicants must now meet certain integration criteria.	MPI 2012; EMN 2011: 22	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
321	Belgium	increased border control at Oostende	2011	The city of Oostende presented on 19 September 2011 its Action Plan Transit-Migration - increasing the presence of the railway police and the modernisation of the optical observation system of the harbour and the installation of additional enclosures to improve the shielding of the Schengen-Zone of the ferry terminals. > In recent years Oostende is confronted with a rising influx of irregular migrants, planning to travel further to the UK via the port of the city.	EMN 2011: 29	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Border and land control	Surveillance technology/control powers	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
322	Belgium	law on detention of illegally staying families with minor children	2011	Law of 16 November 2011 - specifies the possibilities of detention of illegally staying families with minor children.  > The aim of the law is to avoid detention of families, and when detention is necessary, this must be for a period as short as possible and in an adapted place. A distinction must be made between families at the border and families irregularly staying on the territory: 1) Families, whose access to the territory is refused on grounds of defined criteria, may be detained for an as short as possible period and only in facilities in the border region adapted to the special needs of families. 2) Families without legal stay and already living on the state-territory are generally allowed to remain in their own private housing. In the case the family has no own private housing, it may be detained in a facility adapted to the special needs of families with minor-age children (the so called housing units). In the case the family disrespect the agreed preconditions, the concerned persons may still be detained in units adapted to the special needs of families inside a regular detention facility.	EMN 2012: 25	Minor change	National policy	Border and land control	Detention	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
323	Belgium	prohibition of burqas and niqabs	2011	Law of 1 June 2011 (so-called anti-burqa or anti-niqab law) - bans wardrobes that completely or largely cover the face.  > In December 2012, the Constitutional Court rejected actions for annulment, legitimizing the law which has three objectives: public safety, equality between men and women and a certain conception of living together. It is worth noting in this regard that the arrest of a woman wearing the niqab and following riots in Brussels in June 2012 remained on top of the headlines in Belgium.	EMN 2012: 17	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Access to justice and political rights	All	All	N/A	More restrictive		
