360	Belgium	Family Reunification. Law of 19th March 2014: introduced a right of residence for the parent of a minor EU citizen	2014	Law of 19th March 2014: introduced a right of residence for the parent of a minor EU citizen and for certain other family members of an EU citizen. The family reunification of a parent with its minor is possible if the child is an EU-citizen dependent (economically non-active) on the parent, if the parent has custody over the child and has a health insurance and sufficient (and regular) means of subsistence.	EMN  p.16	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
361	Belgium	Law of 19th March 2014: Law introduced, under specific conditions, a right of residence for certain other family members of EU-citizens	2014	Law of 19th March 2014: Law introduced, under specific conditions, a right of residence for certain other family members of EU-citizens, in accordance with Directive 2004/38:  - The partner with whom the EU citizen has a duly attested durable relationship (and who is not eligible for family reunification as a legally registered partner of the EU-citizen).    - A family member who is in the country from which he has come, dependant or member of the household of the EU citizen (and who is not eligible for family reunification as a spouse or equivalent, a registered partner, (step-) (grand)child or (step-) (grand)parent of the EU-citizen.  - A family member who strictly requires the personal care of the EU-citizen because of serious health reasons (and who is not eligible for family reunification as a spouse or equivalent, a registered partner, (step-) (grand)child or (step-) (grand)parent of the EU-citizen.	EMN  p.17	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
362	Belgium	The Law of 19 March 2014 (modifying the Immigration Act) entailed a number of modifications related to the status of long-term resident	2014	The Law of 19 March 2014 (modifying the Immigration Act) entailed a number of modifications related to the status of long-term resident with the purpose of better transposing EU Directives and reflecting jurisprudence. (residence permit policy). The status is now open to refugees and beneficiaries of subsidiary protection, in accordance with Directive 2011/51/EU amending Council Directive 2003/109/EC to extend its scope to beneficiaries of international protection. For the calculation of the necessary period of residence of 5 years, there are however special rules. In principle only half of the asylum procedure can be calculated (except when it exceeded 18 months). A special notification is made on the residence cards of these long term residents, indicating that they cannot be returned to a country for which they received international protection.	EMN p.22 	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
