1117	Czech Republic	liberal residency permit system introduced	1992	1992 Law on the stay of foreigners (Aliens Act) - introduced a standard modern structure of residence statuses: a short-term residence permit up to six months, a long-term residence permit up to one year and a permanent residence permit.  > The Act allowed foreigners to submit an application for a long-term stay on Czech territory.	SOPEMI 1995: 141; Drbohlav et al 2009: 46; http://www.psp.cz/sqw/sbirka.sqw?cz=123&r=1992 [accessed on 18.02.2014]	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
1118	Czech Republic	permanent residency possible for humanitarian reasons	1992	1992 Law on the stay of foreigners (Aliens Act) - made only humanitarian cases eligible to permanent residence permits. > Other migrants were not permitted to change their statuses from a long-term to a permanent one.	SOPEMI 1995: 141; Drbohlav et al 2009: 46; http://www.psp.cz/sqw/sbirka.sqw?cz=123&r=1992 [accessed on 18.02.2014]	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Access to permanent residency	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
