1151	Czech Republic	tightening of access to business certificate	2000	March 2000 Amendment to the Business Act - restricts the granting of a business certificate to those who previously obtained a long-term visa for the purpose of business activity. The applicant must also demonstrate sufficient financial resources.  > The aim of this amendment is to restrict uncontrolled business activity of foreigners.	SOPEMI 2001b: 153	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Investors, entrepreneurs and business people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1152	Czech Republic	restricted access to immigration visa with tourist visa	2000	Act No. 326/1999, on the Stay of Aliens on the Territory of the Czech Republic (Aliens Act) came into force on 1 January 2000 - making it more difficult for tourists wishing to settle or work in the Czech Republic to change their status. > They will now be obliged to go through prior formalities in embassies or consulates in their home countries. In addition, Czech consulates abroad have been made largely responsible for issuing visas, and the requirements for obtaining a visa on Czech territory have been tightened.  Those who intend to come to the Czech Republic for a specific purpose, such as employment, now must first obtain a visa in their country of origin through Czech embassies or consular offices. This replaced the rather liberal 1992 act.	SOPEMI 1999: 127; SOPEMI 2001a: 167; SOPEMI 2001b: 153	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1153	Czech Republic	stricter rules for temporary residence	2000	Act No. 326/1999, on the Stay of Aliens on the Territory of the Czech Republic (Aliens Act) came into force on 1 January 2000 -  redefining temporary residence and restricting access to temporary permits. These permits could only be obtained through czech embassies, and not any more within the country. >  Temporary residence is possible on a short term visa for non-professional visits under 90 days and on a long-term visa for any stay over 90 days. The validity of short-stay visas has been shortened from 180 to 90 days. Also, the new regulations tightened the application procedure for long term visas by adding stricter conditions and introducing the obligation to submit the visa application abroad.	SOPEMI 2001a: 167; SOPEMI 2001b: 153	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
