1165	Czech Republic	asylum seekers can work only after one year	2002	Amendment to the 2000 Asylum Law - introduced a ban on working legally for the first year of the asylum procedure.  > This was because of an increase in applications from 8,788 in 2000 to 18,094 in 2001	Drbohlav et al 2009: 25	Major change	National policy	Integration	Work visa/permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1166	Czech Republic	only three months subsidies for asylum seekers	2002	Amendment to the 2000 Asylum Law - reduced the time in which asylum seekers can get social subsidies for housing to three months	Drbohlav et al 2009: 25	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to social benefits and socio-economic rights	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1167	Czech Republic	migration policy strategy	2003	Resolution No. 55 of 13 January 2003 - approved the Czech Governments Migration Policy Principles. In six fundamental points, this material defines the direction of the migration policy of the Czech Republic. > Principle 1: With regard to international obligations which are to arise from the EU membership, the Czech Republic consistently fosters government control in the field of migration. Principle 2: The country's migration policy is based on the coordinated approach of all state administration bodies and local governments and institutions and is promoted by other entities dealing with immigration.  Principle 3: The country's migration policy is aimed at eliminating all forms of illegal immigration and other illicit activities by means of measures taken on the basis of international cooperation as well as measures adopted at the national level. Principle 4: The country's migration policy does not hinder legal migration and supports those forms of immigration that are beneficial to the country and society in the long term.  Principle 5: The implementation of the country's migration policy is conditional upon the mass involvement of non-governmental and other organisations of the civic society. Principle 6: The Czech Republic is involved in global and European communities' efforts aimed at coping with migration-related consequences of humanitarian crises and eliminating the reasons for such phenomena.	MPI 2005; http://www.mvcr.cz/mvcren/article/migration.aspx?q=Y2hudW09MQ%3d%3d [accessed on 15.01.2014]	N/A	N/A	Legal entry and stay	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
1168	Czech Republic	skilled migration programme though pbs	2003	In July 2003 the 'Programme of Active Selection of a Qualified Foreign Labour Force' was launched - a program that assesses candidate's present employment, work experience, education, age, previous experience in the Czech Republic, language ability, and family members through a points system. Accepted candidates may qualify to receive a permanent residence after just 2.5 years.  > The project was launched as a pilot in Bulgaria, Croatia and Kazakhstan and extended to 51 countries in the following years. Applications can be made both from these countries and by their nationals from within the Czech Republic, but only if those applying from within the Czech Republic have a legal status. For 2003, the quota was fixed at 300 persons. Between July and April 2004, 167 applicants were selected (mostly from Bulgaria). For 2004, the quota is 1 400 persons. The programme was terminated in 2010.	SOPEMI 2005: 177;  SOPEMI 2003b: 184; SOPEMI 2011: 272	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Points-based system	Skilled/high-skilled workers	Specific nationalities	Those on the list of eligible countries	Less restrictive		
