1212	Czech Republic	green card introduced	2009	Resolution of the Government of the Czech Republic No. 1174 of 22 October 2007 on simplifying the conditions for employment of qualified foreign workers came into force in January 2009 - introduced the Green Card entitling a foreigner to reside and to be employed in the Czech Republic > It is aimed at highly qualified and skilled workers, but does not exclude the possibility of recruiting low-skilled workers for occupations in demand. It is issued to three categories of foreigners: a) qualified workers with university education and key staff; b) workers for jobs requiring the minimum level recognised by an apprentice-leaving exam; c) other workers. The green cards are for third-country nationals listed in the ministerial regulation (In 2012 there were 12 countries: Australia, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Montenegro, Croatia, Japan, South Korea, Canada, Macedonia, New Zealand, Serbia, Ukraine and the United States). The green card is granted for a maximum of two to three years, after which green card holders may apply for formal residence.	SOPEMI 2009; EMN 2012: 21; http://www.mvcr.cz/mvcren/article/migration.aspx?q=Y2hudW09NA%3d%3d [accessed on 15.01.2014]	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	Specific nationalities	Those on the ministerial regulation	Less restrictive		
