1354	Denmark	quicker processing of unjustified asylum applications	2000	A reform of the Aliens Act was implemented in July 2000 - made it possible to process patently unjustified asylum applications more rapidly.  > The main reason for this change seems to be the growing number of Romani immigrants from Poland and the Slovak Republic.	SOPEMI 2001b: 161	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1355	Denmark	new government immigration and integration plan	2000	New government presented a legislative 'package' on immigration and integration - Its principal purpose was to restrict the number of immigrants and refugees, to introduce tougher requirements on access to permanent residence and citizenship, to ensure the loyalty of newcomers to 'Danish values,' and to speed up the integration of immigrants, particularly women and young, second-generation males, into the labor market.  > The proposals passed into law in summer 2002.	MPI 2006	N/A	N/A	Integration	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
1356	Denmark	Ministry of Refugees, Immigrants and Integration created	2001	Ministry of Refugees, Immigrants and Integration Affairs created in 2001 - taking over tasks that had belonged to the Ministry for the Interior. The new minister assumed responsibility for the Aliens Act, the Integration Act, statistics on foreigners, ethnic equality, naturalization, instruction in Danish language and civics, etc.	SOPEMI 2012: 224; MPI 2006	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Institutional capacities	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Change in restrictiveness cannot be assessed		
1357	Denmark	Schengen agreement implemented	2001	Schengen agreement entered into force in 2001 (signature on 19.12.1996) - the free-circulation area will be extended from Nordic countries to the Schengen area	http://people.exeter.ac.uk/watupman/undergrad/rich/time.htm [accessed on 11.09.2013]	Major change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Border and land control	Free mobility rights/agreements	All	EU citizens	EU member states at that time	Less restrictive		
1358	Denmark	work and stay permits required before entering DK	2001	2001 Amendment to the 1993 Aliens Act (711/2001) - requires migrants to have both permission to stay and permission to work before entering Denmark.  > A residence permit is granted after the applicant has received the work permit.	Ortega and Peri 2009	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1359	Denmark	initiation programme for new migrants mandatory	2002	Amendment to the Integration Act in 2002 - makes the Initiation Programme mandatory for newly arriving immigrants  > Background: Since the introduction of the Integration Act, it has become apparent that there is a rather large problem of absenteeism and that large differences exist in the way that local councils interpret this act. As cities that are the most strict in dealing with absenteeism are also the most successful, the Act on Integration has been changed so that it is now mandatory for city councils to consider sanctioning unwilling participants.	SOPEMI 2003a: 168; SOPEMI 2003b: 188	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Language, housing and cultural integration programmes	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1360	Denmark	social benefits cut for new immigrants	2002	Amendment to the Integration Act in 2002 -  reduces the amount of assistance granted to newly-arrived immigrants in order to encourage them to look for a job more rapidly.	SOPEMI 2003a: 168	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to social benefits and socio-economic rights	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1361	Denmark	language exam for naturalisation introduced	2002	Circular on naturalisation of 12 June 2002 - required applicants to sign a declaration on faithfulness and loyalty to Denmark and introduced an examination certificate as documentation of the applicants knowledge of the Danish language.	Ersboll 2013: 21	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1362	Denmark	longer residency requirements for naturalisation	2002	Circular on naturalisation of 12 June 2002 - raised the residence requirements by two years (nine years for aliens with no special status, eight years for refugees and stateless persons and from six to eight years for spouses of citizens  depending on the length of their marriage).	Ersboll 2013: 21	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1363	Denmark	stricter rules of conduct for naturalisation	2002	Circular on naturalisation of 12 June 2002 - strenghtened rules on conduct: a sentence to imprisonment of between one and two years implied a waiting period of eighteen years, and a sentence of more than two years excluded naturalisation forever. Any overdue debts owed to the state also precludes naturalisation.	Ersboll 2013: 21	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	Specific categories	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1364	Denmark	assisted return for afghan asylum seekers	2002	An assisted return programme was initiated in August 2002 - providing financial assistance of up to DKK 20,318 per adult and DKK 6,773 per minor child, for Afghan nationals who had applied for asylum in Denmark by 1 November 2002.	IOM 2004 (Return): 84	Mid-level change	National policy	Exit	Reintegration/return programmes	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	Specific nationalities	Afghanistan	Less restrictive		
1365	Denmark	stricter requirements for granting protection status	2002	Amendments to the Aliens Act entered into force in July 2002 - abolished the de facto status and introduced a protection status (B-status)  > Asylum seekers who previously belonged to the category of de facto refugees are now granted protection status (the new concept replacing de facto status). The conditions for obtaining this status have become stricter and as a result, most asylum seekers in this group do not obtain residence permits. Also, now only applications filed in Denmark are considered.	SOPEMI 2005: 181; DIS 2002: 1	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1366	Denmark	shorter period to leave the country for rejected asylum seekers	2002	Amendments to the Aliens Act entered into force in July 2002 - required asylum seekers whose applications are refused to leave the country immediately (previously they had 15 days).	SOPEMI 2005: 181	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Exit	Expulsion	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1367	Denmark	detention of asylum seekers broadened	2002	Amendments to the Aliens Act entered into force in July 2002 - introduced the possibility of detaining applicants at all stages of the asylum procedure.  > Detention can thus be ordered under the following circumstances:  Upon arrival if the police deems the detention necessary to enforce a potential refusal of entry (return on grounds of the safe third-country concept or transfer under the Dublin Convention);  For asylum seekers whose claims are processed under the accelerated procedure for manifestly unfounded cases;  Prior to enforcement of the removal of foreigners convicted of a criminal offence and ordered deported;  For asylum seekers who do not cooperate in the examination process of their claim by for example not disclosing their identity, or rejectees who attempt to obstruct the removal process, or adopt a violent or threatening behaviour towards personnel in charge of reception or similar centres;  For rejectees pending their removal in order to ensure enforcement of the deportation.	IOM 2004 Return: 74	Minor change	National policy	Border and land control	Detention	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1368	Denmark	stricter requirements for permanent residency for refugees	2002	Amendments to the Aliens Act entered into force in July 2002 - required refugees to have resided in Denmark for seven years (previously three years) in order to be granted permanent status.  > This meant that refugees could be sent home within 7 years if their country is considered safe.	SOPEMI 2005: 181; Mayda 2004: 6	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Integration	Access to permanent residency	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1369	Denmark	stricter requirements for permanent residency	2002	Amendments to the Aliens Act entered into force in July 2002 - raised the requirements for permanent residence permits which can only be granted after 7 years of uninterrupted legal residence (previously 3 years).	SOPEMI 2003a: 168	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to permanent residency	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1370	Denmark	attachment requirement introduced	2002	Amendments to the Aliens Act entered into force in July 2002 - restricted family reunification which can now only be granted if the combined connection of the couple to Denmark is greater than their combined connection to another country.  > This requirement is waived if the individual, already resident in Denmark, has either had Danish citizenship for 28 years or more, or has been born and has lived in the country for 28 years.	http://www.nyidanmark.dk/en-us/coming_to_dk/familyreunification/spouses/attachment-requirement/attachment_requirement.htm [accessed on 14.10.2013]	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1371	Denmark	job card scheme - positive list introduced	2002	Amendments to the Aliens Act entered into force in July 2002 - introducing a special scheme for shortage jobs (Job Card Scheme - Positive List) facilitating access to work and residence permits for immigrants employed in sectors with a shortage of skilled labour (e.g. engineers, scientists in the nature sciencesand technology sector, doctors, nurses and IT specialists).  > In these cases, the Danish Immigration Service  immediately grants a permit for up to 3 years.	SOPEMI 2005: 181; DIS 2007: 7	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
1372	Denmark	additional requirement for refugees and asylum seekers to receive cash allowances	2003	In July 2003, a new law regarding asylum seekers and refugees came into effect - creating a contract that needs to be fulfilled by an applicant in order to receive basic cash allowances from the state.	SOPEMI 2005: 181	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to social benefits and socio-economic rights	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1373	Denmark	stricter age limit for family reunification	2003	In 2003, the '24-year rule' for family reunification was introduced - no Danish citizen can marry a non-EU or Nordic foreign national and settle in Denmark with his/her spouse unless both parties are 24 years or older.  > Also, the immigrants parents cannot, in principle, immigrate and requests from spouses between 18 and 24 years of age will be closely scrutinised.	SOPEMI 2003a: 168; SOPEMI 2003b: 188; MPI 2006	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1374	Denmark	restructuring of the integration programme	2004	New Act on Integration and new Danish Language Act entered into force in January 2004 - to facilitate the integration of foreigners into the labour market.  > The changes involve improved opportunities for newly arrived immigrants to enter the labour market, and economic incentives directed at municipalities, Danish language providers and individual migrants. Counselling, job training and employment are the three stages of the new policy. Particular attention is paid to immigrants who previously were not encouraged to participate in the labour market.	SOPEMI 2005: 181	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Language, housing and cultural integration programmes	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
1375	Denmark	EU 2004 enlargement labour market access restrictions	2004	Since 1 May 2004 workers from the new EU Member States have been covered by transitional rules - Denmark continued to require work permits from citizens from the new EU members stated. Citizens from those countries can receive work permits if they have a minimum of 30 hours of employment per week in Denmark and their position is either covered by a collective bargaining agreement or is in other ways covered by standard Danish terms of employment. For citizens from Cyprus and Malta, the general rules for EU citizens apply.  > The transitional rules are scheduled to end by 1 May 2009 hereafter the general rules for EU citizens will apply.	DIS 2007: 7	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	All migrant workers	EU citizens	Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, Poland, Slovakia and Slovenia	No change		
1376	Denmark	stricter employer sanctions	2004	The penalty for employers offering illegal employment to foreigners was increased - from a fine or imprisonment for up to one year, to a fine or imprisonment for up to two years.	Ortega and Peri 2009	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Border and land control	Employer liabilities	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1377	Denmark	lower age limit for minors under family reunification	2004	Stricter rules on family reunification took effect 1 July 2004 - lowering the normal age limit for minors seeking a Danish residence permit under family reunification rules from 18 to 15.	DIS 2004: 28	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1378	Denmark	no general naturalisation entitlement anymore for second generation migrants	2004	In 2004, the general entitlement rule was repealed - whereby immigrant descendants are referred to apply for Danish citizenship by naturalisation and they have to fulfil the general naturalisation requirements (the general entitlement to citizenship after a certain period of residency was repealed).  > The naturalisation circular provides for few facilitated rules for applicants who have entered Denmark prior to attaining the age of fifteen  they may apply for Danish citizenship at the age of 18. Applicants who have undergone a substantial part of their general education or vocational training in Denmark may apply for naturalisation after four years of residence in Denmark, but for immigrant descendants who are born in Denmark or who have settled in Denmark as minor children, these facilitations have no substantial impact; thus, they can hardly count as facilitations.	Ersboll 2013: 30	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1379	Denmark	declaration of integration to be signed by family reunification applicants	2005	Applicants for family reunification and their spouses now also have to sign a declaration of integration since July 2005. > This obliges an applicant to participate  along with his/her children  actively in Danish language courses and integration into Danish society. The spouse living in Denmark has to declare that he or she will actively support this process.	SOPEMI 2006: 176	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1380	Denmark	more sanctions for those who support irregular migrants	2005	In February the government proposed new changes to the Aliens Act - leading to a significant increase in convictions and the severity of penalties for foreigners who are illegally employed. > Those who help foreigners to stay illegally in Denmark are also targeted. Providing housing, or other forms of assistance can now lead to a punishment of up to two years of imprisonment.	Ortega and Peri 2009	Minor change	National policy	Border and land control	Other sanctions	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1381	Denmark	more sanctions for irregular migrants	2005	In February the government proposed new changes to the Aliens Act - leading to a significant increase in convictions and the severity of penalties for foreigners who are illegally employed. > Under the new amendments, foreign workers who do not have the required work permit will have their sentences raised from financial penalties or imprisonment of up to six months, to increased financial penalties or imprisonment for up to one year.	Ortega and Peri 2009	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Border and land control	Other sanctions	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1382	Denmark	plan suggests more control on integration and access to permanent residency	2005	In June 2005, the parliamentary majority reached an agreement on a variety of integration measures in the context of a new plan entitled a new chance for everyone.  > The measures inter alia include the introduction of mandatory integration contracts for all immigrants who do not have long-term residency (which can generally be obtained after seven years of residence). These contracts oblige immigrants to participate actively in job training and to apply for employment. Respect of the contract influences eligibility for long-term residency. In addition, bilingual children will be offered language stimulation and homework coaches. Danish language skills will be regularly tested. This was implemented in 2006 and 2007.	SOPEMI 2006: 176	N/A	N/A	Integration	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
1383	Denmark	more language courses offered to accepted asylum seekers	2005	In July 2005, Danish language tuition to which accepted asylum seekers may be eligible was increased from 10 to 20 or 25 hours per week.	SOPEMI 2006: 176	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Integration	Language, housing and cultural integration programmes	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
1384	Denmark	cartoon affair	2005	Mohammed Cartoon affair 2005-2006 - Prior to the affair, a number of Danish cartoonists had refused to contribute drawings of Mohammed to a children's book on Islam by a controversial Danish writer. Jyllands-Posten, a Danish daily newspaper with the country's largest circulation, decided to remedy this instance of supposed self-censorship by commissioning and printing 12 satirical cartoons. The paper, tacitly supported by the government and large sections of the public, depicted its decision to print the cartoons as almost an example of civic disobedience, in order to prevent the 'Muslim Other' from winning this clash of cultures. Free speech and the defense of 'our values' is thus the formal framework within which Danish politicians, public commentators, and ordinary people alike find the space and the justification to express disparaging views on Muslim communities and the security threat they are seen to embody.	MPI 2006	N/A	N/A	Integration	Contextual elements	All	All	N/A	N/A		
1385	Denmark	government bill presented to strenghten immigration and integration rules	2006	The government put forward a bill in November 2006 - it suggested the following measures: > * Foreigners with a specific job offer earning at least EUR 60000 (DKK 450000) can obtain a residence permit, even for employment in sectors where there is no shortage of labour (pay limit scheme, implemented in 2008) * Introduction of a points system (greencard-scheme) by which high-qualified foreigners may be granted a residence permit for up to 6 months in order to seek employment in Denmark. Points are given according to a set of criteria including education, language, work experience and age. Foreigners who have concluded a post-secondary educational programme in Denmark shall have the possibility to seek a job for a period for up to 6 months. (implemented in 2008) * The bill also includes measures to further tighten conditions for obtaining a permanent residence permit. An integration exam is planned according to which, among other restrictions, an applicant must have been at least 2½ years in full-time employment in order to obtain a permanent residence permit. (implemented in 2007) * The bill contains proposals on further restrictions on family reunification. Applicants must have passed a test in Danish language and Danish society in order to obtain a residence permit (introduced in 2007 or 2010)	SOPEMI 2007: 242	N/A	N/A	Legal entry and stay	Contextual elements	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
1386	Denmark	stricter requirements for permanent residency	2006	In March 2006, conditions for obtaining a permanent residence permit had been tightened. > Applicants must, among other obligations, have signed an integration contract and declare that they will involve themselves actively in integration into Danish society. These contracts oblige immigrants to participate actively in job training and to apply for employment. Respect of the contract influences eligibility for long-term residency.	SOPEMI 2007: 242	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to permanent residency	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
