1388	Denmark	rules of conduct for naturalisation strenghtened	2006	Circular on naturalisation of 12 January 2006 - further strenghtened the rules on conduct: a sentence to a term of imprisonment of more than 60 days for violations of the Criminal Codes Parts 12 and 13 as well as a sentence to a term of imprisonment of more than eighteen months exclude naturalisation forever.	Ersboll 2013: 22	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	Specific categories	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1389	Denmark	applicant for naturalisation must be self supporting	2006	Circular on naturalisation of 12 January 2006 - introduced as a new condition for naturalisation that the applicants must be self-supporting, which at that time was defined in the sense that they could not have received social benefits according to the social assistance law or the integration law (at that time) for more than one out of the last five years.	Ersboll 2013: 22	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1390	Denmark	language test for naturalisation level raised	2006	Circular on naturalisation of 12 January 2006 - raised the Danish language skill requirements  considerably from Test in Danish 2 (comparable to ALTE level 2 and the Council of Europe level B1) to Test in Danish 3 (comparable to ALTE level 3 and the Council of Europe level B2).  > The tests require three years Danish language courses. At that time, the language schools reported that on a national basis only around 25-30 per cent of all participants were referred to Danish Education Programme 3.	Ersboll 2013: 22	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1391	Denmark	citizenship exam introduced (implemented in 2007)	2006	Circular on naturalisation of 12 January 2006 -  introduction a citizenship test by which the applicants should demonstrate their knowledge of Danish culture, history and society. The test was introduced in the naturalisation circular and implemented in May 2007.  > It was organised by the language schools across Denmark as a multiple choice test with a list of potential answers to each question. Among the 40 questions, 35 were selected from a question bank with 200 questions (in Danish). The question bank was made public at the homepage of the Ministry of Integration, where the applicants could read both the 200 questions and the corresponding correct answers. Based on this arrangement where the applicant could learn all the answers to the questions in the test bank by heart, about 97 per cent of the tested persons passed the test. Many applicants considered the citizenship test a piece of cake. As a whole it gave rise to criticism. It was widely held that the test was very easy to pass and therefore needless.	Ersboll 2013: 22	N/A	N/A	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
