1398	Denmark	green card scheme created	2007	In April 2007, the Green Card Scheme was created - granting a six-month residence permit to those passing a points system to seek employment (the  Green Card Scheme came into force on 10 October 2007).  > Residence permits falling under the Green Card Scheme are issued based on an individual evaluation to determine the likelihood that the applicant will be able to find work in his/her field within six months. The evaluation uses a point system. In order to be granted a residence permit under the Green Card Scheme the applicant must attain at least 80 points. Points are given for educational level, language skills, work experience and age. The applicant is not allowed to work in Denmark while seeking employment.	DIS 2007: 7	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Points-based system	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
1399	Denmark	green card scheme for students	2007	As of 25 July 2007 a special Green Card Scheme for students that have completed a higher educational programme in Denmark was implemented - Those student residence permits are valid for an additional six months after they have completed the programme to allow them to apply for work in Denmark.  > During this jobseeking period the same rules apply as to foreign students still following a higher educational program. This means that the foreigner is allowed to work 15 hours a week, as well as fulltime during the months of June, July and August. Additional work requires a residence and work permit.	DIS 2007: 7	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	International students	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
