1408	Denmark	Corporate scheme for big companies	2008	Amendment of the Aliens Act taking effect on 1 July 2008 - introduced the Corporate Scheme, allowing employees from a companys foreign department to obtain a corporate residence permit in Denmark > The Corporate scheme makes it possible for companies with operations in Denmark to transfer employees with special abilities or qualifications from the companys foreign departments to Denmark to work on a specific project or to carry out work that is innovative, developmental or educational in nature.	DIS 2008: 16	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
1409	Denmark	stricter naturalisation requirements	2008	Circular of 22 november 2008 on naturalisation - strenghtened the language and the citizenship test requirements.  > The citizenship test questions and answers can no longer be found on the homepage of the Ministry of Integration; only sample questions are accessible. In addition, 32 out of the 40 questions (instead of 28) must be answered correctly in order to pass the test, and the applicants have only 45 minutes (instead of an hour) to complete the test.  As to the Danish language requirement it was no longer sufficient to pass Danish Test 3 (B2)  passing requires a mark of 6 (on a 13-point scale) or a mark of 2 (on the 7-step scale); after the agreement, the general language requirement was set to a certificate of having passed Danish Test 3 with an average mark of at least 7 (on the 13-point scale) or 4 (on the 7- step scale) (or another comparable exam).	Ersboll 2013: 24	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1410	Denmark	new division to deal with radicalisation	2008	In 2008, the Division for Cohesion and Prevention of Radicalisation was established within the Ministry of Integration Affairs > The overall aim of this division is the prevention of radicalisation.	SOPEMI 2010: 200	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Institutional capacities	All	All	N/A	Change in restrictiveness cannot be assessed		
1411	Denmark	EU 2004 enlargements labour market access restrictions ceased	2009	2004 enlargement - The transitional legislation for citizens from the 2004 newly joined EU countries (Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania, Poland, Slovakia, Slovenia, Czech Republic and Hungary) ceased on 1 May 2009.	SOPEMI 2009	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Free mobility rights/agreements	All migrant workers	EU citizens	Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, Poland, Slovakia and Slovenia	Less restrictive		
1412	Denmark	EU 2007 enlargements labour market access restrictions ceased	2009	2007 enlargement - The transitional legislation for citizens from the 2007 newly joined EU countries (Bulgaria, Romania) ceased on 1 May 2009.	SOPEMI 2009	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Free mobility rights/agreements	All migrant workers	EU citizens	Romania, Bulgaria	Less restrictive		
1413	Denmark	specific board to deal with discriminations	2009	On 1 January 2009, the new Complaints Board on Equal Treatment came into force - to handle concrete complaints about discriminatory treatment of any kind and is able to award discrimination victims for non-pecuniary damages.	SOPEMI 2010: 200	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Institutional capacities	All	All	N/A	Less restrictive		
1414	Denmark	PBS introduced to grant permanent residency	2010	New rules regarding permanent residence permits entered into force in June 2010 - In order to qualify for a permanent residence permit, the applicant must meet a number of criteria along a points-based system. > Points are awarded for Danish language knowledge, active participation in Danish society, a completed degree in Denmark, and employment for a number of years prior to acceptance of the application, among other criteria. Exemptions may apply for disabled, pensioners, young applicants, and applicants with strong ties to Denmark. In addition, all applicants must have at least four years of residence and no serious criminal record. If the foreigner cannot obtain the required 100 points, he or she can apply for an extension of the time-limited residence permit and apply for a permanent residence permit at a later date.	SOPEMI 2011: 274	Major change	National policy	Integration	Points-based system	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1415	Denmark	stricter requirements for entry of spouse	2010	Since 1 August 2010, a spouse/partner living in Denmark must not have received public assistance for a period of three years prior to the application of his/her spouse/partner.  > This period was one year before.	SOPEMI 2011: 274	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1416	Denmark	immigration test for family migrants	2010	Since 15 November 2010, spouses/partners are  required to pass an immigration test veryfing Danish language skills and knowledge about Denmark and Danish society > This test has to be taken in Denmark, and a fee of DKK 3 000 (EUR 400) applies. This requirement was introduced in 2007 but only implemented in 2010.	SOPEMI 2011: 274	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1417	Denmark	more protection for au pairs	2010	On 1 September 2010, the practice for residence permits for au pairs was modified to respond to the growing flow and to reports of abuse - au pairs may no longer have children back in their country of origin and during the assessment of the application, the applicants family ties to the host family may be taken into account. In addition, every host family must have a separate room for the au pair.	SOPEMI 2011: 274	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Low-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1418	Denmark	substantial change of voluntary return programme	2010	On 16 March 2010, legislative changes amended the Danish Repatriation Act - to facilitate voluntary return for elderly persons and for persons without contact to the labour market and to increase the incentives for immigrants to return if they cannot or will not integrate in the Danish society > The payment for voluntary return was increased significantly from up to DKK 28 256 (about EUR 3 800) in 2009 to DKK 117 581 (about EUR 15 800) in 2010 for each adult. Furthermore, the age condition to be eligible for the so-called reintegration allowance for elderly persons has been lowered from 60 to 55 years. Finally, a foreigner holding a residence permit based on family reunification no longer must hold a permanent residence permit to qualify for financial assistance, but must have had a residence permit in Denmark for at least five years.	SOPEMI 2011: 274	Minor change	National policy	Exit	Reintegration/return programmes	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
1419	Denmark	Migration and Integration Strategy of Denmark until 2020	2010	In February 2010, the Government launched its work plan Denmark 2020 - including goals for boosting labour supply and for strenghening the integration of migrants and their descendants into the labour market by 2020.  > To reach these goals, facilitations for high-qualified immigrants to work and study in Denmark are considered, as well as improved facilities and integration measures for accompanying spouses and children.	SOPEMI 2011: 274	N/A	N/A	Legal entry and stay	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
1420	Denmark	integration courses extended to EU migrants	2010	Since 1 August 2010, the Integration Act is amended - also covering newly arrived labour migrants, students and nationals of EU and EEA countries benefiting from the rules on free movement of persons in the EU. > These groups will be offered a so-called introductory course (a lighter version of the integration programme for refugees and family reunified persons).	SOPEMI 2011: 274	Major change	National policy	Integration	Language, housing and cultural integration programmes	All migrants	EU citizens	N/A	Less restrictive		
1421	Denmark	content of integration courses widened	2010	Since 1 August 2010, the Integration Act is amended - offering a course on Danish society and Danish culture and history to all newly arrived refugees and immigrants covered by the Integration Act.  > In addition, municipalities must be able to offer employment-related activities to newly arrived refugees and immigrants who do not work and are supported by their spouse.	SOPEMI 2011: 274	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Language, housing and cultural integration programmes	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
1422	Denmark	government change and change in policy objectives	2011	After ten years of centre-right coalitions, a new left coalition government was appointed in October 2011 - In 'A Denmark that stands together, the new government has announced wide-ranging reforms of migration and integration policy.  > Proposed changes include: A change in the requirements for permanent residency; a change of admission requirements for family migrants; allowing asylum seekers and refugees to live and work outside the asylum centres six months after arrival; liberal changes to the naturalisation requirements; the abolition of lower social benefit rates applied for immigrants. In the area of integration the focus remains on facilitating immigrant access to the labour market and education.	SOPEMI 2012: 224	N/A	N/A	Legal entry and stay	Contextual elements	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
1423	Denmark	rearrangement of ministerial responsibilities	2011	The Ministry of Refugees, Immigrants and Integration Affairs, which had been created in 2001, was abolished - its portfolio divided between the Social Affairs Ministry  renamed as Ministry of Social Affairs and Integration  and the Ministry of Justice. > More broadly, the creation of the new Ministry of Social Affairs and Integration brings a different approach to integration, one which allows for differentiations among immigrants and their needs according to their social context.	SOPEMI 2012: 224	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Institutional capacities	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Change in restrictiveness cannot be assessed		
1424	Denmark	housing rules changed	2011	The Integration Act of 1999 was amended in July 2011  - removing the right of local authorities to assign migrants housing in deprived neighbourhoods, in order to combat residential segregation and thereby strengthen integration.	SOPEMI 2013: 246	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Language, housing and cultural integration programmes	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
1425	Denmark	initiative to increase labour market participation of immigrants	2012	The Ministry of Employment rolled out an initiative in 2012 called We Need Everyone - This initiative focuses on individuals receiving cash assistance (not including newly arrived immigrants already in an integration programme) who are considered to have most difficulty in finding a job due to personal or social problems.  > About a quarter of the 29 550 targeted individuals are non-Western immigrants. In each municipality a dedicated team makes plans for their job placement.	SOPEMI 2013: 246	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Language, housing and cultural integration programmes	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
1426	Denmark	cash allowances for new migrants replaced by direct access to social assistance	2012	From January 2012, cash allowances for newly arrived refugees and immigrants, as well as the starter allowances for persons having resided in Denmark for less than seven of the preceding eight years will be eliminated - instead, new immigrants will be entitled to social assistance from the moment they arrive in Denmark.	SOPEMI 2013: 246	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to social benefits and socio-economic rights	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
1427	Denmark	stricter sanctions of THB	2012	In March 2012, amendments strenghtening the framework on trafficking entered into force > The maximum sentence for trafficking in the Danish Criminal Codes was increased from eight to ten years of imprisonment. The definition of trafficking was also expanded to include trafficking for petty crimes.	EMN 2012	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Border and land control	Other sanctions	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1428	Denmark	biometric residence cards introduced	2012	In May 2012, biometric residence cards were launched in Denmark - They contain finger prints and photo of the applicant along with personal data.	EMN 2012	Major change	National policy	Border and land control	Identification documents	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1429	Denmark	family reunification rules changes	2012	Since May 2012, the rules for family reunification have changed - the application fee was reduced and the points system was replaced by a new set of rules whereby foreign nationals can now obtain a residence permit if their spouse, cohabitant or registered partner is already legally residing in Denmark.  > The new rules require that both the applicant and the spouse be at least 24 years old (this requirement was reintroduced) and that the applicant pass a Danish language test within six months of receiving a residence permit. Moreover, the amount of collateral for a spouse has been lowered (from DKK 100.000 to DKK 50.000 (2012-level)). In addition, the couples combined attachment to Denmark must be greater than the couples combined attachment to any other country in order to qualify for spousal reunification  the former rules stated that it had to be significantly greater. However, the length of legal residency/citizenship granting exemption from this requirement would be reduced from 28 to 26 years.	SOPEMI 2012: 224; SOPEMI 2013: 246; EMN 2012	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
1430	Denmark	change in requirements for permanent residency	2012	New rules regarding permanent residence permits entered into force in July 2012 - The former points system, which required applicants to reach a 100-point threshold based on diverse eligibility criteria, was dropped.  > The issuance of a permanent residence permit is now made conditional on four requirements: at least five years residence in Denmark (up from four), three years full-time employment in the previous five years, financial self-support, and passage of a language test.	SOPEMI 2012: 224; SOPEMI 2013: 246	Major change	National policy	Integration	Points-based system	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
1431	Denmark	work allowed for refugees after six months	2012	A new rule enacted in September 2012 - allows asylum seekers and refugees to take up employment and residence outside of refugee centres after six months, on condition that they co-operate with authorities.	SOPEMI 2013: 246	Major change	National policy	Integration	Work visa/permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
1432	Denmark	new vision on integration	2012	In November 2012 the Government launched its new vision for integration - which include better reception, improved access to education and a more active role for migrants in society and the labour market. > The vision deals with seven main areas of concern: * Management and monitoring of the integration effort (including the launch of a National Integration Barometer with indicators for successful integration concerning, inter alia, discrimination, active citizenship, employment, education and knowledge of Danish language); * Reception and integration of newly arrived refugees and migrants; * Ensuring a higher rate of employment of migrants and descendants; * Furthering education  focusing on better achievements of migrants and descendants in schools and in the educational system; * Strengthening active citizenship and social inclusion, equal opportunities and gender equality among migrants and descendants; * Ensuring a more comprehensive integration effort in deprived housing areas; * Preventing of marginalisation and crime with regard to migrants and descendants	EMN 2012	N/A	N/A	Integration	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
1433	Denmark	eased naturalisation requirements	2013	Political agreement of 23 May 2013 on the naturalisation criteria - facilitating the language and civic knowledge requirements and the requirement on being self-supporting.  > the language requirement is lowered to the level adopted in 2002, and the requirement on being self-supporting has to a certain extent been eased (reception of social benefits for up to two and a half year within the last five years is accepted).	SOPEMI 2013: 246; Ersboll 2013: 26	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
1434	Denmark	announcement to allow dual citizenship	2013	Political agreement of 23 May 2013 on the naturalisation criteria - states in its introduction  that the amendments concerning acceptance of dual citizenship and automatic citizenship to immigrant descendants are expected to be implemented in the 2013-14 parliamentary session.	Ersboll 2013: 26	N/A	N/A	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
1435	Denmark	Amendment of the Aliens Act, in force since May 2013	2013	Amendment of the Aliens Act, in force since May 2013  provided that with regards to the revocation of residence permits issued on the basis of spousal reunification in cases where the foreigner concerned or the foreigners child has been exposed to abuse etc. by the spouse, the length of the foreigners residence in Denmark can no longer be taken into consideration if the abuse has caused the cessation of cohabitation and the invoked abuse has been substantiated, when deciding whether a foreigner can retain his or her residence permit	EMN factsheet p.1	fine-tuning change	National policy	legal entry and stay	entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	less restrictive		
1436	Denmark	Amendment of the Aliens Act, in force since May 2013  new possibilities to live outside the asylum centres	2013	Amendment of the Aliens Act, in force since May 2013  provided new possibilities to live outside the asylum centres to asylum beneficiaries and international protection status holders. Accommodation outside an asylum centre may include: private lodging with family or friends, privately rented accommodation, or independent accommodation in connection with an asylum centre.	EMN factsheet p.2	minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	language, housing and cultural integration programmes	refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
1437	Denmark	Amendment of the Aliens Act, in force since May 2013. seek employment	2013	Amendment of the Aliens Act, in force since May 2013  stated that asylum seekers are now allowed to seek for employment	EMN  factsheet p.2	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Access to social benefits and socio-economic rights	refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	less restrictive		
1438	Denmark	Amendment of the Aliens Act, in force since May 2013  Danish language lessons	2013	Amendment of the Aliens Act, in force since May 2013  introduced the offer of Danish language lessons and orientation with regard to the Danish labour market, education system and housing possibilities to asylum seekers	EMN factsheet p.2	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	language, housing and cultural integration programmes	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	less restrictive		
