1696	Finland	Returning Ingrians granted automatic residence permit	1990	10 April 1990 announcement made by the president - granting all ethnic Finns living within the former Soviet Union automatic residence permit if they chose to return to Finland.  > There was not really a well planned repatriation programme and  came as a surprise to the public as well as authorities, who had quickly to prepare for potentially large-scale immigration by ethnic Finns from the Soviet Union. The president himself motivated it mainly with a need of more labour force. Background: Many of these people, known as Ingrian Finns, are descended from 17th-century vanguards of Swedish Lutheranism who originally settled in Ingria, near Saint Petersburg, when Finland and that part of present-day Russia were under Swedish control. Because the Ingrian Finns were poorly treated by the Soviet Union, many Finns felt that Estonian or Russian citizens from the Ingria region who were sufficiently Finnish in terms of ethnicity had a morally legitimate right of return.	MPI 2011; Leitzinger 2010: 68, 72, 82-84	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Diaspora	Specific nationalities	Ethnic Finns in Former Soviet Union	Less restrictive		
1697	Finland	border control with Russia increased due to Somali refugee inflow	1991	In January 1991, the president required tougher measures in guarding the borders against asylum-seekers coming through Russia, and cooperation with Soviet authorities in keeping traffic under control was stepped up > Background: Somali immigration to Finland started in May 1990 through Russia. By the end of the year 1441 Somalis had applied for asylum, and soon they became the largest Muslim and also the largest African nationality in Finland.	Leitzinger 2010: 85-86	Mid-level change	National policy	Border and land control	Surveillance technology/control powers	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	Those coming through Russia	More restrictive		
1698	Finland	new aliens act	1991	New Aliens Act took effect in March 1991 - consolidating regulations on arrIval, departure, residence and working of aliens. It listed dozens of separate categories for residence permits while before the permit would not have indicated the exact justification. > They do not bring about any major changes in the basic principles of Finnish immgration policy. The new law was issued too quickly and had soon to be amended many times.	SOPEMI 1992: 59;  Leitzinger 2010: 79, 126, 134, 154, 187-189	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	No change		
1699	Finland	commission for both refugee and migration issues	1991	The separate commissions for migration and refugee issues were united into a Refugee and Migration Commission	Leitzinger 2010: 188	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Institutional capacities	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Change in restrictiveness cannot be assessed		
1700	Finland	visa introduced for citizens from former yugoslav countries	1992	Finland introduced visas for citizens from former Yugoslavian countries in July 1992 > Background: In summer 1992, a sudden influx of Kosovo Albanian asylum-seekers from visa-free Yugoslavia, caused the Finnish government to call off the visa-free treaty.	SOPEMI 1995: 81; Leitzinger 2010: 90-91; http://www.migri.fi/tietoa_virastosta/tilastot/turvapaikka-_ja_pakolaistilastot/turvapaikanhakijat_ja_paatokset_1990-1999 [accessed on 21.01.2014]	N/A	N/A	Legal entry and stay	Travel visa/permit	All	Specific nationalities	Former Yugoslavia	N/A		
1701	Finland	agreements on trainee exchange with Russia and Estonia	1992	Treaties have been signed with Russia and Estonia - allowing for special quotas of trainees to enter Finland to improve their qualifications and labour skills, normally for periods of 8-12 months.  > The first trainees are expected in 1993.	SOPEMI 1994: 74	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	Specific nationalities	Russia, Estonia	Less restrictive		
1702	Finland	restrictions on rights to property  for foreigners removed	1992	The restrictions on foreigners' rights to property from 1939 were removed in 1992 in anticipation of Finland's accession to the EU	Leitzinger 2010: 190	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to social benefits and socio-economic rights	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
1703	Finland	residence granted to bosnian refugees	1993	Special act on 8 January 1993 - grants Bosnians (mainly Muslims) residence permits on the exceptional handling of Yugoslavian asylum-applications.	Leitzinger 2010: 90, 189	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	Specific nationalities	Bosnia	Less restrictive		
1704	Finland	safe country rule introduced	1993	A new legislation governing the right of asylum came into force on 1 July 1993 - providing for the rejection of applications from asylum seekers originating from safe countries or those arriving via countries deemed to be safe  > EFTA or EU countries, Poland, Czech Republic, Slovak Republic were considered safe countries. In January 1994 the government extended the list to include Russia, Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania and Hungary.	SOPEMI 1995: 82	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	Those transiting through or originating from countries on the safe country list	More restrictive		
1705	Finland	Free movement of workers within EEA	1994	Agreement between Finland and EEA on free labour migration - forbids any discrimination based on the nationality of European citizens who wish to take up employment in Finland > As a consequence of the entry into force of the Agreement on the European Economic Area, workers from Austria, Finland and Sweden were granted the right of free movement in the internal market before the accession of those countries to the European Union.	OECD 2012 (Free mobility): 40	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Free mobility rights/agreements	All migrant workers	EU citizens	EU member states at that time	Less restrictive		
1706	Finland	family reunification for European workers	1994	Agreement between Finland and EEA on free labour migration - grants European citizens the right to family reunification, regardless of the nationality of the family members	OECD 2012 (Free mobility): 40	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	EU citizens	EU member states at that time	Less restrictive		
1707	Finland	Free movement for Finish workers	1994	Agreement between Finland and EEA on free labour migration - forbids any discrimination based on the nationality of Finish citizens who wish to take up employment in another Member State. > As a consequence of the entry into force of the Agreement on the European Economic Area, workers from Austria, Finland and Sweden were granted the right of free movement in the internal market before the accession of those countries to the European Union.	OECD 2012 (Free mobility): 40	Major change	National policy	Exit	Free mobility rights/agreements	All migrant workers	Citizens	N/A	Less restrictive		
