1726	Finland	MoU signed with NZ and AUS on trainee agreement	2002	In 2002, Finland signed a working holiday maker agreement with Australia and New Zealand in 2002 - to enable the young nationals of those countries to take working holidays in Finland.	SOPEMI 2003b: 191; http://formin.finland.fi/public/default.aspx?contentid=56902&culture=en-US, http://formin.finland.fi/Public/default.aspx?contentid=50420&contentlan=1 [accessed on 21.01.2014]	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Low-skilled workers	Specific nationalities	Australia, New Zealand	Less restrictive		
1727	Finland	asylum seekers can work after 3 months	2002	In October 2002, the labour market test for asylum seekers was abolished - the requirement that asylum seekers first receive approval on the basis that there was no-one else available to do the job in question was abolished and from now on, asylum seekers who have been in Finland for at least 3 months may work.	SOPEMI 2003b: 192	Major change	National policy	Integration	Work visa/permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
1728	Finland	dual citizenship allowed	2003	In June 2003, the new Nationality Act came into force - legitimising the holding of multiple nationalities both for Finns and foreigners acquiring a new nationality > Loss of Finnish citizenship is no longer a consequence of the acquisition of a foreign citizenship. Nor does the current Act include a requirement of renunciation of former citizenships when acquiring Finnish citizenship.	SOPEMI 2005:188; MPI 2011; Fagerlung and Brander 2013: 14	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All	All	N/A	Less restrictive		
1729	Finland	residency requirement longer, but alternative counting method introduced	2003	In June 2003, the new Nationality Act came into force - increasing the number of years of continuous residence required for naturalisation  from five to six years. > At the same time an alternative residency requirement, an accumulated period of residence, was introduced, according to which residence in Finland for eight years after the age of fifteen, with the last two years uninterrupted equally qualified for naturalisation	Fagerlung and Brander 2013: 19	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Change in restrictiveness cannot be assessed		
1730	Finland	stricter language skill requirements for naturalisation	2003	In June 2003, the new Nationality Act came into force - for the first time mentioned language skills requirement explicitly: Before 2003, there was only a general requirement of sufficient knowledge of Finnish or Swedish stipulated by decree without clear rules on how to prove language proficiency. After the adoption of the 2003 Act, the documentation accepted as proof of the language skills were outlined.  > The most common way to show language skills is to pass a general language examination (National Certificate of Language Proficiency test) at level three (out of six levels, where six is excellent and three is satisfactory). Language proficiency can also be shown by completing different kinds of education (comprehensive school, upper secondary school, vocational qualifications or university studies in Finland) in Finnish or Swedish or by passing the Civil Service Language Proficiency Certificate. The language skills requirement of the 2003 Nationality Act is without dispute more difficult than under earlier legislation.	Fagerlung and Brander 2013: 22	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1731	Finland	eased naturalisation for descendants for Finnish citizens	2003	In June 2003, the new Nationality Act came into force - Persons who have lost Finnish citizenship or who are descendants of Finnish citizens or former Finnish citizens, can, until the end of May 2008, regain or acquire Finnish citizenship if they make an appropriate declaration.	SOPEMI 2005:188	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	Diaspora	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
