1967	France	Family reunification restricted	2006	Law 2006-911 of 24 July 2006 relative to immigration and integration - restricted the possibilities for family reunification  > The law extended the required time of residence for the applicant from 12 to 18 months, imposed stricter resource requirements (now calculated without family and social benefits) and made the extension of the residence permit granted to the spouse uncertain in the event of a breakup. Also, the minimum age for women wishing to marry or to benefit from family reunification has been raised to 18. Background: Family reunification accounts for nearly 65 percent of immigration to France.	SOPEMI 2007: 99, 246; SOPEMI 2008: 242; MPI 2006	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1968	France	new temporary residence permit for high skilled and ICTs	2006	Law 2006-911 of 24 July 2006 relative to immigration and integration - created two new types of 3-year residence permits for highly skilled: the Skills and Talents and Employee on Assignment permit > Under the new law, foreigners who possess skill sets of interest to French employers in the designated areas will be granted 'skills and talents' visas, valid for three years. In a uniquely French twist, eligible candidates must be able to demonstrate that they will contribute to the economic or intellectual and cultural development of both France and their country of origin. In an attempt to ease fears about 'brain drain,' the government will only issue this visa to qualified immigrants from a developing country if the sending country has signed a 'co-development' agreement with France or if the immigrants in question agree to return to their country of origin within six years.	SOPEMI 2007: 99, 246; MPI 2006	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	Specific nationalities	Those with co-development agreements	Less restrictive		
1969	France	eased working rights for students during and after studies	2006	Law 2006-911 of 24 July 2006 relative to immigration and integration - makes it easier for foreign students to work during their studies, as they are now allowed to work up to 60% of annual work time and can continue their stay in France when their student status ends. > The new law would require foreign students to receive approval to study in France from their country of origin. Once in France, foreign students who receive a masters or higher degree would be allowed to pursue a 'first professional experience' that contributes to the economic development of both France and the student's country of origin. The student will be granted a six-month renewable visa to look for and take up work in France.  Foreign students can continue their stay in France when their student status ends. If they fulfil the conditions for issue, they may obtain the following permits: the skills and talents residence permit, the scientist residence permit or provisional authorisation to reside six months with option of looking for full-time employment in any professions without invoking employment situation, on condition that they are in receipt of remuneration that is greater than 1.5 times the SMIC and that they choose a professions related to the qualification conferred by the diploma	SOPEMI 2007: 99, 246; MPI 2006; EMN 2010: 18	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Work visa/permit	International students	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
1970	France	Integration contract made mandatory for all over 16	2006	Law 2006-911 of 24 July 2006 relative to immigration and integration - makes the Welcome and Integration Contract (Contrat daccueil et dintégration) mandatory for all persons aged over 16 years > The CAI (reception and integration contract) is signed between the State, represented by the Prefect, and the migrant, for a period of one year, which is possibly renewable for a similar period. The State, through the French Office for Immigration and Integration (OFII) and manages the following services: - a one-day citizenship training course which consists of an introduction to French institutions and the values of the French Republic,  - language training, where required, which be up to 400 hours, officially recognised by the issue of the initial diploma in French language (DILF).  - social support if the personal or family circumstances of the signatory so justify.	SOPEMI 2008: 242; EMN 2009: 32	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Language, housing and cultural integration programmes	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
1971	France	creation of new deportation measure, obligation to leave	2006	Law 2006-911 of 24 July 2006 relative to immigration and integration - introduced a new deportation measure, the obligation to leave French territory (OQTF). > The situation prior to the entry into force of the Decree of 23 December 2006 was shown to be unsatisfactory in terms of deportation effectiveness. Before the OTQF was implemented, whenever a Prefecture withdrew or refused a residence permit, it accompanied its decision with an invitation to leave French territory (IQTF) within a period of one month. This decision in itself did not bear any consequences  it only notified foreign persons of the date on which they would become an illegal resident, and of the opportunity to benefit from assisted repatriation. The introduction of the OQTF now enables Prefects to accompany their decisions of refusal, non-renewal or withdrawal of a residence permit of any kind, with an obligation to leave French territory (OQTF).	EMN 2008: 12	Minor change	National policy	Exit	Expulsion	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
