2250	Germany	old case arrangement	1999	1999 Old Case-Arrangement - granted rejected asylum seekers a residence permit if they were residing in Germany for at least six (with children) or eight (without children) years.   > The applicant may not have violated the law in any way and may not have been receiving social benefits in order to live.  As opposed to Southern European countries, the legalisation issue was discussed in Germany in view of rejected asylum seekers who cannot be deported, rather than in view of the labour market.	Junkert and Kreienbrink 2008: 45; Sinn et al 2005: 56	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Regularisation	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
