2252	Germany	residency period for naturalisation shortened	2000	New Nationality Code adopted by Parliament in May 1999 (entered into force in January 2000), replacing the old nationality code in force since 1913 - shortening the  mandatory residence period preceding naturalisation: adult foreigners may acquire it after 8 years of legal residence (instead of the 15)	SOPEMI 1999: 146; Hailbronner 2012: 7	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2253	Germany	ius soli for children born in DE to foreign parents under certain conditions	2000	New Nationality Code adopted by Parliament in May 1999 (entered into force in January 2000), replacing the old nationality code in force since 1913 - grants children of foreign parents German citizenship at birth (ius soli) if (1) at least one parent has lived legally and continuously in Germany for at least eight years prior to the birth, and if (2) at the time of the birth, that parent as been in possession of a permanent residence permit for three years prior to the birth.  > Children born of foreign parents must, between the ages of 18 and 23 years, choose which nationality they will definitively take, dual nationality not being an option.	SOPEMI 2003b: 202; Hailbronner 2012: 7	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2254	Germany	dual citizenship remains an exception	2000	New Nationality Code adopted by Parliament in May 1999 (entered into force in January 2000), replacing the old nationality code in force since 1913 - excludes dual citizenship.  > Exceptions to this are granted, for example, when the country of origin does not allow the applicant to give up their original citizenship, or when giving up their citizenship would entail undue hardship.	Focus Migration 2007: 4	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	No change		
2255	Germany	eased entry program for non-EU IT specialists	2001	Ordinance 28/7/2000 created the Green Card system (launched in August 2001) - that allowed up to 20.000 non-EU IT specialists to work and reside in Germany for up to five years, provided that they have a university degree in the related IT field (85%) or were promised an annual salary of EUR 51.000 (15%).  > The German government indicated that the green card programme will end on 31 July 2003.	SOPEMI 2003b: 202	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2256	Germany	old case arrangement for people from yugoslavia and bosnia-herzegowina	2001	2001 old case arrangement for people from Bosnia-Herzegovina and Yugoslavia - to grant people with exceptional leave to remain residence permits if they were in Germany since six years and working since at least two years.	http://www.asylforschung.de/info_duldung.htm [accessed on 18.11.2013]	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Regularisation	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	Specific nationalities	Yugoslavia, Bosnia-Herzegowina	Less restrictive		
2257	Germany	Report of the Sussmuth Commission suggest point system for entry	2001	In July 2001, the Sussmuth commission presented a report titled 'Structuring Immigration, Fostering Integration' - highlighting well-known demographic developments, such as increasing life expectancy, low birth rates, and a workforce that is shrinking due to an aging population. In light of such developments, the commission argued for initiating a controlled immigration program for foreigners with favorable characteristics for integration into both the labor market and society. They proposed the implementation of a point system as a tool for selecting 20,000 immigrants per year based on criteria of education, age, and language skills. In the event of urgent labor shortages, another 20,000 immigrants should be let into the country on a five-year basis.	MPI 2004; Focus Migration 2007: 5	N/A	N/A	Legal entry and stay	Points-based system	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
2258	Germany	unsuccessful immigration bill as result of sussmuth report	2001	A bill introduced to parliament in November 2001 by the ruling Social Democrat and Green coalition - picked up on several commission recommendations, including highly qualified migration and integration. The immigration of those who plan to establish a business was also welcomed, and there was no cap on the numbers of such entrepreneurs. However, companies could only hire temporary migrant workers outside of the categories outlined above if there were no Germans (or foreigners such as EU nationals, who are legally treated as Germans) available for the work. The legislation also provided for language classes for immigrants in the future  with failure to attend possibly translating into difficulties in extending residence permits.  > Despite vocal criticism by the opposition, the bill was passed by both chambers of parliament. It was subsequently signed by President Johannes Rau in March 2002 and was set to take effect on January 1, 2003. However, it was procedurally contested by the country's conservative opposition, which successfully filed a lawsuit in the Federal Court. In December 2002, the court blocked the immigration law. In January 2003, the government re-introduced the unchanged bill, since the court objected only to procedural failings in how it had been passed. In May 2003, the bill again passed the lower house of parliament. However, a month later it was voted down in the upper chamber, where the federal states are represented and the opposition parties have a majority.	MPI 2004	N/A	N/A	Legal entry and stay	Contextual elements	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
2259	Germany	police gets more control powers to question people in streats, anti terrorism measure	2002	Counter-Terrorism Act of 2002 - delegates the authority to carry out inspections on transit routes and at railway stations and airports to the Federal Police. They are also authorized not only to stop and question people in the course of checks, but also to examine and verify their passports.	Junkert and Kreienbrink 2008: 34	Major change	National policy	Border and land control	Surveillance technology/control powers	All	All	N/A	More restrictive		
2260	Germany	students allowed to work more than before	2003	Beginning in January 2003, foreign students in Germany may work 40 hours a week or 180 days a year without needing a work permit (previously 20 hours per week or 90 days).	SOPEMI 2003b: 202	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Work visa/permit	International students	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
