2267	Germany	EU enlargement restricted labour market access	2004	EU 2004 enlargement - Germany restricted the access to its labour market for workers from the 8 new EU MS (excluding Malta and Cyprus) > Temporary work permits will still be required for citizens of the new member states. The period of exceptional measures can be extended until end of 2010. Starting in 2011, free movement for workers from the new member states is guaranteed.	MPI 2004	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	All migrant workers	EU citizens	Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, Poland, Slovakia and Slovenia	No change		
2268	Germany	employer sanctions strenghtened	2004	2004 Act to Combat Illicit Work and Illegal Employment (Schwarzarbeitsbekämpfungsgesetz) - sanctions the people involved in irregular employment (employers, principals, employees, service providers, craftsmen and customers) with fines of up to EUR 500,000 as well as by imprisonment of up to five years.	Junkert and Kreienbrink 2008: 15	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Border and land control	Employer liabilities	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
2269	Germany	BAMF created	2005	New Immigration Act (Zuwanderungsgesetz) passed in July 2004 and entered into force on January 2005 - created the BAMF as centralised Federal authority for migration and asylum, bundling competences for asylum, migration and integration	SOPEMI 2006: 182	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Institutional capacities	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Change in restrictiveness cannot be assessed		
2270	Germany	simplification of residence permits	2005	New Immigration Act (Zuwanderungsgesetz) passed in July 2004 and entered into force on January 2005 - reduces the number of residence permits from 5 to 2, namely to a residence permit of unlimited duration (Niederlassungserlaubnis) and to one of limited duration (Aufenthaltserlaubnis), with the duration varying according to the purpose of entry (education, employment, family, protection).  > The new law is no longer structured according to the permits themselves, but rather with respect to the purpose of stay (e.g. education, employment, family reunion, humanitarian migration). Also, foreigners will only have to apply to the aliens office that has jurisdiction. The aliens office obtains approval of the work permit directly from the labour administration and issues the work permit along with the resi-dence permit in a single act (one-stop government).	SOPEMI 2006: 182; EMN 2005: 21	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Change in restrictiveness cannot be assessed		
2271	Germany	eased entry for high-skilled	2005	New Immigration Act (Zuwanderungsgesetz) passed in July 2004 and entered into force on January 2005 - allows highly qualified non-EU-workers such as scientists or top-level managers with a minimum salary of 84.000 EUR yearly to obtain a work and residence permit of unlimited duration at the outset.  > According to the Immigration Act, highly-skilled persons are scientists with special technical knowledge, scientific personnel in prominent positions or specialists and executive personnel with special professional experience who earn a high salary. However, the core of the law, the innovative point system for selecting immigrants, has been eliminated at the demand of the opposition Christian Democrats, who have the majority in the upper house. Also, companies can only hire non-EU workers if there are no Germans (or foreigners such as EU nationals, who are legally treated as Germans) available for the job.  The new law replaces the current special framework for IT specialists, which expires on 31 December 2004. Recruitment of highly skilled individuals, however, remains generally subject to a labour market test.	MPI 2004; Focus Migration 2007; SOPEMI 2005: 198-199; EMN 2005: 21	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Access to permanent residency	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2272	Germany	eased entry for entrepreneurs and investors	2005	New Immigration Act (Zuwanderungsgesetz) passed in July 2004 and entered into force on January 2005 -  welcomes those who plan to establish a business > There will be no cap on the numbers of such entrepreneurs, but they will be required to invest at least a million euros in their project and create at least 10 new jobs.	MPI 2004; Focus Migration 2007	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Investors, entrepreneurs and business people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2273	Germany	family members granted same working rights as the relative they join	2005	New Immigration Act (Zuwanderungsgesetz) passed in July 2004 and entered into force on January 2005 - grants nuclear family members arriving to join a relative in Germany the same labour market access as the relative they are joining.  > Dependents of foreigners with equal (unlimited) access to the labour market will be granted equal access as well, whereas dependents of sponsors with limited access will be granted limited access. Formerly, there was generally a waiting period of one year and a priority check after the expiry of the one-year period.	SOPEMI 2006: 182; Kreienbrink and Ruehl 2007: 25	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Work visa/permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2274	Germany	students allowed to stay one year after studies	2005	New Immigration Act (Zuwanderungsgesetz) passed in July 2004 and entered into force on January 2005 - allows foreign students to stay in Germany for a year after finishing their studies to look for a job. At present they have to leave Germany.	MPI 2004; Focus Migration 2007	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Work visa/permit	International students	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2275	Germany	no mimimum age for family reunion	2005	New Immigration Act (Zuwanderungsgesetz) passed in July 2004 and entered into force on January 2005 - no longer requires the sponsor to be at least 18 years old, i.e. to have reached the legal age of majority. Also, the Act does not give a legal minimum age for the immigrating spouse.	Kreienbrink and Ruehl 2007: 15	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2276	Germany	language requirements for family members of ethnic germans	2005	New Immigration Act (Zuwanderungsgesetz) passed in July 2004 and entered into force on January 2005 - imposed language requirements on family members of ethnic Germans.	SOPEMI 2006: 182	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	Ethnic Germans (Aussiedler)	More restrictive		
2277	Germany	refugee recognition grounds enlarged	2005	New Immigration Act (Zuwanderungsgesetz) passed in July 2004 and entered into force on January 2005 - will recognize asylum seekers who are persecuted because of their sex, as well as those under 'non-state' persecution, as refugees.	MPI 2004; Focus Migration 2007	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2278	Germany	eased deportation for grounds of national security	2005	New Immigration Act (Zuwanderungsgesetz) passed in July 2004 and entered into force on January 2005 -  facilitated the deportation of foreigners for reasons of national security > Besides allowing the deportation of foreigners on the basis of a threat prognosis supported by factual evidence, the new law will make it easier to deport religious extremists and those deemed 'preachers of hatred'	Focus Migration 2007: 5	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Exit	Expulsion	Specific categories	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
2279	Germany	mandatory integration courses for new immigrants	2005	New Immigration Act (Zuwanderungsgesetz) passed in July 2004 and entered into force on January 2005 - provided for mandatory integration courses for new immigrants from non-EU countries > These consist of a 600-hour course in German, plus a 30-hour orientation course in which participants are instructed on Germanys legal system, history and culture. Immigrants who do not participate or fail to complete the courses will face sanctions, which may ultimately lead to a denial of the prolongation of their stay in Germany.	Focus Migration 2007: 6; SOPEMI 2005: 198-199	Major change	National policy	Integration	Language, housing and cultural integration programmes	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
2280	Germany	naturalisation linked to compliance with german law and language knowledge	2005	New Immigration Act (Zuwanderungsgesetz) passed in July 2004 and entered into force on January 2005 -  adjusted the nationality law by making the right to naturalisation dependent upon a proof of sufficient knowledge of the German language.	Hailbronner 2012: 8	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
2281	Germany	hardship commissions created for case by case regularisations	2005	New Immigration Act (Zuwanderungsgesetz) passed in July 2004 and entered into force on January 2005 - created state Hardship Commissions which may request their responsible state government to grant a residence permit to foreigners whose removal is hindered for important humanitarian or personal reasons.  > According to the hardship regulation provided by law people in a very tough situation may be granted a residence permit. It is irrelevant whether the person is a rejected asylum seekers or an irregular migrant. The decision whether or whether not a single person or a family is acknowledged as a case of hardship lies in the hands of the Ministery of the Interior of each German state. The procedure varies from state to state, and not in all of them exists such a thing as a Committee on Hardship Cases.  This clause was initially designed as a sunset clause to become invalid on 31 December 2009.	EMN 2008: 19	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Regularisation	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2282	Germany	Readmission agreement with South Korea	2005	South Korea has concluded a readmission agreement with the Germany, it was signed in 2004 and entered into force in 2005	http://www.bmi.bund.de/SharedDocs/Downloads/DE/Themen/MigrationIntegration/AsylZuwanderung/RueckkehrFluechtlinge.pdf?__blob=publicationFile [accessed on 18.11.2013]	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Exit	Readmission agreements	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	Those transiting through or originating from South Korea	More restrictive		
2283	Germany	Readmission agreement with France	2005	France has concluded a readmission agreement with the Germany, it was signed in 2003 and entered into force in 2005	http://www.bmi.bund.de/SharedDocs/Downloads/DE/Themen/MigrationIntegration/AsylZuwanderung/RueckkehrFluechtlinge.pdf?__blob=publicationFile [accessed on 18.11.2013]	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Exit	Readmission agreements	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	Those transiting through or originating from France	More restrictive		
2284	Germany	Readmission agreement with Bulgaria	2006	Bulgaria has concluded a readmission agreement with the Germany, it was signed and entered into force in 2006.	http://www.bmi.bund.de/SharedDocs/Downloads/DE/Themen/MigrationIntegration/AsylZuwanderung/RueckkehrFluechtlinge.pdf?__blob=publicationFile [accessed on 18.11.2013]	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Exit	Readmission agreements	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	Those transiting through or originating from Bulgaria.	More restrictive		
2285	Germany	Readmission agreement with Algeria	2006	Algeria has concluded a readmission agreement with the Germany, it was signed in 1997 and entered into force in 2006 (it was however practically used since 1999).	http://www.bmi.bund.de/SharedDocs/Downloads/DE/Themen/MigrationIntegration/AsylZuwanderung/RueckkehrFluechtlinge.pdf?__blob=publicationFile [accessed on 18.11.2013]	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Exit	Readmission agreements	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	Those transiting through or originating from Algeria	More restrictive		
2286	Germany	integration summit to discuss integration policy	2006	First ever integration summit took place in July 2006 at the invitation of the German Chancellor, Angela Merkel and under the direction of the Integration Commissioner of the German Federal Government, Maria Böhmer.  > The summit brought together state and government officials, town councillors, employers and trade union representatives, welfare organisations, religious communities, the media, charitable foundations, scientists and migrant organisations. Participants in the integration summit are meeting until summer 2007 in different thematically grouped working parties in order to draft a national plan for integration.	Focus Migration 2007: 6	N/A	N/A	Integration	Contextual elements	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
2287	Germany	First ever Conference on Islam	2006	The German 'Conference on Islam' was initiated by the Federal Minister of the Interior, Wolfgang Schäuble (CDU) > The first meeting, between state and government officials and representatives of the Muslim community plus other individuals who were not members of any Muslim organisation, took place in September 2006. In future years, the Conference on Islam is to establish measures to clarify the relationship between the state and Islam and to improve the integration of Muslims.	Focus Migration 2007: 6	N/A	N/A	Integration	Contextual elements	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
2288	Germany	regularisation through right to continued stay arrangement	2006	Arrangement for the Right to Continued Stay (Bleiberechtsregelung) was passed on 17 November 2006 - offering foreigners with an exceptional leave to remain (Geduldete) a residence permit if they have lived in Germany for at least six (with children) or eight (without children) years and if they can prove employment until 2009. > In addition, she/he must not rely on benefits in order to live and there should be no anticipation that she/he will do so in the future. Furthermore, families must have sufficient living space and, by 30 September 2007, all potential recipients of a residence permit must have given proof that they have sufficient command of the German language, here adjudged to be level A2 of the Common European Framework of References for Languages.	Junkert and Kreienbrink 2008: 45	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Regularisation	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2289	Germany	2007 enlargement restricted access to DE labour market	2007	2007 enlargement - Germany continues to require work permits from workers of Bulgaria and Romania	http://ec.europa.eu/social/main.jsp?catId=508&langId=en [accessed on 18.11.2013]	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	All migrant workers	EU citizens	Romania, Bulgaria	No change		
2290	Germany	quicker access to residence permit for long term residents of third countries	2007	2007 amendment of the Immigration act - introducing a new residence permit for third-country nationals who have been residing in Germany for five years. > This is a reaction to the EU directive concerning the status of third-country nationals who are long-term residents. This directive grants third country nationals who have lived in a member state for at least five years the right to permanent residence in EU member states and entitles them to take up an occupation or to study within the EU.	SOPEMI 2008: 244; Focus Migration 2007: 7; http://www.bmi.bund.de/SharedDocs/Downloads/DE/Gesetzestexte/Richtlinienumsetzungsgesetz.pdf?__blob=publicationFile	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to permanent residency	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2291	Germany	stricter family reunification criteria	2007	2007 amendment of the immigration act - tightened the rules on entry of spouses from most third countries: These can now generally only enter Germany if they are at least 18 years old (16 years old previously) and have to prove basic knowledge of German.  > Citizens of visa-free countries are exempted from this rule (i.e. Japan, Australia, US, South Korea etc.)	SOPEMI 2008: 244; Kreienbrink and Rühl 2007	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	Specific nationalities	Visa-required countries	More restrictive		
2292	Germany	family members of high skilled exempt from stricter criteria	2007	2007 amendment of the immigration act - exempted spouses of highly-qualified persons, researchers, those starting up in business from the minimum age and from the language requirement.	EMN 2007: 16	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members of high-skilled workers, investors or students	All foreign nationalities	N/A	No change		
2293	Germany	eased entry for entrepreneurs and investors	2007	2007 amendment of the immigration act - facilitated entry for foreign entrepreneurs: They have to invest only 0.5 Million and create five new jobs (previously 1 million and 10 jobs)	SOPEMI 2008: 244	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Investors, entrepreneurs and business people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2294	Germany	regularisation through old cases arrangement	2007	2007 amendment of the immigration act - introduces a legal arrangement for old cases (gesetzliche Altfallregelung) which grants people with exceptional leave to remain (Geduldete) and who have lived in Germany legally for six (with children) or eight (without children) years a stay permit (Aufenthaltsrecht)  > Additional conditions for the stay permit are a decent living, basic german knowledge, kids going regularly to school, no criminal record. The stay permit is only granted on trial basis and can be transformed into a regular residence permit if they prove to earn their own living until 31.12.2009. The main difference with the 2006 arrangement is that also those who are not yet self sustaining can apply but are expected to become so.	SOPEMI 2008: 244; http://www.bpb.de/gesellschaft/migration/dossier-migration/56350/zuwanderungsgesetz-2007 [accessed on 11.07.2013]	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Regularisation	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2295	Germany	National integration plan	2007	Federal, regional and municipal governments and non-governmental civil actors agreed on a National Integration Plan in July 2007 - containing 400 measures and commitments, including expansion and improvement of integration courses, integration of migrants into the labour market, stimulation of ethnic economies, language support and stronger early intervention policies for children of immigrants.	SOPEMI 2009(online)	N/A	N/A	Integration	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
2296	Germany	Hardship commissions continued without time limit	2008	2008 amendment to the Immigration Act -  abolished the time limit for the Hardship Commissions which may request their responsible state government to grant a residence permit to foreigners whose removal is hindered for important humanitarian or personal reasons.  > The Harship Commissions have since become a fixed feature in the German immigration system.	EMN 2008: 19	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Regularisation	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2297	Germany	introduction of language and citizenship test	2008	2008 Amendment of the 2000 nationality act -  requires sufficient knowledge of the German language by providing a certificate in German at level B of the Common European Reference Framework for Languages. Furthermore, integration tests have been introduced as requirements for a right to naturalisation. > As a rule, an applicant for naturalisation may prove knowledge of basic facts of the political and social system and the living conditions in Germany. There are exceptions for older people and juveniles, for sick persons and disabled persons.	Hailbronner 2012: 10, 11	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
2298	Germany	Readmission agreement with Georgia	2008	Georgia has concluded a readmission agreement with the Germany, it was signed in 2007 and entered into force in 2008.	http://www.bmi.bund.de/SharedDocs/Downloads/DE/Themen/MigrationIntegration/AsylZuwanderung/RueckkehrFluechtlinge.pdf?__blob=publicationFile [accessed on 18.11.2013]	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Exit	Readmission agreements	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	Those transiting through or originating from Georgia	More restrictive		
2299	Germany	Readmission agreement with Armenia	2008	Armenia has concluded a readmission agreement with the Germany, it was signed in 2006 and entered into force in 2008.	http://www.bmi.bund.de/SharedDocs/Downloads/DE/Themen/MigrationIntegration/AsylZuwanderung/RueckkehrFluechtlinge.pdf?__blob=publicationFile [accessed on 18.11.2013]	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Exit	Readmission agreements	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	Those transiting through or originating from Armenia	More restrictive		
2300	Germany	Readmission agreement with Syria	2009	Syria  has concluded a readmission agreement with the Germany, it was signed in 2008 and entered into force in 2009.	http://www.bmi.bund.de/SharedDocs/Downloads/DE/Themen/MigrationIntegration/AsylZuwanderung/RueckkehrFluechtlinge.pdf?__blob=publicationFile [accessed on 18.11.2013]	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Exit	Readmission agreements	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	Those transiting through or originating from Syria	More restrictive		
2301	Germany	eased entry for entrepreneurs and investors	2009	July 2008 action program Contribution towards securing the skilled labour basis in Germany by labour immigration entered into effect on 1 January 2009 - lowered the minimum sum of investment for foreigners setting up their own business from  500,000 to  250,000	Parusel and Schneider 2010	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Investors, entrepreneurs and business people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2302	Germany	income for permanent residence lowered	2009	July 2008 action program Contribution towards securing the skilled labour basis in Germany by labour immigration entered into effect on 1 January 2009 - lowers the income threshold for granting unlimited residence to highly skilled workers from EUR 86 400 to 64 800.	SOPEMI 2009; Parusel and Schneider 2010	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Access to permanent residency	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2303	Germany	eased access to labour market for for graduates of german educational institutions	2009	July 2008 action program Contribution towards securing the skilled labour basis in Germany by labour immigration entered into effect on 1 January 2009 -  removed prior labour market tests for international students with a tertiary degree from a German educational institution.  > They must however have an employment offer commensurate with their qualification level.	SOPEMI 2009	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	International students	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2304	Germany	eased access to labour market for university graduates from new EU MS	2009	July 2008 action program Contribution towards securing the skilled labour basis in Germany by labour immigration entered into effect on 1 January 2009 -  removed prior labour market tests for all migrants from the new EU member countries holding a tertiary degree, as well as their family members	SOPEMI 2010: 206; http://ec.europa.eu/social/main.jsp?catId=508&langId=en [accessed on 18.11.2013]	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	EU citizens	Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, Poland, Slovakia, Slovenia, Romania and Bulgaria	Less restrictive		
2305	Germany	eased access to labour market for specific skills categories	2009	July 2008 action program Contribution towards securing the skilled labour basis in Germany by labour immigration entered into effect on 1 January 2009 - removed prioir labour market tests for workers in specific skill categories and their spouses.	SOPEMI 2009	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2306	Germany	longer employment period for low skilled	2009	July 2008 action program Contribution towards securing the skilled labour basis in Germany by labour immigration entered into effect on 1 January 2009 - extended te maximum period for which lowly qualified or unqualified seasonal workers may be employed from four to six months per year	EMN 2008: 20	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Low-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2307	Germany	ad hoc resettlement programme for iraqis	2009	Germany committed  to  resettle  2. 500 Iraqis  (2 000  from  Syria  and  500 from  Jordan)  in  2009. > Diverging slightly from the definition of resettlement, this ad-hoc programme gave refugees a temporary residence permit  with  the  option  of  renewal  after  three  years  versus  a  permanent  residency permit that is often given to refugees resettled in other countries.	http://www.resettlement.eu//country/germany [accessed on 30.09.2013]	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Resettlement programmes	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	Specific nationalities	Iraq	Less restrictive		
2308	Germany	doctors do not need to pass on data on irregular migrants anymore	2009	Administrative Regulation on the Residence Act  entered into force on 31 October 2009 - lifts the requirement of doctors and pharmacists to pass on the data on irregular migrants they treat > public bodies are required to notify the foreigners authorities if they become aware of a foreigners illegal residence in Germany. However, the notification obligation is limited insofar as personal data given to the public body by a doctor or pharmacist, for example, may not be passed on to the foreigners authority due to privacy rules. The law spells out that doctor-patient confidentiality also extends to patient secrets.  Even if doctors in-form the social security offices of the personal data of illegal migrants during the invoicing procedure, the social security offices may no longer pass on these data.	EMN 2009: 37	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to social benefits and socio-economic rights	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2309	Germany	Readmission agreement with Kosovo	2010	Kosovo has concluded a readmission agreement with the Germany, it was signed and entered into force in 2012.	http://www.bmi.bund.de/SharedDocs/Downloads/DE/Themen/MigrationIntegration/AsylZuwanderung/RueckkehrFluechtlinge.pdf?__blob=publicationFile [accessed on 18.11.2013]	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Exit	Readmission agreements	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	Those transiting through or originating from Kosovo	More restrictive		
2310	Germany	more legal security for victims of forced marriage	2011	The Combatting Forced Marriage Act took effect on 1 July 2011 - grants victims of forced marriage and abduction to another country a right of return of at most 10 years after leaving Germany in order to improve protection of these individuals and avoid potential residential consequences of abduction.  > Prior to the revision of this section, a residence permit became void following an absence from Germany of at least six months. This means victims of forced marriage abducted to another country risk forfeiting their right of residence.	EMN 2011: 32	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Integration	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2311	Germany	longer waiting period for spouse before independent right of residence	2011	The Combatting Forced Marriage Act took effect on 1 July 2011 - extended the term before receiving an independent right of residence: spouses emigrating after July 2011 must now wait three years instead of two before receiving a right of residence independent of the marriage > This is justified in that the independent right of residence designed to protect victims could be an incentive for marriages of convenience.	EMN 2011: 33	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Integration	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
2312	Germany	labour market restrictions raised for EU8 entered in 2004	2011	EU 2004 enlargement - On May 1, 2011 the transitional restrictions for the access to the German labour market for EU8 will terminate. From then on, nationals from these countries will not need a work permit anymore.	SOPEMI 2011: 282	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Free mobility rights/agreements	All migrant workers	EU citizens	Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, Poland, Slovakia and Slovenia	Less restrictive		
2313	Germany	New strategy for labour migration	2011	The government adopted, in June 2011, the Concept for Securing the Skilled Labour Base - a five-pronged strategy aimed at sustaining the supply of skilled workers in Germany in the medium and long term, in light of the decline in the working-age population.  > The Concept for Securing the Skilled Labour Base also aims to attract skilled workers from abroad through managed migration in response to labour market needs	SOPEMI 2012: 323	N/A	N/A	Legal entry and stay	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
2314	Germany	creation of a positive shortage list	2011	Establishment of a positive list of shortage professions granting exemption from the labour market test - The list, reviewed by the Federal Employment Agency every six months on the basis of a job monitoring system, initially included doctors as well as mechanical, automotive and electrical engineers, with several other occupations added in 2012.	SOPEMI 2012: 323	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2315	Germany	regularisation for youths with long-term exceptional leave to remain	2011	In 2011, a special arrangement was created - granting residence documents to youths with long-term exceptional leave to remain, provided they meet certain requirements (in particular successful completion of school and training qualifications) and offer the promise of integrating into the living conditions in Germany based on their integration efforts thus far.  > In addition, also the parents of these youths should receive a right of residence when they have made sufficient efforts at integration and can largely provide for the family on their own.  The person with exceptional leave to remain must have entered Germany before the age of 14, must have resided in the Federal Territory legally, with exceptional leave or with a residence title for specific purposes for six years uninterrupted and has either attended school for six years or has obtained a recognised school leaving certificate or training qualification. Criteria for successful school attendance are regular attendance and placement in the next grade.	EMN 2011: 44	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Regularisation	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2316	Germany	Readmission agreement with Croatia	2012	Croatia has concluded a readmission agreement with the Germany, it was signed and entered into force in 2012.	http://www.bmi.bund.de/SharedDocs/Downloads/DE/Themen/MigrationIntegration/AsylZuwanderung/RueckkehrFluechtlinge.pdf?__blob=publicationFile [accessed on 18.11.2013]	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Exit	Readmission agreements	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	Those transiting through or originating from Croatia	More restrictive		
2317	Germany	resettlement programme for north africans	2012	In 2011, Germany decided to start a permanent resettlement programme, including the admission of 300 refugees over the next three years from North Africa. > Background: For many years, Germany has practiced ad-hoc resettlement, without managing an official annual quota for resettlement. It is still unknown how the German resettlement programme will develop after 2014, and specifically if a continuing or larger annual quota will be introduced.	http://www.resettlement.eu//country/germany [accessed on 30.09.2013]	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Resettlement programmes	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	Specific nationalities	North Africa	Less restrictive		
2318	Germany	easier procedure for recognition of foreign qualifications	2012	Law to improve the assessment and recognition of foreign professional qualifications came into force in April 2012 - to improve the labour market integration of persons with foreign professional qualifications.  > The law entitles holders of a foreign qualification in one of 350 specified occupations (mostly requiring vocational qualifications) to the right, within three months from application, to have their credentials assessed in terms of equivalence with German degrees. The assessment procedure has been standardised and foreign qualifications are evaluated exclusively in terms of essential differences with the German equivalent, while the applicants nationality is no longer relevant. The new recognition act covers immigrants residing in Germany and potential immigrants abroad who may seek recognition before arrival. An estimated 285 000 current residents hold foreign qualifications eligible for evaluation.	SOPEMI 2012: 323	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2319	Germany	EU Blue card introduced with lower salary threshold	2012	In August 2012, the EU Blue Card was introduced - granting a renewable permit to tertiary-educated workers earning at least EUR 46 400 gross per year (or above 36 200 for certain shortage occupations) > The previous salary based permanent permit for the high skilled was eliminated.	SOPEMI 2013: 254	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2320	Germany	Access to labour market for family members of EU Blue card holders	2012	In August 2012, the EU Blue Card was introduced - extending labour market access to their family members, with no language requirements.	SOPEMI 2013: 254	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Work visa/permit	Family members of high-skilled workers, investors or students	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2321	Germany	six months job search visa	2012	In August 2012, the EU Blue Card was introduced - including a job-search visa for up to six months for tertiary-educated job-seekers.	SOPEMI 2013: 254	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2322	Germany	work permit for foreigners with german vocational degree	2012	A measure opened up employment for foreigners holding a German vocational degree - Foreigners who terminated a German vocational degree have one year to find a Job.	SOPEMI 2013: 254	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Integration	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2323	Germany	job serach visa for graduates extended	2012	The post-graduation job-search period for German university graduates was extended from 12 to 18 months.	SOPEMI 2013: 254	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Integration	Work visa/permit	International students	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2324	Germany	default approval of labour market test if no answer in 2 weeks	2012	The labour market test was accelerated by expanding the grounds for exemption and granting default approval if the Employment Agency fails to respond within two weeks.	SOPEMI 2013: 254	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2325	Germany	National Action Plan for Integration	2012	The National Action Plan for Integration, with concrete, binding and verifiable objectives, was presented in January 2012 on the basis of the 2007 National Integration Plan.	SOPEMI 2013: 254	N/A	N/A	Integration	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
