2332	Germany	ad hoc resettlement programme for syrians	2013	In March 2013, Germany agreed to grant humanitarian admission to 5,000 Syrian refugees. - The programme grants those arriving, a temporary residence status, with the expectation that refugees will return to Syria when the conflict there has been resolved. In December 2013, the quota of Syrian refuges has been increased from 5,000 to 10,000.	http://www.resettlement.eu//country/germany [accessed on 30.09.2013]; EMN 2013: 2	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Resettlement programmes	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	Specific nationalities	Syria	Less restrictive		
2333	Germany	more legal protection against transfers of asylum seekers	2013	National regulations on temporary legal protection against transfer decisions entered into force on 6th September 2013 - The regulations aim to ensure a smooth application of the new Dublin Regulation and to improve legal protection in the current procedure.	EMN 2013: 2	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Access to justice and political rights	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2334	Germany	minors can now reunite with one of their parents	2013	On 6th September 2013 a new law concerning family reunification including minors entered into force - Following the introduction of the new law, minors (under 18) can now be granted the right to family reunification with one of their parents, even when the minors custody is shared by the parents and when one of parents resides in the country of origin. In such cases, the law provides that family reunification would be granted after the remaining parents agreement on the permanent move of the minor to Germany, or when such a decision has been made by a competent public authority (for example a court).	EMN 2013: 2	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2335	Germany	fingerprint verifications at borders becomes the norm	2013	Since 2013, fingerprint verifications have been extended to all external border check points - German law enforcement and security agencies have had access to the Visa Information System (VIS) since 2 September 2013, following the VIS Access Decision. During 2013, Germany also reported that it will extend the collection of biometrical data in line with the progressive roll-out of the VIS.	EMN 2013: 2	Major change	National policy	Border and land control	Surveillance technology/control powers	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
