2390	Germany	data sharing of irregular migrants and asylum seekers between German authorities made possible	2016	Data Sharing Improvement Act of February 2016 - In February 2016, the essential parts of this act came into force. It allows for certain personal data of asylum seekers, persons who irregularly crossed the border into Germany and persons staying in Germany without the requisite residence title, to be recorded in a central key data system, which has been made available to all authorities dealing with these groups in order to fulfil their tasks. Federal, state and local authorities have been able to access the centralised data system since May 2016. After their registration, asylum seekers will be given a proof of their arrival in form of an official paper with integrated forgery-proof elements. At the offices and arrival centres, fingerprints can be checked almost in real time so that identifying applicants is only a matter of seconds. Personal data and fingerprints from all asylum procedure files are automatically transmitted to the federal security authorities for daily checks against their databases.	EMN 2016: 1	Major change	National policy	Border and land control	Surveillance technology/control powers	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
2391	Germany	introduction of new workflow for asylum procedures, speeding up the process	2016	Adaptations in BAMF procedures of 2016 - Following the significant increase in the number of asylum applications between 2015 and 2016, procedures in connection with the asylum procedure at the Federal Office for Migration and Refugees (BAMF) were adapted. The aim was to optimise and accelerate the processing of applications and to expand BAMFs capacities. Introducing a new workflow for the asylum procedure: this significantly reduces the applicants waiting times and allows the authorities involved better control and dovetailing of admission, asylum procedure, integration and, if applicable, return.	EMN 2016: 1	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Institutional capacities	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Change in restrictiveness cannot be assessed		
2392	Germany	expulsions enforced, with the only exception in case of severe illness	2016	Asylum Package II (Asylverfahrensbeschleunigungsgesetz)  of March 2016 - deportations, which often did not take place due to the poor health status of rejected applicants, can now be enforced unless the migrant is severely ill.	SOPEMI 2016: 260	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Exit	Expulsion	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
2393	Germany	family reunification for humanitarian migrants with subsidiary protected status only possible after two years	2016	Asylum Package II (Asylverfahrensbeschleunigungsgesetz)  of March 2016 - family reunification for humanitarian migrants with subsidiary protection status, including unaccompanied minors, is now only possible after two years. Due to the influx of people requesting international protection and the numbers of family members requesting family reunification,  the right for family reunification was withdrawn again  for subsidiary protected sponsors (introduced in 2015).	SOPEMI 2016: 260; EMN 2016: 2	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members of irregular migrants or refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
2394	Germany	decisions on asylum applications from safe countries can be made by an accelarated procedure	2016	Asylum Package II (Asylverfahrensbeschleunigungsgesetz)  of March 2016 - foresees the development of specialised reception centres where decisions on asylum for applicants from safe countries of origin can be made within three weeks. In conformity with the recast Asylum Procedures Directive (Directive 2013/32/EU), which provides for fast-track asylum procedures for persons from safe countries of origin. Decisions are issued within one week. Within another week of that decision, applicants can appeal for immediate legal protection against a negative decision. The administrative court should then rule on the appeal within a further week. Applicants who appeal first-instance decisions or those who do not co-operate  for instance by submitting false documentation or refusing to have their fingerprints taken  can also be subjected to this accelerated procedure.	SOPEMI 2016: 260; EMN 2016: 1	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	Specific nationalities	Those transiting through or originating from a safe country	More restrictive		
2395	Germany	resettlement places offered for Syrians from Italy, Greece and Turkey	2016	Council Decision establishing provisional measures in the area of international protection for the benefit of Italy and Greece (12098/15) and Council Decision (2016/1754) - On the basis of EU Council Decisions of 2015 and 2016, Germany offered 1,600 resettlement places for Syrian refugees from Turkey. Regarding relocation activities, in 2016, 444 persons from Italy and 634 persons from Greece were relocated to Germany under the Council Decisions on relocation of September 2015.	EMN 2016: 1	Fine-tuning change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Resettlement programmes	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	Specific nationalities	Syrians from Italy, Greece and Turkey	Less restrictive		
