2416	Germany	Act to Implement the EU Residence Directives on Labour Migration transposed the EU Seasonal Workers Directive (2014/36/EU)	2017	The Act to Implement the EU Residence Directives on Labour Migration transposed the EU Seasonal Workers Directive (2014/36/EU)  The Directive deals with the entry and employment of thirdcountry nationals for up to six months (Bundesrat 2017a: 1). This requires approval by the Federal Labour Office, which will also set the total number of approvals depending on the labourmarket situation (Bundesrat 2017a: 61). The preconditions and the procedure for the issuance of the necessary work permit will be defined by a statutory instrument to be is sued by the Federal Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs	Bundesrat 2017a: 1	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
2417	Germany	Act to Implement the EU Residence Directives on Labour Migration transposed the EU Directive on IntraCorporate Transfers (ICT Directive)	2017	The Act to Implement the EU Residence Directives on Labour Migration transposed the EU Directive on IntraCorporate Transfers (ICT Directive) - it introduces the socalled ICT card, a new residence title issued for intracorporate transfers of managers, experts and trainees which go beyond a period of more than 90 days. In addition, the new provisions permit the residence of thirdcountry nationals who already stayed in a different EU Member State in the framework of an intracorporate transfer. They can be issued with a mobile ICT card for a stay of more than 90 days. Under the ICT Directive persons holding a residence title issued for an intracorporate transfer and who went through the newly regulated notification procedure for short term mobility from another EU Member State may stay and work for up to 90 days in Germany without holding a German residence title.	EMN?	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
