2456	Germany	acceptance of social norms required for naturalization	2019	New law amending the Nationality Act of 9 August 2019 - introduced verification of identity and nationality of applicants for naturalisation. Such applicants must demonstrate acceptance of social norms in Germany.	EMN 2019: 2	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
2457	Germany	new toleration status for those required to leave the country but whose identity remains unclear	2019	The Act on Orderly Returns of 20 August 2019 -  a new status for 'toleration for people with unverified identity' has been introduced for those who do not conform with provisions to reliably identify persons required to leave the country, i.e. who actively hide their identity or do not pursue the necessary steps to acquire a passport. Such persons must take all reasonable action to acquire a passport or substitute document. Those affected must apply to the authorities of their country of origin for travel documents, appear there in person, provide photographs and fingerprints, and participate in any necessary hearings in their country of origin, in particular to verify their identity. The law stipulates that anyone failing to cooperate in acquiring the necessary documents will have 'for persons with unverified identity' noted in their temporary suspension of removal.	EMN 2019: 3; SOPEMI 2020: 194; https://www.asyl.net/view/detail/News/weitere-gesetze-aus-dem-migrationspaket-im-bundesgesetzblatt-veroeffentlicht/ [accessed on 21.02.2021]	Mid-level change	National policy	Exit	Identification documents	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
2458	Germany	asylum seekers must stay for a max of 18 months in reception centres	2019	The Act on Orderly Returns of 20 August 2019 -  Asylum seekers will be obliged to live in reception centres for the duration of the procedure, up to 18 months (previously 6 months). The federal states have the option to prolong this obligation of stay to 24 months. Minors and their caretakers are the exception, as they can only be obligated to stay for a period of 6 months	SOPEMI 2019: 234; https://www.asyl.net/view/detail/News/weitere-gesetze-aus-dem-migrationspaket-im-bundesgesetzblatt-veroeffentlicht/ [accessed on 21.02.2021]	Major change	National policy	Border and land control	Surveillance technology/control powers	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
