2504	Greece	Regularisation of irregular workers	1997	Presidential Decrees 358/1997 and 359/1997 - introduced the first regularisation programme for foreigners who at least spent one year in the country.  > The process is completed in 2 steps: a registration phase followed by the issuance of a 'green card'.  During the initial registration phase, the non documented workers must submit an application to their local Employment and Manpower Organisations (OAED). This involves supplying information regarding their occupation, level of eduation, skills, employment experience, age, family status, nationality and country of origin. Upon completion of these formalities the applicant will receive a Temporary Residence Permit (white card) which will give her/him the right to work on the same basis as native workers. The applicant must have supplied by the end of May 1998 a number of other docments. These include a passport or other  kind of travel document, a certificate testifying to the non possession of a criminal record and documents detailing the previous duration of stay in Greece.  During the second phase which will last until the end of July 1998 the applicants must demonstrate that they have earned an income equivalent to 40 working days of a non specialised labour. An OAED committee, after a consideration of the applicant's record, the needs of the labour market and the needs of the Greek economy, may grant the Residence Card of Limited Duration. The card will be valid initially for 1 to 3 years. Subsequent renewals for two year periods will be possible. Special provisions exist for the granting of 5 year permits.	SOPEMI 2003b: 204	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Regularisation	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2505	Greece	family reunification allowed for long term residents	1998	Presidential Decree - allowing workers with more than 7 years residency or with definite permit to stay to bring family members > Permission for family reunion is however subject to four conditions: before the arrival of the migrant to Greece they were cohabitants and dependants; that all the incoming family members possess a certificate attesting their good health; that the adults do not have a criminal record; and, finally, that the sponsoring migrant can provide proof of his/her financial ability to support the dependants	SOPEMI 1999: 150	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
2506	Greece	ethnic reasons for citizenship withdrawal abolished	1998	June 1998 Act - abolished the 1955 Act which gave power to the Minister to withdraw Greek citizenship from Greek citizens of non Greek ethnic background who had left Greece with no intention to return or who lacked 'Greek consciousness'.  > The Muslim minority is the principal beneficiary of this measure.	SOPEMI 2001a: 195	Mid-level change	National policy	Exit	Access to citizenship	Diaspora	Citizens	non-Greek ethnic background	Less restrictive		
2507	Greece	Border Guard Force created	1998	Law 2622/98 established the Border Guard Force (Synoriofylaki) - to identify, arrest and send back irregular migrants.  > They operate in prefectures that are near the borders but also in prefectures that receive a large number of illegal immigrants.	IDEA 2009: 9	Major change	National policy	Border and land control	Institutional capacities	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
2508	Greece	special IDs for Greek Albanians to grant access to labour market	1998	In April 1998, Special Identity Cards are issued to ethnic Greeks from Albania - granting the right to accommodation and guaranteeing equal treatment in the labour market.  > The cards, valid for three years and renewable, are also given to spouses, children and grandchildren provided that they can furnish formal documents attesting to their relationship	SOPEMI 1999: 150	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Diaspora	Specific nationalities	Ethnic Greeks from Albania	Less restrictive		
