2521	Greece	quota for work permits introduced	2001	Act 2910/2001 on the entry, residence and naturalisation of immigrants in Greece (entered into force on 2 June 2001; amended by Act 3013/2002) - introduces yearly quotas for work permits > Under the terms of the Act, immigration into Greece is now linked to the labour market. The Greek Employment and Labour Organisation (OAED) is responsible for preparing a yearly reports evaluating the needs of the labour market and the number of job vacancies by occupation and region in order to set a quota for work permits. Only if the alien has obtained a permit for studies, work, or another occupation, he can receive an entry permit (visa) and then request a residence permit. Aliens are, therefore, in principle not permitted to enter the country and then look for a job.	SOPEMI 2003b: 205; Skordas 2002: 24	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Quota/target	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
2522	Greece	better access to social services for migrants - first real integration measure for immigrants	2001	Act 2910/2001 on the entry, residence and naturalisation of immigrants in Greece (entered into force on 2 June 2001; amended by Act 3013/2002) - guarantees equal access to the courts, social services and health care to legal migrants, as well as access to education for undocumented children. > Since 2001, immigrants who work and pay taxes in Greece have the same rights as Greek workers. For example, they can benefit from the housing program of the Organisation of Labour Housing (OEK) as long as they fulfill certain requirements that also apply to Greek workers. This housing program is supervised by the Ministry of Employment and Social Protection and it gives immigrants the opportunity to either receive a monthly rent subsidy or reside in public (labour) housing.	SOPEMI 2003b: 205; Zigoura 2007: 24; http://www.academia.edu/2579778/IMMIGRATION_TO_GREECE_AN_OVERVIEW_OF_IMMIGRATION_POLICIES_LEGISLATION_AND_SPORADIC_ATTEMPTS_AT_SOCIAL_INCLUSION_OF_IMMIGRANTS [accessed on 16.07.2013]	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to social benefits and socio-economic rights	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
