2728	Greece	LAW 4636  International Protection Act	2019	Law 4636/2019 in force since January 2020  Article 53 introduced a six-month time limit before access to the labour market is granted to applicants and it repealed the relevant provisions of Law 4540/2018 (transposition of the Reception Conditions Directive).  As a result, under the newly established legal framework, the access of asylum seekers to employment is restricted and their possibility to be self-sufficient and independent from the countrys strained reception system is seriously hampered. As for beneficiaries of international protection (refugees and subsidiary protection beneficiaries), they have access to wage employment or self-employment on the same terms and conditions that apply for Greek citizens, provided they hold a valid residence permit (art69 of Law 4375/2016). The same status remained under the newly adopted Law 4636/2019 (art27).   p.17	https://www.ecoi.net/en/file/local/2032753/WP5_Greece_Integration.pdf	Mid-level change	National policy	legal entry and stay	Access to social benefits and socio-economic rights	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
