2801	Hungary	free mobility for workers from countries which grant free mobility to Hungarian workers (reciprocity)	2004	Hungary implemented a differential treatment regarding access to the Hungarian market for EU citizens depending on their degree of openness to Hungarian citizens - i) workers from countries that apply no or a very weak transitory regime (the United Kingdom, Ireland, Sweden, Malta, Cyprus) are treated just like Hungarian nationals ii) workers from fellow new members of the EU need no work permit but must register with the authorities	SOPEMI 2006: 186; SOPEMI 2008: 248	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Free mobility rights/agreements	All migrant workers	EU citizens	UK, Ireland, Sweden, Malta, Cyprus, Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania,  Slovakia and Slovenia	Less restrictive		
2802	Hungary	work permit required from workers from countries where Hungarian workers need work permit (reciprocity)	2004	Hungary implemented a differential treatment regarding access to the Hungarian market for EU citizens depending on their degree of openness to Hungarian citizens - iii) Citizens from Denmark and Norway need a work permit but are not subject to an assessment of the labour market situation and iv) Citizens of all other EEAmember states do not benefit from any advantage relative to over any other foreigner wishing to work in Hungary. > Hungary is the only country among those who became EU members in 2004 which maintains the application of the reciprocity principle until 2009.	SOPEMI 2006: 186; SOPEMI 2008: 248	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	All migrant workers	EU citizens	France, Germany, Spain, Italy, Austria, Portugal, Netherlands, Belgium, Luxembourg, Denmark, Norway, Switzerland, Finland, Greece	No change		
