2810	Hungary	national visa for ethnic hungarians introduced	2006	The government introduced measures to simplify the stay in Hungary for Hungarian minorities abroad - creating a new visa type, the so-called national visa, authorising multiple entries and stays in Hungary for up to five years without the need to obtain any further authorisation. > This visa may be issued for five years to a foreign applicant who is capable of sustaining himself or herself, and wishes to use his or her stay in Hungary for practicing the Hungarian language and cultural activities. Under this visa, employment or study in Hungary is not allowed. The visa policy intends to secure the possibility for individuals belonging to the kin-minority to visit and enter Hungary freely in order to compensate for EU law and security requirements.	SOPEMI 2007: 252; Kovacs and Toth 2013: 13	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Diaspora	All foreign nationalities	Ethnic Hungarians	Less restrictive		
2811	Hungary	HU joins Schengen area	2007	Hungary joined the Schengen area in December 2007 - As a result, checks at internal land (and air borders by March 2008) have been eliminated with other European Union countries.	https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Enlargement_of_the_European_Union [accessed on 21.01.2014]	Major change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Border and land control	Free mobility rights/agreements	All	EU citizens	EU Member States at that time	Less restrictive		
2812	Hungary	consolidation of freedom of movement of EU citizens	2007	Act I on the Admission and Residence of Persons with the Right of Free Movement and Residence entered into force on July 1st 2007 - regulates the entry and residence of persons enjoying the right to free movement and the entry and residence of their family members It separates the legal status of EU citizens and their family members from the status of third country nationals, which was unclear in 2004-2007 despite of accession to the EU.	EMN 2008: 4, 7; Hars 2009: 51	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	All migrants	EU citizens	N/A	No change		
2813	Hungary	family reunification for recognized refugees extended	2007	Act II on the entry and stay of third country nationals entered into force on July 1st 2007 -  extended the scope of family members of a refugee who may be granted a long-term visa or a residence permit on the grounds of family reunification by: the parents of the refugee who are dependent on him/her and the siblings of the refugee, if they are unable to provide for themselves due to health reasons. > The preferential term concerning the time frame within which the family member applying for family reunification does not have to prove the requirements of accommodation, livelihood and health insurance was extended from three months to six months, therefore this preferential term became even more favourable for the family member of a refugee.	EMN 2008: 14; Hars 2009: 51	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members of irregular migrants or refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2814	Hungary	border traffic agreement with Ukraine	2007	Local border traffic agreement between Hungary and Ukraine was signed in September 2007 - allowing two consulates of the Republic of Hungary in Ukraine to issue special permits which entitle the holder to multiple visa-free entries into the territory of Hungary and to reside for maximum three months within a six months period. > The minimum validity period of the permit is 1 year, while the maximum validity period is 5 years.	EMN 2008: 9	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Travel visa/permit	All	Specific nationalities	Ukraine	Less restrictive		
2815	Hungary	EU 2007 enlargement no direct free access to labour market	2007	EU 2007 Enlargement - A government decree in December 2006 concerning Romanian and Bulgarian citizens made their access to the labour market in Hungary subject to authorisation.  > However, in sectors of labour shortages (currently 219 professions), indicated on a government list, an employment permit is automatically issued. Since January 2007, the government has been reviewing the labour market situation on a quarterly basis to amend the list of professions without labour market testing.  Background: Due to the concern over potential inflows of Romanian workers, the Hungarian labour market remained partially subject to authorization for Romanian and Bulgarian workers, even after their countries accession to the EU. This policy has to be viewed in light of the fact that Romanians have accounted for about 50% of the inflows of foreign nationals since 2000.	SOPEMI 2008: 248	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	All migrant workers	EU citizens	Romania, Bulgaria	Less restrictive		
2816	Hungary	subsidiary protection created	2008	Act LXXX of 2007 on Asylum entered into force on 1st January 2008 - introduced the concept of subsidiary protection into the Hungarian legislation and simplified the procedural rules of recognition as a beneficiary of temporary protection.  > The refugee status and the subsidiary protection are determined in a single unified procedure in accordance with the provisions of the Procedures Directive.	EMN 2008: 3, 10	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2817	Hungary	family reunification for beneficiaries of subsidiary protection	2008	Act LXXX of 2007 on Asylum entered into force on 1st January 2008 - grants immediate family reunification to a beneficiary of subsidiary protection  > The recognition of a refugees family member is automatic, meaning that the asylum authority does not examine whether the conditions of recognition as a refugee are met by the family member. The refugee authority has to establish only that the family relationship is certified.	EMN 2008: 14	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members of irregular migrants or refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2818	Hungary	reform of the reception system for asylum seekers	2008	Act LXXX of 2007 on Asylum entered into force on 1st January 2008 - reformed the reception system:  From the 1st of January 2008, the three reception centres host  asylum-seekers, refugees and beneficiaries of subsidiary protection at three different stages of the asylum procedure.  > The newly arrived asylum-seekers are accommodated in the screening centre (in Békéscsaba) during the period of the preliminary assessment procedure. If it ends with a positive decision, the process continues with the inmerit procedure and the asylum-seekers are moved into the accommodation centre (in Debrecen) where they can stay till the end of the in-merit procedural phase. When asylumseekers become recognised refugees or beneficiaries of subsidiary protection they shall move to the pre-integration centre (to Bicske) where they can participate in different courses and receive supports in order to start a new life.  All three reception centres provide accommodation and the necessary provisions (meals, washing and cleaning devices, clothes) free of charge.	EMN 2008: 19	Major change	National policy	Border and land control	Institutional capacities	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Change in restrictiveness cannot be assessed		
2819	Hungary	extended language courses for refugees and subsidiary protected people	2008	Act LXXX of 2007 on Asylum entered into force on 1st January 2008 - extended the scope of getting free language courses and free language exam from refugees also to beneficiaries of subsidiary protection and beneficiaries of temporary protection.  > The new Act on Asylum increased the number of lessons from 360 to 520 hours which can be pursued at intermediate and advanced level. The new Act on Asylum prolonged the period during which the language course can be pursued; it was increased from 12 months to 24 months from the date of granting international protection status in the institution assigned by the refugee authority.	EMN 2008: 19, 21	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Language, housing and cultural integration programmes	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
