2973	Hungary	Return and readmission	2019	Certain returnrelated provisions of Act ll of 2007 on the admission and right of residence of thirdcountry nationals came into force on 1 January 2019. The changes aimed to make returns more efficient, for example, setting a specific timealimit for contesting a court's return decision, and earlier identification of returnees in prison.	EMN report	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Exit	Reintegration/return programmes	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
2974	Iceland	resettlement of Vietnamese refugees	1990	In 1990 and 1991, a total of 60 quota Refugees from Vietnam were resettled to Iceland	http://eng.velferdarraduneyti.is/information/refugees/nr/947 [accessed on 20.02.2014]	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Resettlement programmes	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	Specific nationalities	Vietnam	Less restrictive		
2975	Iceland	free mobility for EU workers	1993	Act on the Free Right to Employment and Residence within the European Economic Area No. 47/1993 - reversed Iceland's strict immigration policy, as it granted citizens of the EU countries to come to Iceland to work without a work permit.  > This was introduced in anticipation of the EEA agreement that came into force in 1994.	Gisladottir Bissat 2013: 49; Eydal and Ottosdottir 2009: 8; http://eng.velferdarraduneyti.is/media/acrobat-enskar_sidur/Act-No-47-1993-with-subsequent-amendments-and-regulation.pdf [accessed on 20.02.2014]	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Free mobility rights/agreements	All migrant workers	EU citizens	EU member states at that time	Less restrictive		
2976	Iceland	consolidation of work permit rules	1994	Act on the employment of foreigners no. 133 of 21 December 1994 - did not importantly change the 1982 rules. The work permit was still as before restricted to an occupation and issued to the employer, so the employee was in fact bound to stay with the same employer or else risk losing the work permit, would she/he choose to leave their employer.	http://www.althingi.is/altext/stjt/1994.133.html [accessed on 06.03.2014]	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Change in restrictiveness cannot be assessed		
2977	Iceland	possibility of open work permit after three years	1994	Act on the employment of foreigners no. 133 of 21 December 1994 - created possibility for a migrant worker who had had a legal residency in the country for three consecutive years to apply for an independent open and unrestricted work permit.  > The law did however still allow restricted work permits to be repealed at any given time and as seem at arbitrary will, as the law did not indicate anywhere what causes needed to be behind such a revocation. In light of the revocation stipulation it seems that the authorities were in fact not as ready to extend the freedom of migrant laborers on the Icelandic labor market as might seem at first	Ellenberger 2003: 76; http://www.althingi.is/altext/stjt/1994.133.html [accessed on 06.03.2014]	Major change	National policy	Integration	Work visa/permit	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
