2979	Iceland	continuous resettlement programme created	1996	The Icelandic Refugee Committee (until 2005 the Council) was established in 1996 - together with a continuous resettlement programme. On arrival into Iceland, resettled refugees are granted full refugee status and receive a temporary residence card valid for 4 years. After four years, refugees who have completed 250 hours of Icelandic language lessons may apply for permanent residence.  > Since then Iceland has overseen the reception of refugees annually or every other year, approximately 22 refugees each year, as a part of the UNHCR Resettlement Programme.	http://www.refworld.org/pdfid/52a0776a0.pdf [accessed on 20.02.2014]	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Resettlement programmes	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2980	Iceland	integration programme for resettled refugees	1996	The Icelandic Refugee Committee (until 2005 the Council) was established in 1996 - to coordinate municipalities and the Icelandic Red Cross in implementing the integration programme for resettled refugees during the first 12 months after arrival > In addition to housing, municipalities are responsible for language courses, financial support, psychological assessment and social counselling provided during the first 12 months. Financial support, also for the first 12 months, is set at a level determined as adequate for health and general living expenses by social services in the receiving municipality.  This support ceases after 12 months, and resettled refugees are then eligible to receive the same level of financial assistance as other Icelandic residents with similar/the same needs.  Language courses include both classroom lessons and individual private lessons, and are provided for an initial period of 6 months.  Classroom learning provision during this initial period is three hours per day, for four days per week.	http://www.resettlement.eu/country/iceland [accessed on 20.02.2014]	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Language, housing and cultural integration programmes	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2981	Iceland	naturalisation not conditioned anymore on acquiring Icelandic name	1996	In 1996, parliament accepted a change in the law on names, dropping completely the demand that new citizens adopt an Icelandic name.	Johannesson et al 2013: 13; http://eng.innanrikisraduneyti.is/laws-and-regulations/english/personal-names/ [accessed on 20.02.2014]	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2982	Iceland	gender imbalance reduced	1998	Act no. 62/1998 amending the 1952 citizenship act - laid down rules which were meant to increase gender equality.	Johannesson et al 2013: 13	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All	All	N/A	Less restrictive		
2983	Iceland	citizenship rules clarified and eligible after seven years of residency	1998	Act no. 62/1998 amending the 1952 citizenship act - gave the Minister of Interior the authority to grant citizenship through an administrative procedure and laid down criteria to be fulfilled by an applicant for citizenship, in the new Articles 89 of the Citizenship Act, largely in line with the guidelines in use by the General Committee. > The main rule is seven years of residence (previously 10) and additional criteria can be summarised as follows: 1) The applicant shall be employable and have a good reputation, which shall be demonstrated by testimonials from two reputable Icelandic citizens. 2) The applicants shall have no unpaid tax duties, been declared bankrupt or have had his or her property subject to bankruptcy proceedings, for the past three years. 3) The applicant may not, either in Iceland or abroad, have been fined or imprisoned or be involved in a criminal case pending in the justice system in which he or she is suspected of, or charged with, conduct which is criminal according to Icelandic law.	Johannesson et al 2013: 19	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
2984	Iceland	nordic citizens can be naturalised after 4 years	1998	Act no. 62/1998 amending the 1952 citizenship act -  Nordic citizens were to have held legal residence in Iceland for four years (previously five).	Johannesson et al 2013: 19	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	Specific nationalities	Nordic cooperation countries	Less restrictive		
2985	Iceland	family members can be naturalised after 3 years	1998	Act no. 62/1998 amending the 1952 citizenship act - The husband or wife of an Icelandic citizen could be granted citizenship after three years of marriage, but only if the Icelandic partner had held his or her citizenship for at least five years. Foreign citizens whose mother or father held Icelandic citizenship could acquire citizenship after three years if the other parent was Nordic; if not, the period was five years.	Johannesson et al 2013: 19	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	No change		
