3020	Iceland	rearrangement of work permits	2008	Act No. 78/2008 amending the 2002 Employment Act - entails the adoption of categories of temporary work permits reflecting the grounds on which foreign nationals are working in Iceland.	http://eng.velferdarraduneyti.is/media/acrobat-enskar_sidur/Foreign-Nationals-Right-to-Work-Act-No-97-2002-as-amended.pdf [accessed on 20.02.2014]	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Change in restrictiveness cannot be assessed		
3021	Iceland	projects for integration of foreigners	2008	The Government policy on the integration of immigrants was followed by an extensive action document put together by the Ministry of Social Affairs and enacted by Parliament in May 2008.  > This document is a comprehensive set of projects that shall be undertaken and completed within two years: The list of projects includes among others, the making of a comprehensive and extensive bill on immigration affairs; projects in employment; education; health and social services. Each project entails a description of the project and outlines who is responsible for the processing of the project, for supervising it and the time limits as well as a cost estimate.	Eydal and Ottosdottir 2009: 12; http://www.velferdarraduneyti.is/media/acrobat-skjol/Tingsalyktun_um_framkvamdaaatlun_i_malefnum_innflytjenda_asamt_tingsalyktunartillogunni.pdf [accessed on 06.03.2014]	Major change	National policy	Integration	Language, housing and cultural integration programmes	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
3022	Iceland	language test for naturalisation introduced in 2007, implemented	2009	Regulations No. 1129/2008 on Icelandic language tests for persons applying for Icelandic citizenship took effect on 1 January 2009.   > Tests shall involve speaking, oral understanding, writing and reading comprehension and applicants are required: a.to be able to cope with day-to-day situations in educational institutions, employment and private life; b.to be able to cope with unexpected circumstances; c.to have acquired sufficient command of vocabulary in order to take part in discussions of familiar topics; d.to be able to understand simple conversations between persons; e.to be able to read short texts in simple language about familiar topics; f.to be able to write a short text in simple language about familiar topics; g.to be able to understand the main points in coverage in the broadcasting media (radio and television) when the topics are familiar to them.	http://eng.innanrikisraduneyti.is/laws-and-regulations/english/citizenship/nr/6759 [accessed on 20.02.2014]	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
3023	Iceland	lower refugee resettlement quota	2009	Due to the financial crisis in Iceland in 2008 the quota for resettled refugees was reduced - in the year 2010 two families (six persons) were accepted as resettled refugees. In the year 2012 Iceland accepted three families (nine persons) as quota refugees.	http://www.refworld.org/pdfid/52a0776a0.pdf [accessed on 20.02.2014]	Fine-tuning change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Quota/target	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
3024	Iceland	action plan against THB	2009	First Government Action Plan against trafficking in human beings of 7 December 2007, > This Action Plan is divided into nine chapters. These are: 1. Ratification of international treaties and harmonisation of Icelandic legislation. 2. Specialist and co-ordination team and the supervision of affairs concerning human trafficking. 3. Education to professionals and public officials. 4. Protection of victims and aid to victims. 5. Police provisions and investigation into alleged trafficking in humans. 6. Actions against demand in the prostitution and pornography industry. 7. International co-operation. 8. Proactive search and emergency phone numbers. 9. Registration of information and intelligence gathering.	http://eng.velferdarraduneyti.is/Reports/nr/20397 [accessed on 20.02.2014]; http://eng.velferdarraduneyti.is/Reports/nr/20397 [accessed on 20.02.2014]	N/A	N/A	Border and land control	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
3025	Iceland	temporary stay permit for victims of THB	2010	Act 116/2010 amending the 2002 Foreigners Act - introduced the possibility to grant a temporary stay permit for six months to a foreign national, who is suspected of being a victim of human trafficking, even though all the requirements of Art. 11 are not fulfilled. Notwithstanding the provisions of Art. 20, the individual concerned may not be deported during this period. > A permit granted as referred to in this provision cannot serve as the basis for a permanent residence permit.	http://eng.innanrikisraduneyti.is/laws-and-regulations/nr/105 [accessed on 20.02.2014]	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
3026	Iceland	2007 enlargement temporary restriction raised	2012	2007 Enlargement - Iceland raised the temporary restrictions on labour migrants from Romania and Bulgaria in 2012.	http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Freedom_of_movement_for_workers [accessed on 20.02.2014]	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Free mobility rights/agreements	All migrant workers	EU citizens	Romania, Bulgaria	Less restrictive		
3027	Iceland	Amendment of the Foreign Nationals Right to Work Act	2014	Amendment of the Foreign Nationals Right to Work Act  postponed the time until Croatian nationals are exempted from providing a work permit until 1 July 2015	http://www.ilo.org/dyn/natlex/docs/ELECTRONIC/64015/61222/F859279759/ISL64015%20Eng%202014.pdf	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	All migrant workers	Specific nationalities	Croatia	More restrictive		
3028	Iceland	Act on the Free Right to Employment and Residence within the European Economic Area (Act 105/2014)	2014	Act on the Free Right to Employment and Residence within the European Economic Area (Act 105/2014)  provided that relatives of citizens of EEA or EFTA member states who are legally resident in Iceland shall have the right to engage in employment or work as self-employed individuals on the Icelandic labour market, irrespective of their nationality	http://www.ilo.org/dyn/natlex/docs/ELECTRONIC/104421/134531/F834855132/ISL104421%20Eng.pdf	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Family members	EU citizens	N/A	Less restrictive		
