3244	Ireland	bosnian resettlement programme	1992	UNHCR Bosnian Refugee Programme	Ward 1998	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Resettlement programmes	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	Specific nationalities	Bosnia	Less restrictive		
3245	Ireland	ireland becomes an immigration country	1996	In 1996, Ireland reached its migration 'turning point,' making it the last EU Member State to become a country of net immigration > Background: rapid economic growth created an unprecedented demand for labor across a wide range of sectors, including construction, financial, information technology, and health care. Unemployment declined from 15.9 percent in 1993 to a historic low of 3.6 percent in 2001.	MPI 2009	N/A	N/A	Legal entry and stay	Contextual elements	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
3246	Ireland	refugee determination procedure created	1996	Refugee Act 1996 - the first significant legislation in this area since 1936 establishes a refugee determination procedure in Ireland on the basis of the 1951 Geneva convention and the 1967 Protocol  > In addition there has been extension to these guidelines with inclusion of those suffering from persecution for reasons of gender, sexual orientation or membership of a trade union.	SOPEMI 2003b: 214-215; SOPEMI 1997: 119	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
3247	Ireland	refugee status determination institutions established	1996	Refugee Act 1996 - the first significant legislation in this area since 1936 established the Refugee Applications Commissioner (ORAC) as a statutorily independent body that considers asylum applications at first instance, as well as the Refugee Appeals Tribunal to hear appeals of negative asylum decisions.	Focus Migration 2010: 5	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Institutional capacities	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
3248	Ireland	Dublin entered into force in Ireland	1997	On 1 September 1997, the Dublin Convention entered into force in Ireland (signed on 15 June 1990) - determining the state responsible for assessing asylum claims of third country nationals	Vink 2012	Major change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
3249	Ireland	naturalisation through investment ends	1998	In 1998 the investment-based naturalisation scheme ends	SOPEMI 1995: 97; Handoll 2012: 5	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	Investors, entrepreneurs and business people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
3250	Ireland	refugee resettlement programme started	1998	In 1998, Ireland became involved in the UNHCR Resettlement Quota Programme - Initially, the Irish Government agreed to accept an annual quota of 10 cases plus immediate family members > Ireland has been resettling refugees since 1956 under country-specific agreements.	http://www.resettlement.eu//country/ireland [accessed on 17.10.2013]	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Resettlement programmes	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
3251	Ireland	first anti-discrimination legislation	1998	The Employment Equality Act 1998 - prohibits discrimination on nine grounds: gender, marital status, family status, sexual orientation, religious belief, age, disability, race and membership of the Traveller community.  > The scope of this Act is employment related and discrimination is prohibited in employment, vocational training, advertising, collective agreements, and employment agencies. The legislation prohibits direct discrimination, indirect discrimination, harassment, procurement of discrimination and requires reasonable accommodation.	EMN 2004: 18	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to justice and political rights	All	All	N/A	Less restrictive		
3252	Ireland	good Friday agreement	1998	1998 Good Friday Agreement - a Multi-Party Agreement between political parties in the North and a British-Irish Agreement between the UK and Irish government. To secure political settlement in the North, the Irish government agreed that, subject to a referendum approving the necessary changes, the Irish claim to territorial unity was abandoned.  > This led to a constitutional change of art. 2 which now provided: It is the entitlement and birthright of every person born in the island of Ireland, which includes its islands and seas, to be part of the Irish nation.' This implied that every person born in the island of Ireland was entitled to be part of the Irish nation, in reality intending to enable people in Northern Ireland to identify themselves as Irish.	Handoll 2012: 6	N/A	N/A	N/A	Contextual elements	N/A	N/A	N/A			
3253	Ireland	ICT transfer scheme created	1999	Intra-company transfer scheme introduced in 1999 - for a limited number of highly skilled or key personnel. > Companies with a presence in Ireland and at least one other non-EEA country could transfer staff via the scheme to Ireland for up to four years without requiring an employment permit. In October 2002 these schemes were suspended due to abuse, but reintroduced in 2007.	Quinn and O'Connell 2007: 9	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
3254	Ireland	expulsion criteria introduced	1999	1999 Immigration Act - sets out the principles, procedures and criteria which govern the detention and removal of non-Irish nationals from the State, and makes provision for the issuing of deportation and exclusion orders. It allows the Minister for Justice, Equality and Law Reform to require any non-Irish national to leave the State and remain thereafter out of the State.  > The Act also lays out the matters to which the Minister is required to have regard in determining whether to make a deportation order. These matters are (a) the persons age, (b) duration of residence in the State, (c) family and domestic circumstances, (d) the nature of their connection with the State, (e) their employment record, (f) their employment prospects, (g) their character and conduct, (h) humanitarian considerations, (i) any representations made, (j) the common good, and (k) considerations of national security and public policy. The Act gives the Minister power to amend or revoke a deportation order, and provides for the arrest and detention (for a period or period not exceeding eight weeks in aggregate) of a person against whom a deportation order is in force.  Background: In the case of Laurentiu v Minister for Justice, Equality and Law Reform [2000] the Aliens Act 1935 was found to be unconstitutional in the manner in which it gave the Minister for Justice, Equality and Law Reform the power to deport. In effect the Minister was found to be without statutory powers in relation to deportation of non-Irish nationals from the State. The Immigration Act 1999 was designed to remedy this gap.	SOPEMI 2003b: 214-215; http://emn.ie/cat_search_detail.jsp?clog=4&itemID=35 [accessed on 21.10.2013]	Major change	National policy	Exit	Expulsion	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
3255	Ireland	sanction for organising entry of irregular migrants	2000	Illegal Immigrants (Trafficking) Act 2000 - makes it an offence to organise or knowingly facilitate the entry into the State of an illegal immigrant or a person who intends to seek asylum.	http://emn.ie/cat_search_detail.jsp?clog=4&itemID=37&item_name= [accessed on 21.10.2013]	Mid-level change	National policy	Border and land control	Other sanctions	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
3256	Ireland	new visa for high skilled workers in certain jobs	2000	In 2000 a work visa and work authorisation programme was introduced - to facilitate the recruitment of highly-skilled non-EU nationals in the areas of information and computing technologies, construction professionals, and a broad range of medical, health and social care professions.	Focus Migration 2010: 4	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
3257	Ireland	broadening of anti-discrimination legislation	2000	Equal Status Act 2000 - moves the concept of discrimination beyond the workforce and into the public arena (education, social interaction, housing, business)  > Discrimination is given a broader definition than in the Employment Equality Act and includes direct discrimination, indirect discrimination and discrimination by association and by imputation	EMN 2004: 18	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to justice and political rights	All	All	N/A	Less restrictive		
3258	Ireland	change in immigration flows from returning irish emigrants to non-EU immigrants	2000	In the late 1980s around 65 per cent of the immigrants coming to Ireland were returning Irish emigrants. During the 1990s and 2000s the share of returning Irish dropped significantly and between 2006 and 2008 Irish immigrants made up only 18 per cent of the inflow. As the share of returning Irish migrants continued to fall, non-EU migrants came to dominate the flows, constituting more than half of all non-Irish immigrants arriving in Ireland between 2001 and 2004.	Focus Migration 2010: 2	N/A	N/A	Legal entry and stay	Contextual elements	All migrants	All	N/A	N/A		
3259	Ireland	voluntary return programme	2001	The first pilot voluntary return programme was initiated in 2001 for Nigerian and Romanian nationals - It has now been extended to all asylum seekers and irregular migrants from non-EEA countries, without documentation and the necessary financial means.  > The programme offers assistance in three stages of return: pre-departure, transportation and post arrival. Returning migrants are given assistance in the form of information, counselling, medical assistance, travel allowance, transport assistance, reintegration assistance and limited monitoring. Reintegration support is not in the form of a cash payment, but rather assistance with starting a small business, training, job placements, further education and language courses, as well as the provision of information and referral to local health services, social security systems and other services as appropriate.	Quinn and Hughes 2005: 24	Major change	National policy	Exit	Reintegration/return programmes	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
3260	Ireland	agreement with Bulgaria on THB and other criminal activities	2001	Bulgaria signed a bilateral agreement with Ireland in 2001 to fight against trafficking, terrorism and other criminal activities, such as drug smuggling and money laundering.	SOPEMI 2003b: 175	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Border and land control	Surveillance technology/control powers	Specific categories	Specific nationalities	Bulgaria	More restrictive		
3261	Ireland	northern ireland inhabitants now eligible for irish citizenship	2001	The Irish Nationality and Citizenship Act 2001 -amended the 1956 Act to reflect the changes following the Good Friday Agreement in relation to ius soli citizenship, changing the attribution of Irish citizenship from birth to every person born in Ireland by a provision stating that [e]very person born in the island of Ireland is entitled to be an Irish citizen.	Handoll 2012: 7	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All	Specific nationalities	Northern Ireland	Less restrictive		
3262	Ireland	ICT transfer scheme suspended	2002	Intra-company transfer scheme introduced in 1999 was suspended in October due to abuse > It was reintroduced in 2007 with the Employment Permits Act	Quinn and O'Connell 2007: 9	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
3263	Ireland	work permit system made stricter	2002	Since January 2002 certain restrictions were applied to the Work Permit system - requiring employers to prove that they could not source workers in Ireland before applying for a permit. Previously the requirement was voluntary.  > New applications are not now accepted unless accompanied by a confirmation from the National Training and Employment Authority (FÁS) stating that all reasonable efforts had been made by the employer to find an Irish or other EEA national to fill the vacancy on offer. The fees associated with obtaining permits were also increased.	SOPEMI 2003b: 214-215; Focus Migration 2010: 4	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
3264	Ireland	First policy document on Irish diaspora	2002	Key policy document on 'Ireland and the Irish Abroad: Report on the Taskforce on Policy regarding Migrants Abroad'   > The Task Force recommended to  Ensuring, as far as possible, that Irish who emigrate do so voluntarily and on the basis of informed choice and are properly prepared to live independently abroad;  Protecting and supporting the Irish abroad, particularly those who emigrated involuntarily and those who find themselves marginalised or at risk of social exclusion;  Facilitating the return to Ireland and reintegration into Irish society of emigrants who wish to do so, especially the vulnerable and the elderly;  Supporting the Irish abroad who wish to express and share the Irish dimension of their identity.	https://www.dfa.ie/media/dfa/alldfawebsitemedia/newspress/publications/2007-vfm-policy-review-of-irish-emigrant-groups-programme.pdf [accessed on 14.01.2014]	N/A	N/A	Integration	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	Diaspora	Citizens	N/A	N/A		
