3321	Ireland	spouses now need to apply for work permits	2009	June 2009 restrictions due to the economic crisis - restricts access and eligibility to the spousal work permit scheme of 2004  > Dependents, spouses and dependants of firsttime work permit applicants whose applications were received on or after 1 June 2009 cannot be considered for an employment permit under the Spousal/Dependant Scheme, except for spouses/dependants of Green Card holders and Researchers.	SOPEMI 2009; SOPEMI 2010: 212	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Work visa/permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
3322	Ireland	eased criteria for resident foreign workers to stay in Ireland	2009	In August 2009, several measures were taken that facilitate migrants stay and economic activity  > Those who stayed and worked legally in Ireland for at least five consecutive years continuously, and holders of green cards which were due to expire no longer require a work permit. The permission is for one year and can be renewed, but the holders of the permit are expected to work and support themselves. The time to seek alternative employment for unemployed work permit holders was expended from three to six months, and the labour market test no longer applies to them.	SOPEMI 2011: 288	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Work visa/permit	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
3323	Ireland	regularisation for specific category of undocumented workers	2009	Undocumented Workers Scheme initiated in the last quarter of 2009 - allowing workers who had become undocumented through no fault of their own to obtain a temporary immigration permission of four months within which they could seek legitimate employment or obtain an employment permit if they were already employed.  > The measure thus only concerned a small part of the estimated 30 000 undocumented migrants living in Ireland at that time.	SOPEMI 2011: 288	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Regularisation	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
3324	Ireland	discussions about restricting student status and stronger controls	2009	In September 2009, the Ministry of Justice proposed to review the immigration regime for full time non- EEA students - to reduce abuse of student status for employment purposes by capping the duration of studies and imposing stricter inspection regimes.  > At the same time, measures to retain graduates as part of highly skilled migration are also considered.	SOPEMI 2010: 212	N/A	N/A	Integration	Work visa/permit	International students	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
