4211	Luxembourg	regularisation campain	2001	In March 2001, the Government launched a regularisation - aimed at two main categories (and 7 sub-categories) of immigrants, i.e. undocumented immigrants and asylum seekers. Those who met the government's conditions were given six months to find work.  > For undocumented immigrants, the procedure was open to persons who had resided without interruption since 1 January 2000 and had stable employment or could plead special social circumstances. The asylum seekers eligible were those who had filed their application before 1 July 1998 or had been in the country since 1 January 2000 and belonged to an ethnic minority of Kosovo.  The innovative aspect of the procedure lay in the fact that it was implemented in close co-operation with the Craftsmens Federation, the Chamber of Agriculture and Horesca (the federation of hotel, restaurant and café owners), which represented the sectors most affected by labour shortages. These professional federations sought to place the persons  regularised in vacancies in their respective sectors. At the same time, the government announced that it would not take measures against firms employing illegal immigrants if they declared them and paid any unpaid social contributions.	SOPEMI 2003b: 228, Ortega and Peri 2009; http://www.gouvernement.lu/823588/09_biltgen [accessed on 10.02.2014]	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Regularisation	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4212	Luxembourg	shorter residency requirement for citizenship	2002	Act of 24 July 2001 on the Acquisition of nationality came into force in January 2002 - facilitated naturalisation by requiring applicants for citizenships to have resided in Luxembourg for 5 consecutive years (instead of 10 as was the previous case)	SOPEMI 2003b: 230; Mayda 2004: 10	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4213	Luxembourg	language requirement introduced for naturalisation	2002	Act of 24 July 2001 on the Acquisition of nationality came into force in January 2002 -  refused naturalisation to the foreigner who does not demonstrate sufficient integration, notably if he or she does not demonstrate sufficient active and passive knowledge of at least one of the [national] languages [i.e. Luxembourgish, French, German]  and if he or she does not have at least a basic knowledge of the Luxembourgish language, underscored by certificates and official documents.	Scuto 2013: 7	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4214	Luxembourg	social benefits for asylum seekers	2002	Grand Ducal Regulation of 4 July 2002 - defines the modalities and conditions of social aid for asylum seekers	SOPEMI 2003b: 230; http://www.legilux.public.lu/leg/a/archives/2002/0084/a084.pdf#page=2 [accessed on 10.02.2014]	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to social benefits and socio-economic rights	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4215	Luxembourg	voting rights extended to non-EU nationals	2003	New electoral legislation entered into force in February 2003 - allowing foreigners residing in Luxembourg, regardless of whether or not they are EU nationals, to vote and/or stand as a candidate in the communal elections of October 2005 without losing their voting rights in their home country commune. Only the EU nationals have the right to stand as a candidate. > It also reduces the length of the residence period required before which foreigners can register on electoral lists. Foreigners must be domiciled in the Grand Duchy, or to have legally resided there prior to 1 April 2004, for at least five years. Foreign nationals had until 31 March 2004 to register on electoral lists.	SOPEMI 2005: 233; Scuto 2013b	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to justice and political rights	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4216	Luxembourg	special education support for children of immigrants	2003	With a view to promoting the integration of foreigners, in July 2003, Luxembourg set up reception and insertion classes for first generation immigrant pupils and the children of asylum seekers who do not speak the languages in which instruction is provided.  > In addition, special language classes have been introduced (in which instruction can be provided in a language other than German) in technical secondary schools. The law provides for the possibility of employing foreign nationals to provide integrated classes in the mother tongue of foreign children, notably the children of refugees. It also provides for the possibility of recruiting intercultural mediators.	SOPEMI 2005: 233	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Language, housing and cultural integration programmes	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4217	Luxembourg	EU 2004 enlargement restrictions to labour market access	2004	Act of 29 April 2004 regulates the access to the labour market of the new EU member states nationals - allowing the government to take measures with regard to the transitional period of two years during which restrictions on access to the labour market for such nationals will remain in force.	SOPEMI 2005: 232	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	All migrant workers	EU citizens	Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, Poland, Slovakia and Slovenia	No change		
4218	Luxembourg	fast track for refugees from safe third countries	2004	Amendment of the 1996 Act on asylum introduced in April 2004 - aimed at reducing the time taken to process asylum applications by providing for a fast-track procedure for applicants from safe third countries and by abolishing certain appeals and introducing shorter administrative and judicial procedures >  The bill was withdrawn and replaced by a new bill on January 2005 which became the Asylum Law (Law of 5 May 2006)	SOPEMI 2005: 233	N/A	N/A	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	Those originating from or transiting through safe countries	N/A		
4219	Luxembourg	special education support for children of immigrants	2005	From 2005/2006, all communes are obliged to establish pre-school education programmes, with Luxembourgeois to be taught but the native language of the child taken into account.  > Other programmes in place include the training of teachers, information sessions for parents of students, information meetings for associations, language courses in Italian and Portuguese, intercultural mediation, specific measures for children of asylum seekers and international exchanges.	SOPEMI 2006: 196	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Integration	Language, housing and cultural integration programmes	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4220	Luxembourg	subsidiary protection status created	2006	Asylum Law of 5 May 2006 - creates the status of subsidiary protection > For this status, the applicant does not have to prove its persecution by a state entity. Also non-state entities are valid reasons for granting the protection status.	EMN 2009: 9; http://www.legilux.public.lu/leg/a/archives/2006/0078/a078.pdf [accessed on 10.02.2014]	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4221	Luxembourg	work permit for asylum seekers if no response after 9 months	2006	Asylum Law of 5 May 2006 - grants access to the labout market to asylum seekers if 9 months after the request no decision is made.  > The asylum seeker then gets a temporary work authorisation for six months, renewable, until the request is either rejected or approved. It is valid only for one profession and employer.	EMN 2009: 9; http://www.legilux.public.lu/leg/a/archives/2006/0078/a078.pdf [accessed on 10.02.2014]	Major change	National policy	Integration	Work visa/permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4222	Luxembourg	2007 enlargement restricted access to labour market	2007	In January 2007, citizens of Romania and Bulgaria were included in the transitional measures for  nationals of the new EU member states to obtain work permits	SOPEMI 2008: 260	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	All migrant workers	EU citizens	Romania, Bulgaria	No change		
4223	Luxembourg	2004 enlargement free access to labour market	2007	In November 2007 Luxembourg lifted restrictions for workers from the 2004 accession countries.	EMN 2011 (CTM): 50; http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/3513889.stm [accessed on 09.12.2013]	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Free mobility rights/agreements	All migrant workers	EU citizens	Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, Poland, Slovakia and Slovenia	Less restrictive		
4224	Luxembourg	students can work during studies	2007	Since the beginning of academic year, students enrolled in the University of Luxembourg who are nationals of a third country may obtain a work permit allowing them to work on a part time basis  while pursuing their studies.  > They may work ten hours  per week during the academic year, but this restriction is lifted when the university is not in session. This permit is renewable upon presentation of proof of re-enrolment in the university but may be withdrawn if a student fails to attend classes on a regular basis.	SOPEMI 2008: 260	Major change	National policy	Integration	Work visa/permit	International students	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4225	Luxembourg	list of safe countries  of origin created	2007	Grand-ducal regulation of 21 decembre 2007 - created a list of 11 safe third countries: Albania, Benin, Bosnia-Herzegowina, Cap-Verde, Croatia, Ghana, Macedonia, Mali, Montenegro, Senegal and Ukraine.  > Three of those countries, Benin, Ghana and Mali, are declared safe countries only for male applicants, as female genital mutilation is still practiced there.	http://www.legilux.public.lu/leg/a/archives/2007/0245/a245.pdf [accessed on 10.02.2014]	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	Those originating from or transiting through safe countries	More restrictive		
4226	Luxembourg	reception desk for new young immigrants created	2008	Creation of the Reception Desk for Newly Arrived Pupils (CASNA) in 2008 - to better assess the educational needs of the many young people who arrive each year in Luxembourgh with their parents, and to assist their scholastic and vocational training integration, all 12-18 year olds must pass throgh CASNA.	SOPEMI 2009	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Integration	Institutional capacities	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4227	Luxembourg	permanent regularisation mechanism introduced	2008	Law of 29 August 2008 on immigration came into force on 1 October 2008 - enables the minister responsible for immigration to authorize residence on an exceptional basis to persons unlawfully resident in Luxembourg if they have remained continuously on the territory and worked there for at least eight years	EMN 2009: 43	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Regularisation	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4228	Luxembourg	new work permit system	2008	Law of 29 August 2008 on immigration came into force on 1 October 2008 - instituted different types of residence documents based on the diverse motivations for immigration.  > With regard to economic immigration, the following residence documents can be distinguished: salaried workers, detached workers, transferred workers, highly skilled workers, and independent workers.	EMN 2010: 27	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Change in restrictiveness cannot be assessed		
4229	Luxembourg	employees can now apply for work permit	2008	Law of 29 August 2008 on immigration came into force on 1 October 2008 - introduces authorized residence for paid employment and ends the two-tier system of residence permits and work permits.  > Application for a residence permit for purposes of employment must be made by the prospective employee or worker, whereas previously the employer had to apply for the work permit. Under the former legislation, the first work permit was valid for just one employer and a single profession, whereas under the new law, those allowed to work may undertake professional activity in one sector and profession, but with any employer.	EMN  2009: 25	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4230	Luxembourg	no removal of trafficking victims for 90 days	2008	Law of 29 August 2008 on immigration came into force on 1 October 2008 - grants trafficking victims who are third-country nationals a ninety-day cooling-off period during which the victim cannot be removed from Luxembourger territory.  > This Law sets the conditions under which residency permit may be granted upon expiration of this period (Articles 95 to 98).	EMN 2011: 105	Mid-level change	National policy	Exit	Expulsion	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4231	Luxembourg	new sanctions for irregular entry and stay	2008	Law of 29 August 2008 on immigration came into force on 1 October 2008 - strenghtened measures relating to irregular entry and residence > Fines and/or imprisonment are possible for foreigners who commit offences relating to entry or residence, or who make false statements or produce forged, falsified or inaccurate documents to gain entry to Luxembourg. The law also allows for the incarceration and/or fines for any foreigner who, after having been expelled or repatriated, returns to the country despite a denial of entry to the territory.	EMN  2009: 25; EMN 2011: 93	Major change	National policy	Border and land control	Other sanctions	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4232	Luxembourg	new sanctions for carriers	2008	Law of 29 August 2008 on immigration came into force on 1 October 2008 - strenghtened measures relating to carriers of irregular migrants > Air carriers are punished with fines if they transport third-country nationals to Luxembourg who are not in possession of the proper travel documents or visas, or if they have failed to provide the grand ducal police with appropriate information about their passengers bound for Luxembourg.	EMN  2009: 25; EMN 2011: 93	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Border and land control	Carrier liabilities	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4233	Luxembourg	new sanctions for those helping irregular migrants to enter	2008	Law of 29 August 2008 on immigration came into force on 1 October 2008 - introduced fines (from 500 to 125,000 Euros and/or imprisonment for between six months and five years) for any person who, directly or indirectly, knowingly facilitated or attempted to facilitate the entry, transit or/and (for purposes of gain) the irregular stay of a third-country national	EMN  2009: 25; EMN 2011: 93	Major change	National policy	Border and land control	Other sanctions	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4234	Luxembourg	student permit created	2008	Law of 29 August 2008 on immigration came into force on 1 October 2008 - stipulates that residence permits are issued to students in accordance with the duration of study programme with a maximum validity of one year.  > The first university in Luxembourg was established in 2003.	EMN 2012 (Students): 32	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	International students	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4235	Luxembourg	work allowed after studies under certain criteria	2008	Law of 29 August 2008 on immigration came into force on 1 October 2008 - foresees the possibility for the student to stay on the territory after finishing his or her studies, in order to acquire a first professional experience related to the studies.  > If the student finds a job before the end of his or her studies he/she can stay in Luxembourg to work for a maximum period of 2 year. If the student fulfils these criteria, the Directorate of Immigration can issue a residence permit as salaried worker. However, this residence permit cannot be renewed.	EMN 2012 (Students): 32, 77	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Work visa/permit	International students	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4236	Luxembourg	eased entry for high skilled	2008	Law of 29 August 2008 on immigration came into force on 1 October 2008 - sets out a faster procedure and less restrictive conditions for highly qualified workers seeking to enter the labour market.  > These concessions apply to jobs calling for special knowledge or professional skills, and to third-country nationals with a higher education qualification or at least five years of specialized professional experience who earn a salary at least three times as much as the guaranteed minimum wage for unskilled workers. In contrast to other paid workers, highly skilled workers have only to satisfy the legal conditions for entry to Luxembourg, an employment contract whose obligations they are qualified to fulfil and the above-mentioned salary requirement. The opinions of the ADEM and the CCTS are not required. In addition, the person concerned may be issued with a residence permit for up to three years, which is renewable on request for a further three-year period.	EMN  2009: 25	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4237	Luxembourg	immediate family reunification for high skilled	2008	Law of 29 August 2008 on immigration came into force on 1 October 2008 - allows highly skilled workers to bring members of their family with them (spouses or partners and single children aged under 18) when they enter the country. > Other workers have to wait for one year.	EMN  2009: 25	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members of high-skilled workers, investors or students	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4238	Luxembourg	family reunification after one year	2008	Law of 29 August 2008 on immigration came into force on 1 October 2008 - lais down that family reunification involving the family member of a third-country national is subject to the conditions of a one-year wait, stable, regular and sufficient resources, adequate accommodation and health insurance coverage.	EMN  2009: 30	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4239	Luxembourg	eased access to voting rights	2008	Law of 19 decembre 2008 modifies the electoral law - eases the requirements for foreigners to participate in elections > For european elections, EU citizens now need to prove only two years of residency (against 5 years previously) and for all elections the inscription deadline has become less stringent.	http://www.legilux.public.lu/leg/a/archives/2008/0210/a210.pdf [accessed on 10.02.2014]	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to justice and political rights	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4240	Luxembourg	marriage of convenience criminalized - not implemented	2009	A bill was presented which aims at establishing a legal framework to combat forced marriages or partnerships, or marriages or partnerships of convenience, and to empower marriage registrars to summon just one of the future spouses for an interview, in addition to the joint interview, if he or she has any doubts as to the legitimacy of a marriage.	SOPEMI 2011: 300	N/A	N/A	Legal entry and stay	Surveillance technology/control powers	Family members	All	N/A	N/A		
4241	Luxembourg	integration office created	2009	Law of 16 December 2008 on integration came into force on 1 June 2009 - created the Luxembourg Office of Welcome and Integration (OLAI) responsible for implementing Luxembourg's integration policy.  > This includes, among other responsibilities, coordination of welcome and integration policy, the Welcome Contract (CAI) and a five year national report on integration of foreigners	EMN 2009: 5	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Institutional capacities	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4242	Luxembourg	creation of CAI (implemented in 2011)	2009	Law of 16 December 2008 on integration came into force on 1 June 2009 - makes provision for the introduction of a standard welcome and integration contract (CAI) of up to two years (implemented in 2011)  > This contract will be offered to foreigners residing legally in the territory of the Grand Duchy of Luxembourg who wish to remain there on a long-term basis.	EMN 2009: 34	N/A	N/A	Integration	Language, housing and cultural integration programmes	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
