4244	Luxembourg	double ius soli reintroduced	2009	The new law on nationality that entered into force on 1 January 2009 - reintroduced double ius soli, 68 years after its abolition in 1940.  > A child born in Luxembourg to non-Luxembourgish parents, one of whom was born in the Grand Duchy, has Luxembourgish citizenship.  This provision is not applied only to the children born after 1 January 2009 (the date of entry into force of the law), but also to those who have not reached 18 years of age on 1 January 2009: thus children born between 1 January 1991 and 31 December 2008.	Scuto 2013: 11; SOPEMI 2006: 196	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4245	Luxembourg	longer residency requirement for naturalisation	2009	The new law on nationality that entered into force on 1 January 2009 - raised the minimum number of years of residence before naturalisation from five to seven years.	Scuto 2013: 11	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4246	Luxembourg	language test for naturalisation introduced	2009	The new law on nationality that entered into force on 1 January 2009 - linked naturalisation to the applicants success in a test in the spoken Luxembourgish language and to the obligation to attend at least three citizenship courses.  > The level of competence to be attained in the spoken Luxembourgish language is level B1 of the Common European Framework of Reference for Languages in terms of oral comprehension, and level A2 of the same framework in terms of oral expression. However, an exemption is given to those who have accomplished at least seven years of their schooling in a Luxembourgish public school (or private school applying the curriculum of the public school) and to those who lived on Luxembourgish territory prior to 31 December 1984.	Scuto 2013: 11	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4247	Luxembourg	dual nationality allowed	2009	The new law on nationality that entered into force on 1 January 2009 - introducing the principle of dual nationality into Luxembourg law > The law is aimed at facilitating the integration of foreigners who reside in the Grand Duchy and wish to obtain Luxembourg nationality while keeping their nationality of origin.	SOPEMI 2010: 222	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4248	Luxembourg	language leave created to foster integration	2009	Act of 17 February 2009 introduced language leave  a special, additional period of leave to allow persons of any nationality to learn Luxembourgish or improve their knowledge of the language, in order to facilitate their integration.	SOPEMI 2011: 300	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Language, housing and cultural integration programmes	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4249	Luxembourg	resettlement of iraqis	2009	Luxembourg is taking part in the scheme for reallocation of Iraqi refugees recognized by the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR).  > Luxembourg has no official resettlement programme however it has occasionally carried out ad-hoc resettlement.	EMN 2009: 21; http://www.resettlement.eu//country/luxembourg [accessed on 30.09.2013]	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Resettlement programmes	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	Specific nationalities	Iraq	Less restrictive		
4250	Luxembourg	detention centers created	2009	Law of 28 May 2009 on the establishment and organization of the Detention Centre - set the conditions and general procedures of the detention centre  > Until the opening of the new Detention Centre, people in an irregular situation were detained in a separate section of Luxembourg Penitentiary Centre in Schrassig. Faced with the limited capacity and the impossibility of arranging separate sections, a maximum of 25 individuals of the masculine gender could be placed there. Families waiting to be removed were placed in the AIDA centre, located within the airport, for a stay which could be from 24 to 72 hour	EMN 2009: 9: EMN 2010: 8	Major change	National policy	Border and land control	Institutional capacities	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4251	Luxembourg	fast track for investors - not implemented	2010	To improve competitiveness of the Luxembourg economy, the Minister for the Economy and Foreign trade wants to attract large fortunes to Luxembourg - bu proposing to set up a procedure VIP/fast-track for new potential residents identified as bringing an extraordinary appreciation (investments, revenues from taxes, etc) to the Luxembourg economy.  > This project has not been implemented.	EMN 2010: 25	N/A	N/A	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Investors, entrepreneurs and business people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
4252	Luxembourg	Tax benefits when employing foreign high skilled workers	2010	On December 31st 2010, a new system of taxing for expenditures and fees relating to the hiring of highly skilled and specialized workers from the international market was introduced - reimbursing part of the fees that the companies take on for hiring highly qualified specialized workers through income taxes. This will be applicable to highly skilled workers who settle in Luxembourg after December 31st 2010.  > As such, by tax relief, the recruitment of executives with highly specialized profiles would become less costly for the employers and the individuals concerned.	EMN 2010: 35	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
