4304	Luxembourg	International protection, victimization	2015	Asylum Law of 18 December 2015  introduces a medical assessment in order to reveal any signs of victimization	EMN  p.27	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Access to justice and political rights	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4305	Luxembourg	Asylum, legal assistance	2015	Asylum Law of 18 December 2015  states that legal assistance and representation shall be free of charge during the whole asylum procedure, including interviews and appeal proceedings.  However, free legal aid will not be granted if the applicant's appeal is considered to have no tangible prospect of success. Free legal assistance is also excluded for applicants who are no longer on the territory after having filed a subsequent application found inadmissible.	EMN  factsheet p.1	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Access to justice and political rights	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4306	Luxembourg	Asylum, appeal	2015	Asylum Law of 18 December 2015  reduced the deadline to lodge an appeal against a decisions of inadmissibility of an IP application and against a transfer decision under the Dublin Regulation were both reduced, from one month to 15 days from the date of notification	EMN  factsheet p.2	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Access to justice and political rights	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4307	Luxembourg	Asylum, decision	2015	Asylum Law of 18 December 2015  extends the deadline to render a decision by the Administrative Court from one month to two months	EMN   factsheet p.2	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Access to justice and political rights	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4308	Luxembourg	Asylum, detention	2015	Asylum Law of 18 December 2015  foresees that an applicant may be detained in order to establish or verify his/her identity or nationality, whereas before this was only allowed if the applicant refused to cooperate with the authorities in establishing their identity	EMN  factsheet p.2	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Detention	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4309	Luxembourg	Asylum, detention	2015	Asylum Law of 18 December 2015  states that the decision to detain can only be given after an individual consideration, where it appears necessary and only if other less coercive measures cannot be effectively applied. Less coercive measures include the obligation for applicants for international protection to report regularly to the offices of the Ministry, house arrest, and the obligation to deposit a financial guarantee	https://www.asylumlawdatabase.eu/en/content/country-profile-luxembourg	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Detention	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4310	Luxembourg	Vulnerable groups	2015	Asylum Law of 18th December 2015 - substantially enhances safeguards of vulnerable groups and unaccompanied minors by introducing special procedural guarantees.  a) a needs assessment  b) adequate specialised support c) a medical examination and prioritisation of the examination of applications from vulnerable persons	EMN  factsheet p.2	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Access to justice and political rights	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4311	Luxembourg	Economic Migration	2015	Ministerial Regulation of 13 May 2015  establishes the minimum salary requirement for highly qualified workers in order to apply for a Blue Card to be 71.946 euros  changes in immigration status and purpose of stay, fourth focused study 2015 Luxembourg	EMN p.19	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4312	Luxembourg	Economic Migration	2015	Government Council Decree of 22 May 2015  establishes the first list of professions in which the government considers there is a shortage of qualified workforce  changes in immigration status and purpose of stay, fourth focused study 2015 Luxembourg Most notably the sectors of mathematics, IT and web development	EMN p.19	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4313	Luxembourg	Integration, youth	2015	Amendments to the bill on Youth which foresees the introduction of a quality assurance system for the support of children aged 0 to 12 years in the educational and care facilities, and for young persons in the youth centres.  Such support aims to contribute to the integration of minors into the society and to promote equal opportunities, notably by favouring a social mix and by supporting minors with migration background to learn Luxembourgish language	EMN factsheet p.2	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to social benefits and socio-economic rights	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4314	Luxembourg	Integration, youth	2015	Introduction of the programme InSitu JOBS by the NGO CLAE - the programme offers a gateway towards professional insertion by targeting third-country nationals and beneficiaries of international protection looking for employment through individual counselling for the development of a professional project, thematic group workshops and access to various professional networks	EMN factsheet p.4	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Access to social benefits and socio-economic rights	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
