4318	Luxembourg	International Protection including Asylum	2016	Council of Government decision of 17 February 2016 - limits the maximum capacity of first arrival reception centres to 300 persons (previously 600). In case of absolute emergency, the government may nevertheless decide to temporarily increase the reception capacity	EMN  p.30	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Quota/target	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
4319	Luxembourg	International Protection including Asylum	2016	Reorganisation of the Asylum Unit of the Directorate of Immigration  - creation of a new section which is responsible for all Country of Origin Information related work. - Creation of geographical sections for interviewers and decision-makers.  The geographical sections are the following: Africa, North Africa, Western Balkan, Asia, and Middle East. Within these sections, each interviewer and decision-maker has a certain number of countries to address - Luxembourg pledged to resettle 190 people under the EU-Turkey Agreement of 18 March 2016 and an additional 20 people at the Geneva Conference on 30 March 2016 on with UNHCR	EMN  p.35, p.37	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Institutional capacities	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
4320	Luxembourg	Vulnerable groups	2016	Establishment of a mechanism for identifying signs of persecution - a medical expert from the National Health Laboratory with knowledge concerning the Istanbul Protocol can be consulted during the process of applying for international protection. Furthermore, doctors can be consulted to evaluate the special procedural guarantees that an applicant could need	EMN  p.38/39	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Institutional capacities	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
4321	Luxembourg	Economic Migration, third country nationals	2016	Law of 28 October 2016 transposing the EU Directive on the Recognition of Qualifications (Directive 2013/55/EU) entered into force  simplifies the procedure for the recognition of professional qualifications and creates a register for professional titles and a register for qualification titles  - The law enables qualified persons to practice their profession and is likely going to strengthen the labour force available in certain areas of the national labour market. - The law applies only to those third-country nationals who have a valid residence permit, who are beneficiaries of international protection and who applied for an authorisation of stay under the amended law of 29 August 2008 on the free movement of persons and immigration and who fulfil all the conditions for obtaining the requested authorisation subject to the recognition of professional qualifications for the pursuit of the activity concerned. By limiting the scope of application, Luxembourg intends to minimise any practice whereby third-country nationals without any economic link with Luxembourg would apply for recognition, in order to facilitate their access to another European market	EMN  p.19/20	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4322	Luxembourg	Work and travel agreements	2016	Work and Travel agreements with Australia and New Zealand - enables young residents of both countries aged between 18 and 30 to travel while working or studying in the partner country  o The agreement with New Zealand is limited to 50 residents per state and is foreseen to enter into force in April 2017, while the agreement with Australia entered into force on 1 January 2017 and is limited to 100 persons per state	EMN  p.20	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Specific categories	Specific nationalities	Australia and New Zealand	Less restrictive		
4323	Luxembourg	Work, digital	2016	Launch of the Digital Luxembourg initiative in October 2014  the aim is to strengthen and consolidate the long-term positioning of Luxembourg in the field of ICT and to place the country as a high tech centre of excellence in order to develop and train future ICT specialists and to attract talents from abroad	EMN  p.18/19	N/A	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Contextual elements	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
4324	Luxembourg	Students	2016	Law of 23 July 2016 on financial state aid for higher education  - increase of the semester amount for mobility grants from  1.000 to  1.225; -  increase of the semester amounts of bursaries based on social criteria of an average of 20,8%; - Students who are pursuing studies outside of the Member State that recognises the academic programme as covered by its higher education system will from now on be eligible for financial aid.	EMN  p.22	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Integration	Contextual elements	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4325	Luxembourg	Students	2016	Creation of an integration office at the University of Luxembourg to facilitate the entry into university of Applicants for International Protection (AIP) and Beneficiaries of International Protection (BIP) - if an AIP wishes to join the university, the candidate will take part in an individualised interview during which s/he will receive and outline of the universitys offer, an overview of candidates skills will be established and the university will offer orientation support to the candidate. AIPs will only be allowed to register in a study programme once they have received the status of BIP. While the candidate is still in the application procedure, s/he can follow courses as a free auditor	EMN  p.23	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to social benefits and socio-economic rights	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4326	Luxembourg	Visa, Managing Migration and Mobility	2016	Completion of the Visa Information System (VIS) roll-out in February 2016 - all stations connected to the VIS were operational and an offline procedure was developed in view of enrolling applications in case of a temporary disconnection to the main server	EMN  p.25	N/A									
4327	Luxembourg	Integration, marriage	2016	Law of 23 May 2016 on the recognition of marriage in Luxembourg  addresses the imbalance between the marriages celebrated in Luxembourg and the recognition of marriages celebrated abroad by stating that a marriage contracted in a foreign country shall be valid in the Grand Duchy of Luxembourg if it has been celebrated in the forms customary in the country and if both spouses fulfil either the substantive conditions required by the law applicable to their personal status subject to respect of international public policy, or if both spouses satisfy the substantive requirements of Luxembourgish law	EMN   p.25	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to social benefits and socio-economic rights	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4328	Luxembourg	Integration, same sex marriage	2016	Law of 23 May 2016 on the recognition of marriage in Luxembourg - recognises same-sex marriages celebrated abroad even in cases where the national law of one of the contracting parties prohibited this form of marriage, including those that had been contracted before such marriages were authorised in Luxembourg (i.e. prior to January 2015). The same applies to the recognition of adopted children by a same-sex couple	EMN   p.26	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to justice and political rights	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4329	Luxembourg	Integration	2016	Law of 29 March 2016  introduced the municipal register for physical persons. The municipal register simplifies the procedure for verifying whether a person has habitually resided in Luxembourg for five years, a requirement for the foreign residents registration on the electoral roll for municipal elections. Henceforth, a municipality has access to all residence information and the foreign resident must no longer provide residence certificates for all his or her past places of residence in Luxembourg	EMN   p.55	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4330	Luxembourg	Integration	2016	Law of 24 April 2016  opened up access to care service vouchers to cross-border workers from 5 September 2016 onwards.  These vouchers granting parents reduced prices for education and reception services in non-formal education were previously only available to Luxembourgish residents	EMN  p.41	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Integration	Access to social benefits and socio-economic rights	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
