4341	Luxembourg	Legal Migration and Mobility, salaried worker	2017	Law of 20 July 2017: put in place a simplified access to short-term visas with multiple entries for a range of professions, therefore simplifying the procedure for obtaining a salaried worker authorisation of stay for a number of highly-qualified or highly-specific professions (limited to 50 such authorisations per year).	EMN  factsheet p.2	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4342	Luxembourg	Legal Migration and Mobility, students	2017	Law of 20 July 2017: foresaw that students from both countries can stay in the other country for two years to gain a first professional experience.  - regulated the exchange of young professionals who wish to gain a first work experience in either state (limited to ten per year).	EMN  factsheet p.3	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	International students	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4343	Luxembourg	Entry and stay for third-country nationals	2017	Law of 8 March 2017  transposes Directive 2014/66/EU of 15 May 2014 establishing the conditions of entry and stay for third-country nationals within the framework of an intra-corporate temporary transfer: - managers or specialists who have worked at the company or corporation for an uninterrupted period of three to twelve months directly preceding the application as well as trainee employees, who have worked at the company for an uninterrupted period directly preceding the application of three to six months are eligible to apply for an authorisation of stay ICT of at most three years (one year for trainee employees). Regarding ICT residence permits delivered by another member state, they will be authorised to work in Luxembourg for a duration of no more than 90 days within a period of 180 days under a number of conditions, and for a period that exceeds 90 days if they are first issued a mobile ICT residence permit	EMN  2016 p.13	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4344	Luxembourg	Seasonal Workers Directive (Directive 2014/36/EU), third country nationals	2017	Law of 8 March 2017  transposes the Seasonal Workers Directive (Directive 2014/36/EU) into national legislation  - A third-country national who legally resides in a third-country and who can produce a working contract for seasonal work, proof of appropriate accommodation and health insurance, will be issued a work authorisation and, if needed, a short-term visa for seasonal work, for a maximum period of 90 days. If the seasonal work exceeds 90 days, the worker will be issued an authorisation of stay seasonal worker under the same conditions. The duration of seasonal work cannot exceed five months in a period of 12 months	EMN  report 2016 p.14	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4345	Luxembourg	Entry and stay for third-country nationals, investment	2017	Law of 8 March 2017  introduces an authorisation of stay of three years (renewable for three years if conditions remain fulfilled) for investors who fulfil one of the following conditions  - Invest at least  500.000 in an existing commercial, artisanal or industrial company based in Luxembourg and commit to maintain the investment and the level of employment for at least five years - Invest at least  500.000 in a commercial, artisanal or industrial company yet to be created, this including the creation of five jobs within three years of having founded the company - Invest at least  3 million in an investment structure that is already in existence or yet to be created in Luxembourg, which has an appropriate substance (targeting family office structures) - Invest at least  20 million as a deposit in a financial institution established in Luxembourg, committing to maintain this investment for at least five years (targeting high net worth individuals)	EMN  2016 report p.15	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Investors, entrepreneurs and business people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4346	Luxembourg	'European Blue Card' residence permit	2017	Law of 8 March 2017  increased the period of validity of the 'European Blue Card' residence permit from two to four years (maximum duration allowed by the directive)	EMN  report 2016 p.17	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4347	Luxembourg	Third country nationals, salaried worker	2017	Law of 8 March 2017  introduced a mechanism for continuation of activity, which allows registered entities situated in a third country to continue their activities on Luxembourgish territory if a major incident (geopolitical incident, data processing incident or natural disaster) occurred in the country of origin. In case of a major incident, the TCN workers of the registered entity will receive a residence permit of the category salaried worker, valid for one year at most and renewable for one year upon request, if they can prove that they have health insurance and appropriate accommodation  o If the entity establishes itself permanently in Luxembourg, the TCN can apply for a salaried worker or highly qualified worker authorisation of stay. The authorisation of stay could be withdrawn once the situation in the country of origin has normalised and the continuation of activity from Luxembourg is no longer required	EMN report 2016 p.17	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4348	Luxembourg	Third country nationals, corporate officer of a company with a permit	2017	Law of 8 March 2017  detailed the conditions under which a TCN corporate officer (mandataire social) of a company for which s/he can hold a business permit or ministerial approval and with which s/he has a working contact, has the right to apply for an authorisation of stay - If the corporate officer has a subordinate relationship to his or her employer, s/he has the right to apply for a salaried worker or European Blue Card authorisation of stay (ICT excluded).79 If such a link of subordination cannot be established, the TCNs eligibility for an independent worker authorisation of stay will be considered.80 For the corporate officer to be eligible for any of the mentioned categories, the company must also fulfil a number of conditions.	EMN report 2016 p.18	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4349	Luxembourg	social dumping and labour exploitation of third-country nationals	2017	Law of 8 March 2017  makes efforts to avoid social dumping and labour exploitation of third-country nationals -  - makes it possible to refuse to renew or to withdraw an Intra-Corporate Transferee residence permit in case the employer has been sanctioned for violations of the provisions of the Labour Code on the prohibition of illegal employment of irregular staying TCNs or if s/he has failed to fulfil his legal obligations in the field of social security, taxation, labour rights or working conditions	EMN report 2016 p.20/21	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Other sanctions	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4350	Luxembourg	refuse an application of stay for seasonal work or to withdraw the work permit	2017	Law of 8 March 2017: Makes it possible to refuse an application of stay for seasonal work or to withdraw the work permit and the residence permit 'seasonal worker' in case the employer has been penalised for infringements of the provisions of the Labour Code on the prohibition of illegal employment and employment of illegally staying TCNs or if s/he has failed to fulfil his or her legal obligations in the field of social security, taxation, labour rights or working conditions	EMN report 2016 p.20/22	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Other sanctions	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4351	Luxembourg	Students	2017	Law of 8 March 2017  authorised students to change their status to salaried worker or independent worker under a number of conditions and thus to integrate into the labour market permanently	EMN report 2016 p.21	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Access to social benefits and socio-economic rights	International students	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4352	Luxembourg	a residence permit for medical treatment	2017	Law of 8 March 2017  provides that individuals holding a residence permit for medical treatment are not authorised to change status, which was not the case previously. Likewise, people with a residence permit in the categories pupil, trainee, volunteer, au pair and the new category of seasonal worker are not authorised to change status during stay   The legislator wanted to avoid a circumvention of the conditions for the admission of 'regular' salaried workers.	EMN report 2016 p.23	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4353	Luxembourg	family reunification, third country national	2017	Law of 8 March 2017 - removed the one-year waiting period that previously applied to third-country national sponsors wishing to apply for family reunification. The sponsor's spouse, registered partner or minor child can now join the sponsor directly after hislher residence permit has been granted. However, the oneyear condition remained for the ascendants of the sponsors.	EMN   factsheet p.2	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4354	Luxembourg	family reunification, third country national	2017	Law of 8 March 2017 - provides for immediate family reunification of third-country national family members with their sponsors that fulfil the conditions of appropriate accommodation, health insurance and sufficient, regular and stable resources, fixed by law	EMN   2016 factsheet p.2	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
