4365	Luxembourg	multi-annual national action plan on integration	2017	Approval to elaborate a new multi-annual national action plan on integration with the aim to facilitate the integration of foreigners in September 2017  factsheet p.3. Info campaign: A national information and awareness raising campaign was launched by the Ministry of Family and integration - its aim was to motivate the foreign population to register for the electoral roll and to participate in municipal elections held on 8 October 2017	EMN  factsheet p.3	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Integration	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
4366	Luxembourg	Integration, international protection	2017	Set up of a cell specifically dedicated to beneficiaries of international protection by Luxembourgs National Employment Agency (ADEM) in February 2017  aims to provide employers with information regarding job applications and evaluations of the competences of beneficiaries of international protection	EMN  factsheet p.3	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Integration	Institutional capacities	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
4367	Luxembourg	Guided Integration Trail	2017	Approval of the Guided Integration Trail in March 2017 - this multidisciplinary package of measures consists of both a language and a civic component. The package is split into three phases, accompanying applicants and beneficiaries of international protection through the different phases of integration in reception facilities, aiming to both empower and support them in developing their life journey. The participation in the project is compulsory for adult applicants.	EMN  factsheet p.3	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Integration	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
4368	Luxembourg	Detention, UAM	2017	The Law of 8 March 2017 amending the Law on the Detention Centre extended the permitted period of detention of adults and families with children from 72 hours to seven days. A draft bill adopted by the Council of Governments introduced further modifications. The most significant one concerned minors and the establishment of a Commission to evaluate the best interest of the child on an individual basis when deciding on the return of an unaccompanied minor	EMN	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Detention	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4369	Luxembourg	Students and Researchers Directive	2018	Law of 1 August 2018 - transposed the Students and Researchers Directive ((EU) 2016/801) into national legislation. Students and researchers are now issued a private life residence permit to look for a job or start a business after successfully completing their master's or doctoral studies. The permit is valid for a maximum of 9 months (non-renewable). In the event that the third-country national finds a job, a residence permit for a salaried worker is issued.	EMN  p.17	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	International students	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4370	Luxembourg	Students and Researchers Directive	2018	Law of 1 August 2018 - the permitted number of weekly working hours which a student from a third country is allowed to workwas increased from 10 to 15 hours	EMN  p.23	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	International students	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4371	Luxembourg	Students and Researchers Directive	2018	Law of 1 August 2018 - students and researchers who follow an EU or multilateral programme that includes mobility measures will no longer have to introduce a new application for authorisation of stay, but must notify the authorities of the first Member State and the ministry in charge of Immigration and may stay and study in Luxembourg for up to 360 days	EMN  p.23	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	International students	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4372	Luxembourg	Students and Researchers Directive, residence permit	2018	Law of 1 August 2018  introduces a 'trainee' residence permit valid for a maximum of six month for applicants who provide proof that they have obtained, in the two years preceding the date of the application, an evidence of formal qualification recognised in Luxembourg, that they will have sufficient resources during the planned stay to cover their living expenses (as well as the costs of return) and that they are covered by private health insurance)	EMN  p.26	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Specific categories	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4373	Luxembourg	Students and Researchers Directive, family reunification	2018	Law of 1 August 2018  facilitates family reunification for researchers staying in Luxembourg in the context of short- or long-term mobility	EMN  p. 27	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4374	Luxembourg	Young au-pairs	2018	Law of 1 August 2018 updated the rules governing the reception of young au-pairs: an au pair must have no family ties up to the fourth degree inclusive with the members of the host family in order to avoid any potential for abuse; the law reduced the working time spent by au pairs on family chores from 30 hours to 25 hours on average over a period of one month; host family must now transfer a fixed amount to the au pair per month, corresponding to one fifth of the minimum social wage (no longer one quarter of the minimum social wage), as pocket money, irrespective of periods of inactivity	EMN   p.18	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Specific categories	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4375	Luxembourg	Legal Migration, students and researchers	2018	Grand Ducal Regulation of 1st August 2018  to be eligible for a private life residence permit, students and researchers must prove that they have monthly resources corresponding to at least 80% of the guaranteed minimum income (students) and of the minimum social wage of qualified employees (researchers)	EMN  p.24	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	International students	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
