4395	Luxembourg	legal migration,  working holiday agreement with Canada	2019	Signing of a working holiday agreement with Canada on 3 July 2019 - people of Luxembourgish or Canadian nationality between the ages of 18 and 30 to live and work in the other country for the duration of a year  The aim of this programme is to promote international exchanges of young people and to deepen their linguistic and cultural exchange.	EMN  p.23	Fine-tuning change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Specific categories	Specific nationalities	Canada	Less restrictive		
4396	Luxembourg	legal migration, vocational training	2019	Law of 12 July 2019 - introduces technical adaptations to improve sustainably the quality of vocational training for apprentices and trainees: Grades up to 60 points are gradually being reintroduced from 2019-20 for all three vocational qualifications - training duration may be extended by one year if needed by the learners; a second extension of the apprenticeship contract for a maximum period of one year may be granted with the consent of the apprentice and the training company - establishes an on-the-job vocational training model; this will allow employees without a certification for the trade/profession they are practising to complete their training in parallel to their job, and obtain a diploma.	https://www.cedefop.europa.eu/en/news-and-press/news/luxembourg-updated-labour-code-and-law-reforming-vocational-training	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Low-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4397	Luxembourg	British citizens living in Luxembourg (Brexit)	2019	Law of 8 April 2019 - lays out a legal basis on how to deal with British citizens living in Luxembourg in the event of both a deal or no-deal Brexit   Deal: - British citizens and their family members, who are in possession of a registration certificate or a residence card must apply for a new document at the latest by the end of the transition period, as a replacement of the certificate or card - British citizens and their family members who arrive in Luxembourg during the transition period must request a residence document. With this document, they will be able to apply for the replacement document. -British citizens and their family members benefiting from permanent residency before the end of the transitional period will receive a residence document, as a replacement of a permanent registration certificate, respectively the permanent residence card. - British citizens and their family members will maintain the same rights as other EU citizens under the Withdrawal Agreement with regards to the access to the labour market, the recognition of academic and professional diplomas, the access to financial aid for higher education and the access to jobs in the public service	EMN p.24-27	Fine-tuning change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Specific categories	Specific nationalities	UK	Less restrictive	To check if correct and relevant	
