4653	Netherlands	recruitment of workers for specific industries	1990	Decision to recruit a limited number of foreign workers for the metallurgical industry and seasonal work in the Dutch bulb industry	SOPEMI 1991: 58	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Recruitment/assisted migration programmes	Low-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4654	Netherlands	asylum seekers with low chance of recognition to wait in detention while case is tested	1990	Stricter policy on asylum seekers - stipulated that if an asylum seeker has a very slight chance of being recognised as political refugees, he has to wait in detention while his case is legally tested > This was mainly directed towards Eastern European Asylum seekers	SOPEMI 1991: 58	Major change	National policy	Border and land control	Detention	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4655	Netherlands	recognition of dual nationality	1991	Nationality Act of 1985 was amended in December 1991 - recognizing dual nationality and hence repealing the renunciation requirement  > The renunciation requirement was reintroduced in 1997 and dual nationality restricted to specific cases	SOPEMI 1995: 109; Van Oers et al 2013: 1	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4656	Netherlands	employers to pay expulsion cost	1991	New employer sanctions introduced - to make employers liable for the cost of expulsion of the foreigners concerned.	Mayda 2004	Mid-level change	National policy	Border and land control	Employer liabilities	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4657	Netherlands	temporary humanitarian residence permit for tolerated asylum seekers	1992	Revision of the 1965 Aliens Act - introduces a third refugee status through the 'gedoogdenregeling' (toleration regulation): next to the A-status and the vtv-hum or C-status (the B-status has been abolished in 1988), persons can stay as long as the situation in their home country prohibits return. > As of 1994, this status is called vvtv (voorlopige vergunning tot verblijf humanitair) or temporary humanitarian residence permit. This status foresees that asylum seekers who cannot be repatriated but are not recognizes as refugees will get a 'provisional residence permit' if they withdraw their request for asylum, which is valid for one year, twice renewable, but which does not allow access to the labour market and only limited access to the educational system. After three years of residence, the holder of a provisional residence permit is entitled to a regular residence permit.	SOPEMI 1992: 72; Mayda 2004	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4658	Netherlands	fast track procedures for manifestly unfounded asylum claims	1992	Revision of the 1965 Aliens Act - allows for the acceleration of legal procedures when asylum claims are considered to be manifestly unfounded and/or unacceptable	SOPEMI 1995: 110;  SOPEMI 1997: 136	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4659	Netherlands	easier detention for unsuccessful asylum seekers	1992	Revision of the 1965 Aliens Act - facilitates the procedure for the detention of unsuccessful asylum seekers awaiting deportation.	SOPEMI 1995: 110;  SOPEMI 1997: 136	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Border and land control	Detention	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4660	Netherlands	discussion on family reunification restrictions	1992	Discussions about further restrictions on family reunification have been begun by the Dutch government (October 1992), but no detailed proposals have been made.	SOPEMI 1994: 87	N/A	N/A	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
4661	Netherlands	restriction of family reunification	1993	Tightening of family reunification criteria -  Refugees, holders of residence permits and Dutch citizens are not any more exempted from the income requirements: They now have to earn 70 percent of social welfare level to to bring along their spouse and/or children. Also, if wished, foreigners must bring their family members within three years after the requirements for family reunification have been met. After these three years, family reunification will no longer be possible. > Only those older than 57,5 years old, permanently disabled, or single parents taking care of children under five years old were still automatically exempted from the income requirement.  In cases of family formation, the applicant would have to reside in the Netherlands for at least three years before he could request the entry of a foreign marriage partner.	SOPEMI 1995: 110; SOPEMI 1997: 136; Bonjour 2009: 361	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4662	Netherlands	New ethnic minority policy plan	1993	In September, the Dutch ethnic minorities policy was presented - recognizing as target groupS the following groups: Mediterranean workers, their families and descendants originating principally from Turkey and Morocco; immigrants from Surinam, the Netherlands Antilles and the Moluccas, together with their descendants; political refugees (not asylum seekers); Gypsies; nomads of Dutch nationality.	SOPEMI 1995: 109	N/A	N/A	Integration	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	All migrants	Specific nationalities	See policy measure	N/A		
4663	Netherlands	introduction of safe countries	1994	In 1994, new procedures were introduced for asylum applications - such as the principle of 'safe countries' in the asylum determination procedure > Allows authorities to reject asylum seekers on the basis that they have come from what is considered to be a safe country, whether this is their country of origin or otherwise. In addition, new asylum centres were opened at the Belgian and German borders to immediately reject applications coming from any safe country.	SOPEMI 1997: 136	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	Those people that transit or originate from a country on the safe third country/country of origin list	More restrictive		
4664	Netherlands	new procedures for asylum applications	1994	In 1994, new procedures were introduced for asylum applications - the 'AC-procedure' (aanmeldcentrum-procedure) whereby cases are separated between those that can be clarified within  48 working hours and those that need more extensive research. The latter are then reviewed in the 'OC-procedure' (opvangcentrum-procedure) in which a decision has to be taken (in principle) within 6 months.	ICMPD 2009b: 151-153	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Change in restrictiveness cannot be assessed		
4665	Netherlands	blue card for specific family members abolished	1994	In January 1994, the blue card or 10-lid-2 status was abolished - this status granted residency rights to children of labour migrants, Dutch citizens and refugees after stay of 1 year and protected them from expulsion > The status had been introduced in 1967	Bonjour 2009: 361	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Access to permanent residency	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4666	Netherlands	new identification requirements for access to social security	1994	June Law on Identification - introduced identification requirements in 25 different laws (for example fiscal and social security laws) and determined what kind of identification papers were legally accepted, herewith making it more difficult for undocumented migrants to access to social security > All job seekers need a tax and social security number; these numbers will no longer be issued without a valid residence permit. Hence, it becomes impossible to obtain a social security number if one does not have a regular residence status.	SOPEMI 1997: 136;  SOPEMI 1996: 136	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to social benefits and socio-economic rights	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4667	Netherlands	new identification requirements for access to work	1994	June Law on Identification - introduced identification requirements in 25 different laws and determined what kind of identification papers were legally accepted by employers, herewith restricting illegal labour > According to identification requirements since 1994, employers are obliged to keep copies of the passports of their employees within the wages administration. Each missing copy and each copy of an unvalid passport can be fined by a special assessment.	SOPEMI 1997: 136	Major change	National policy	Border and land control	Employer liabilities	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4668	Netherlands	law to prevent and forbid marriages of convenience	1994	Law on the Prevention of Marriages of Convenience (Wet Voorkoming Schijnhuwelijken) - required that each couple with at least one foreign partner that wanted to get married or have their marriage registered in the Netherlands, should obtain a declaration from the Immigration Service stating whether there were grounds to suspect a marriage of convenience.  > A list of objective indications was established to determine the sham character of a marriage, such as the residential status of the foreign partner, age difference, knowledge of each others language and duration of the relationship. If convinced that it was sham, the civil servant at the registrars office could refuse to conclude or register the marriage.	http://research.icmpd.org/fileadmin/Research-Website/Project_material/NODE/Family_Migration_Pol_NL_final_01.pdf [accessed on 17.06.2013]	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4669	Netherlands	provisional residence permit needed to apply for real residence permit	1994	Amendment to the 1965 Aliens Act - made a 'provisional residence permit' (machtiging tot voorlopig verblijf or MVV) abroad a requirement for being granted a residence permit (on family or labour grounds)  > The government had already (in 1972 and in 1980) tried to enact this, but the court had held that a residence permit should be denied just because a stranger does not have an MVV. Only when the MVV requirement was included in the Aliens Act it became a hard requirement.	Bonjour 2009: 215-216	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4670	Netherlands	regularisation mechanism for long term irregular migrants introduced	1995	In 1995 a permanent regularisation mechanism, the white illegal scheme ('witte illegalenregeling') was introduced - irregular foreigners who could prove they had resided and worked (legally) for six years in the netherlands could apply for regularisation.  > The measure was repealed in 2003. The  main target groups were illegally resident workers who were formally employed and had a social security number and thus the regularisation mechanism can be interpreted as a response to a mismatch between admission procedures and employment policies.	Kraler 2009: 27; https://zoek.officielebekendmakingen.nl/stcrt-1995-53-p14-SC2150.html [accessed on 24.09.2013]	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Regularisation	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4671	Netherlands	three year limit for family reunification abolished	1995	In 1995, the three year time limit for family reunficiation ('omgekeerde wachttijd', in Dutch debates) was abolished - because it was contrary to the European Resolution on Harmonisation of family migration policy. Family reunification is therefore open beyond three years after the income requirements have been met.  > This reversed the 1993 reform.	Bonjour 2011	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4672	Netherlands	priority rule of dutch labour market reinforced	1995	Aliens Employment Actof 1 September 1995 (WAV - Wet Arbeid Vreemdelingen) replaced the 1979 Foreign Workers Employment Act (WABW) - retaining as most important ground for refusal of employment permits the employment situation on the Dutch labour market (priority rule).  > The Dutch Aliens Police became the authority which will add a note to the residence permit of a foreigner stating that he/she is free (or not) to take up employment. The concept of 'an employer' was also enlarged to oblige more employers (in particular the self-employed) to apply for employment permits for foreigners. The strict admission policy for migrant workers was strengthened in 1995 with the Aliens Employment Act. They wanted to avoid the influx of low-skilled workers as much as possible.	SOPEMI 1997: 136	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4673	Netherlands	Schengen entered into force	1995	Schengen Agreement signed in 1985, entered into force in 1995 - removing all border controls while attempting to strengthen the common external frontier, it allowed the free movement of workers in the EU	Mayda 2004: 8	Major change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Border and land control	Free mobility rights/agreements	All	EU citizens	EU member states at that time	Less restrictive		
4674	Netherlands	tightening of dual nationality rule	1997	1985 Nationality Act was amended - restricting dual nationality to individuals whose countries of origin do not authorise them to relinquish their nationality or who have difficulty in doing so.	SOPEMI 1999: 181	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4675	Netherlands	new controls on entry of asylum seekers	1997	In November, the government increased control on the entry of asylum seekers - appointing specific staff in embassies, increasing the use of fingerprinting as a means of checking identity and intensification of behind-border controls, especially with regard to air travel (e.g. extension of pre-boarding checks on certain flights).	SOPEMI 1999: 182	Minor change	National policy	Border and land control	Surveillance technology/control powers	All	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4676	Netherlands	pilot return project for Angola, Erythrea, Ethopia and Surinam	1997	The government created pilot projects encouraging voluntary return of legal immigrants and rejected asylum seekers to Angola, Erythrea and Ethiopia, as well as Surinam.	SOPEMI 1999: 182	Mid-level change	National policy	Exit	Reintegration/return programmes	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	Specific nationalities	Angola, Erythrea, Ethiopia, Surinam	More restrictive		
4677	Netherlands	Dublin Convention entered into force	1997	The Dublin Convention entered into force on 1 September 1997 (signed on 15 June 1990) - determining the state responsible for asylum determination within Europe	Vink 2012	Major change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4678	Netherlands	mandatory integration classes created	1998	Law on the civic integration of newcomers (Wet Inburgering Nieuwkomers, WIN) came into effect in 1998 - requiring all new immigrants with the exception of students and temporary workers  to take 600 hours of language and societal orientation classes, which were followed by assistance in starting an education or finding employment. The eligibility of new immigrants to social welfare was made conditional to the participation in integration programmes: If immigrants did not comply, their social security could be cut or they could be fined.  > The program was meant to help immigrants find their way in Dutch society and become self-supporting. Citizens of the European Union, the EEA17, Switzerland and the United States who came for reasons other than marriage or family reunification were exempt from the obligation.  The Netherlands was the first country to introduce such a mandatory program, and several countries have since followed its lead.	SOPEMI 1997: 136; Focus Migration 2007: 6; https://zoek.officielebekendmakingen.nl/stb-1998-261.html [accessed on 23.09.2013]	Major change	National policy	Integration	Language, housing and cultural integration programmes	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4679	Netherlands	special staff to deal with Afghan and Iraqi asylum seekers	1998	Creation of task force to deal with asylum applications from Afghanistan and Iraq > Given the high number of asylum seekers from Afghanistan and Iraq, information bureaux were set up in both countries in 1998. Special units have also been set up to deal exclusively with applications from nationals of these countries.	SOPEMI 2001: 231	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Institutional capacities	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	Specific nationalities	Afghanistan, Iraq	Change in restrictiveness cannot be assessed		
4680	Netherlands	temporary stay for asylum seekers from specific countries withdrawn	1998	The 1992 VVTV policy was withdrawn - this policy granted temporary stay to tolerated asylum seekers from specific countries who could not be sent back > This concerned people from Liberia, northern Sudan, certain Somalis, Sri Lankan Tamils, Iraqis and Afghans arriving via Pakistan. The aim was to reduce the number of asylum applications in 1999.	SOPEMI 2001: 231	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	Specific nationalities	Liberia, northern Sudan, certain Somalis, Sri Lankan Tamils, Iraqis and Afghans arriving via Pakistan.	More restrictive		
4681	Netherlands	one-time regularisation of long term illegal migrants	1999	In 1999, the  'burgemeesterregeling' introduced a one-time regularisation - During two months, irregular foreigners who had been in the Netherlands since January 1992 and had a social security number could apply for regularisation.  > Their application was evaluated according to their integration, family situation, income. A committee of mayors gave an advice on each case, the Deputy Minister decided.	COE 2007	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Regularisation	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4682	Netherlands	asylum applications without identity documents will not be accepted	1999	Feburary 1 law on people without identity papers - stipulates that asylum applications from people without papers and who cannot justify their loss will not be accepted.	SOPEMI 2001: 231	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4683	Netherlands	asylum applications without identity documents expelled immediately	1999	Feburary 1 law on people without identity papers - stipulates that asylum seekers who have deliberately destroyed their papers may be turned back within 24 hours.	SOPEMI 2001: 231	Major change	National policy	Exit	Expulsion	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4684	Netherlands	new return programme for unemployed over 45	1999	15 June Act on the return of immigrants to their country of origin - offering long-term unemployed over 45 years of age a monthly allowance if they return to their country of origin.  > Other improvements concern a) a supplementary medical insurance scheme; b) payment of individual allowances following divorce; c) financial arrangements for orphans until they reach their majority; d) a special visa to facilitate visits to family members remaining in the Netherlands; e) index-linked monthly allowances; f) optional return to the Netherlands in the year following initial voluntary return to the country of origin; g) the inclusion of EU nationals from former source countries (Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal); and h) introduction of a special arrangement for the disabled who did not apply for an allowance under the previous system.	SOPEMI 2001: 231	Mid-level change	National policy	Exit	Reintegration/return programmes	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4685	Netherlands	conditional independent residency rights for family members	2000	Introduction for family migrants of an independent right of residence after 3 years of residence and 3 years of marriage (no income req)	Bonjour 2009: 361	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4686	Netherlands	restructuring of asylum system	2001	Aliens Act of April 2001 (replacing the 1965 Act and its 1994 amendment) - introduced the Improved Asylum Procedure, which shortened the procedures and simplified the previous system by replacing the three existing categories of asylum by only one asylum status: the temporary (fixed-term) residence permit.  > After three years under the status, asylum seekers are eligible for a residence permit of an indefinite term.	SOPEMI 2005: 240, 241; Bonjour 2009: 361	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4687	Netherlands	work allowed for asylum seekers	2001	Aliens Act of April 2001 (replacing the 1965 Act and its 1994 amendment) - allowed all asylum seekers with the temporary residence permit to  work	SOPEMI 2005: 240, 241; Bonjour 2009: 361	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Work visa/permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	No change		
4688	Netherlands	review of refugees' benefits entitlement	2001	Aliens Act of April 2001 (replacing the 1965 Act and its 1994 amendment) - introduced the same social benefits for all asylum seekers  > In its place, only one asylum status is possible, granting the same temporary (fixed-term) residence permit and entitlements to all refugees: to be eligible for student financing and subsidised accommodation.	SOPEMI 2005: 240, 241; Bonjour 2009: 361	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to social benefits and socio-economic rights	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Change in restrictiveness cannot be assessed		
4689	Netherlands	abolishment of main appeal procedures for asylum seekers	2001	Aliens Act of April 2001 (replacing the 1965 Act and its 1994 amendment) - abolished the objection procedure, which allowed asylum seekers with refused applications to request a review of their case  > Also, rejected applicants can no longer take legal action against a housing eviction or an expulsion order, as in the past.  Now, asylum seekers can make an appeal only to the Council of State, which is required to make a decision within six months.	SOPEMI 2005: 240, 241; Bonjour 2009: 361	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Access to justice and political rights	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4690	Netherlands	stricter expulsion of rejected asylum seekers	2001	Aliens Act of April 2001 (replacing the 1965 Act and its 1994 amendment) - introduced a more restrictive expulsion system for rejected asylum applications  > Asylum seekers are under the obligation to leave the Netherlands within a given period of time and the continued use of reception facilities is forbidden.	SOPEMI 2005: 240, 241; Bonjour 2009: 361	Mid-level change	National policy	Exit	Expulsion	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4691	Netherlands	higher income requirements for family reunification	2001	Aliens Act of April 2001 (replacing the 1965 Act and its 1994 amendment) - tightened the income requirements further to 100% of the welfare level for all family migration applicants > The major aim was to discourage immigration for the purpose of family formation, especially from Turkey and Morocco, and to prevent fake marriages. A Dutch citizen or resident must have an income of at least 100% of the minimum family income (or 120% in case of non-permanent residents), an employment contract for at least one year and be at least 21 years of age.	SOPEMI 2005: 240, 241; Bonjour 2009: 361; Focus Migration 2007: 6	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4692	Netherlands	minister for integration and immigration created	2002	After the elections, the post of minister for integration and immigration was created	MPI 2007	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Institutional capacities	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Change in restrictiveness cannot be assessed		
4693	Netherlands	creation of language and citizenship test	2003	1985 Nationality Act was amended on April 1 - introducing stricter residence requirements,  a ceremony celebrating the moment of acquiring Dutch nationality and a naturalisation test showing proficiency in the Dutch language and understanding of the Netherlands, and Dutch institutions and culture.	SOPEMI 2005: 240, 241; Bonjour 2009: 361	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4694	Netherlands	abolished immediate naturalisation of children recognized by NL citizen	2003	1985 Nationality Act was amended - abolishing the practice to immediately grant citizenship to children aged under seven who are recognised by a Dutch citizen > This was repealed in 2009	SOPEMI 2011: 304	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4695	Netherlands	creation of deportation centers	2003	In June 2003, two deportation centres were opened - where illegal immigrants and rejected asylum seekers will be detained pending expulsion.  > These two centres house up to 300 persons and will be expanded to hold 600. Also, the government announced to double its deportation effort	SOPEMI 2005: 240-1; Bonjour 2009: 361	Major change	National policy	Exit	Institutional capacities	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4696	Netherlands	Permanent regularisation scheme abolished	2003	The permanent regularisation scheme  of unauthorized migrant workers was abolished in 2003 after a decade	Brick MPI 2011: 6	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Regularisation	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4697	Netherlands	one-time regularisation of asylum seekers	2003	Amnesty - a one-off measure available until December 2003 will allow certain asylum seekers, whose cases have been under consideration since May 1998, to be granted a permanent residence permit.  > It is anticipated that about 2 200 people will benefit. These persons are defined as having lived in the Netherlands for more than five years, awaiting a decision on their cases. [Additional conditions, such as a language requirement, were debated but apparently not implemented]	SOPEMI 2005: 241	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Regularisation	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4698	Netherlands	proposal for new integration measures	2003	The government proposed to reform the integration measures - so that newcomers should already have learnt Dutch and acquired knowledge of Dutch society while still in their country of origin; they should pay for the costs of integration projects (about  6 000), with only partial reimbursement possible; a broader range of educational institutions should also be able to offer integration courses.  > This was implemented in 2006 and 2007. In the original proposals and in the original WI, the responsibility of municipalities was much reduced: they were responsible only for providing integration programmes to specific target groups (housewives, refugees, religious ministers, and unemployed).  The new proposal gives municipalities the responsibility for the provision of the integration programme without being able to control the educational course a migrant chooses to follow.	SOPEMI 2005: 241	N/A	N/A	Integration	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
4699	Netherlands	Memorandum on return migration proposes better border control and expulsion mechanisms	2003	Memorandum on Return Migration published in late 2003 by the Minister of Immigration and Integration - is mainly a continuation of the past but puts greater emphasis on effective implementation of the measures and on the final stage of the migration policy cycle, namely the expulsion policy.  > It proposed to improve border control, and to enforce the responsibilities of transporters to remove foreigners who have been intercepted at the border. Also, if deportation is possible, they are detained either in a deportation centre, or a departure centre, where they can stay for eight weeks, after which, it is their own responsibility to leave the country.	SOPEMI 2006: 87-88	N/A	N/A	Exit	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
4700	Netherlands	expulsion of rejected asylum seekers who entered prior to april 2001	2004	In January 2004, the government announced that asylum seekers who entered under the old Aliens Act (prior to 1 April 2001) and unconditionally do not qualify for a residence permit, shall be deported.  > The Minister for Immigration and Integration states that it concerns a group of approximately 26,000 people. This group of people shall have to leave the country if they have exhausted all legal remedies.	EMN 2005: 20	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Exit	Expulsion	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4701	Netherlands	2004 enlargement restrictions for labour market access	2004	2004 EU enlargement - the Netherlands introduced transitional restrictions to the labour market access of the 8 new EU MS by creating a numerical limit of 22 000 per year (until 2007) and by creating a list of occupations for which there is considered to exist an acute labour shortage is published every 3 months. > Citizens of new member countries can then be recruited without the need of an individual labour market test and can benefit from facilitated administrative procedures.	SOPEMI 2006: 200; SOPEMI 2007: 268; SOPEMI 2008: 264	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	All migrant workers	EU citizens	Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, Poland, Slovakia and Slovenia	Less restrictive		
4702	Netherlands	Creation of scheme for high-skilled migrants	2004	Highly skilled migration scheme introduced on 1 October 2004 - aiming at stimulating highly qualified labour immigration > Labour migrants who are able to earn more than EUR 45 000 (for immigrants under 30 years of age the wage criterion is EUR 32 600) in the Dutch labour market, are eligible for residence permits for a maximum of five years and can work without a work permit. After five years of residence, they can obtain a permanent residence permit.	SOPEMI 2006: 78; De Lange 2008: 98	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4703	Netherlands	Temporary humanitarian residence extended to five years	2004	Amendment of the 2001 Aliens Act - extends the temporary residence for humanitarian reasons from three years to five years.	SOPEMI 2006: 84	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4704	Netherlands	no fast track any more for child asylum seekers	2004	Amendment of the 2001 Aliens Act - claims of solitary asylum seekers under the age of twelve are no longer assessed by the accelerated procedure.	SOPEMI 2006: 84	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4705	Netherlands	income requirement for family reunification increased	2004	Family reunification restricted on November 1 - by introducing a distinction between family reunification and family formation. While income and age limits remained the same for family reunification (100%, 18), it was raised to 120% and 21 years old for family formation. > This measure was overruled by the EU Court of Justice in 2010. Now, 100% minimum wage and 21 years minimum age apply to all family migrants.	Bonjour 2009: 362	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4706	Netherlands	requirement of all-time identification of individuals	2004	Law on Extended Compulsory Identification (Wet op de Uitgebreide identificatie plicht, WUIP) was adopted in 2004 - stipulating that everyone must be able to show ID at all times to police officers.	https://zoek.officielebekendmakingen.nl/stb-2004-583.html [accessed on 24.09.2013]	Major change	National policy	Border and land control	Surveillance technology/control powers	All	All	N/A	More restrictive		
4707	Netherlands	uninfluential but positive report on integration	2004	In 2003 a temporary parliamentary committee was installed to investigate the effects of integration policies of the past thirty years - The unofficial goal was to investigate what went wrong. In January 2004 the committee presented its report entitled Bruggen bouwen (Building Bridges). Its main conclusion was that many immigrants had integrated successfully despite the integration policies. The committee stated that newcomers should achieve proficiency in Dutch and observe the norms and values as laid down in laws, but it also recommended that discrimination and prejudice among allochtonen and autochtonen alike should be combatted. Unfortunately, not much was done with the report.	Focus Migration 2007: 6	N/A	N/A	Integration	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
4708	Netherlands	Theo van Gogh murder and ensuing political debate	2004	In November 2004, a young Muslim Dutchman of Moroccan descent killed Theo van Gogh for his role in making 'Submission', a short film about the abuse of Muslim women  > On 11 November 2004 the Lower House held a debate about the murder of Theo van Gogh. During this debate, the tightening of the conditions for obtaining a residence permit on religious grounds (particularly the tightening of the admissions policy regarding spiritual leaders and clerics), relaxing deportation possibilities of radicalising persons and the possible ban on radical mosques were discussed. A better approach of combating terrorism was also discussed. The subjects combating terrorism and tackling radicalising persons remained an important talking point throughout the entire reference period.	MPI 2007; EMN 2005: 18	N/A	N/A	N/A	Contextual elements	All	All	N/A	N/A		
4709	Netherlands	more protection for trafficked people	2005	On 9 March 2005, the Aliens Act implementation guidelines 2000 were amended - to expand the scope of protection of victims of human smuggling and trafficking.  > The Aliens Act implementation guidelines prior to the amendment of 9 March 2005 stipulated that victims and reporting witnesses were deemed part of the following categories aliens: aliens found during a police inspection in a sex establishment, aliens who have worked in prostitution in the Netherlands, who do not dispose of a valid residence permit and who contact police themselves, aliens who have not yet worked in prostitution in the Netherlands, who do not dispose of a legal residence permit, but who are potential victims of human trafficking and finally reporting witnesses of human trafficking. On 9 March 2005 another category aliens was added. This is the category of victims of other human trafficking offences as detailed in article 273A of the Penal Code. They are understood to mean various forms of exploitation, such as being compelled to carry out labour or services, slavery or practices comparable to slavery or providing services. In addition, it has been decided that victims who have reported human smuggling can apply for a residence permit for the duration of the criminal investigation and prosecution. During that time they are free to carry out labour. It has furthermore been decided that they shall be exempted from the means requirement to enable family reunification.	EMN 2005: 34	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4710	Netherlands	widening of the no fault criteria	2005	On 15 March 2005, the Aliens Act implementation guidelines 2000 were amended - widening the no fault criterion to asylum seekers with a nationality, which can now also qualify for the residence permit with the purpose of stay residing as an alien who cannot leave the Netherlands through no fault of his own'  > The Aliens Decree 2000 states that an alien whose application for admission has been rejected and who cannot leave the Netherlands through no fault of his own, on certain conditions qualifies for a residence permit with the purpose of stay being residing as an alien who cannot leave the Netherlands through no fault of his own. Prior to the amendment to the Aliens Act implementation guidelines on 15 March 2005, it was stipulated that this residence permit could be granted to stateless aliens only. The basic principle was that all aliens with a nationality could return to their country of origin. Upon amendment of the Aliens Act implementation guidelines 2000 on 15 March 2005, the no fault criterion was widened to other nationalities who cannot return to their countries of origin due to no fault of their own. This is the case if the alien can prove by means of objectively verifiable documents that the relevant authorities of the country of origin or the country where the person has been residing does not permit him to return. This usually concerns obtaining replacement travel documents enabling the alien to leave the Netherlands.	EMN 2005: 32	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4711	Netherlands	raising of employer sanctions	2005	On 2 December 2004, the Aliens Employment Act was amended and came into force on 1 January 2005 - introducing an administrative penalty as a new instrument to deal with employers who contract aliens illegally sooner and more efficiently. > In the event of a natural person the penalty for employing aliens illegally shall not exceed  11,250 and in the event of a legal person it shall not exceed  45,000. These amounts are considerably higher than the criminal penalty which could be imposed prior to the legislative amendment; these penalties averaged  984.	EMN 2005: 34	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Border and land control	Employer liabilities	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4712	Netherlands	national discussion on banning burqas	2005	On 10 October 2005, Lower House member Wilders submitted a motion to ban the public use of burkas in the Netherlands - On 20 December 2005, the Lower House called for an agreement to ban burkas in public places. The media reported that the Minister of Education, in response to the investigation on the instructions of the Minister of Immigration and Integration, pleaded in favour of a ban on wearing burkas in educational institutions. The educational institutions responded to the plea of the Minister of Education by saying that a national ban on wearing burkas in schools is not needed. In 2003, the Equal Treatment Committee ruled in favour of a school which had banned wearing veils covering the face only leaving the eyes uncovered, using the main argument that it hinders communication and identification in school. If schools wish to ban burkas they can invoke this ruling, but there was no national law enacted on this topic.	EMN 2005: 17	N/A	N/A	Integration	Contextual elements	All	All	N/A	N/A		
4713	Netherlands	improved external border controls	2006	Pilot project to improve external border controls institutionalized - introducing joint patrols by the Seaport Police (Zeehavenpolitie), the Royal Marechaussee (KMar) and Customs (Douane) along the seashores, in the harbours and on the small airports. > At the end of 2006 the Cabinet decided this form of patrols would be carried out structurally	EMN 2006: 15	Minor change	National policy	Border and land control	Surveillance technology/control powers	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4714	Netherlands	facilitation of temporary labour immigration	2006	Labour migration was facilitated by changes in the work permit procedure - abandoning the obligatory five week period for reporting job vacancies for specific and often temporary jobs.	SOPEMI 2008: 264	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4715	Netherlands	family reunification with children liberalized	2006	Family reunfication criterion of being an actual part of the family (feitelijk behoren tot het gezin) abolished - introduced in 1986, this criterion was found to violate the jurisprudence of European Convention on Human Rights  > Until 2006, the admission of children was refused if the parent(s) had left their child to the care of another family for five years or more, and the parent(s) no longer had custody of the child or no longer provided for the costs of the childs upbringing. After two judgements by the European Court of Human Rights in Strasbourg denouncing this policy line as a breach of the right to family life, minister Verdonk announced one of the very few liberal reforms implemented during her time in office: henceforth a family relation would always be assumed to exist between an minor child and its parents, except when the child is living on its own and is financially independent; if the child has formed its own family by entering into a marriage or relationship; or if the child has the (duty of) care for a child or other dependent family member.	Bonjour 2009: 362; Bonjour 2011: 104; http://research.icmpd.org/fileadmin/Research-Website/Project_material/NODE/Family_Migration_Pol_NL_final_01.pdf [accessed on 17.06.2013]	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4716	Netherlands	Creation of pre-entry exam for family members	2006	Law on Integration Abroad (Wet inburgering in het buitenland, came into on March 15, 2006) - makes the granting of a provisional residence permit or entry visa for family members  for all countries except those mentioned below conditional upon their demonstrating a sufficient level of knowledge of Dutch language and society through passing a civic integration exam in the country of origin. Also, immigrants are themselves responsible to learn the language and to bear the costs of the courses. > The Netherlands were the first country in the world to introduce such integration requirements at entry for foreign family members. This exam, which consists of 20 language-related exercises and 30 questions on social orientation in the Netherlands, is usually taken in Dutch embassies when applying for a three-month visa. The language exercises include repeating sentences, indicating opposites, and answering short questions. The social orientation section is based on the controversial video Coming to the Netherlands, which tries to prepare potential migrants for things they will see in the Netherlands, including nudity and homosexuality, and is available in a censored version for countries in which these scenes are legally prohibited.  All questions and answers on social orientation are provided and can be memorized prior to the test. Prospective migrants must purchase examination booklets and the film.	SOPEMI 2006: 91, 200; Bonjour 2009: 362; MPI 2007; http://research.icmpd.org/fileadmin/Research-Website/Project_material/NODE/Family_Migration_Pol_NL_final_01.pdf [accessed on 17.06.2013]	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4717	Netherlands	certain nationalities exempted from pre-entry exam	2006	Law on Integration Abroad (Wet inburgering in het buitenland, came into on March 15, 2006) - Next to EU citizens, citizens of Switzerland, Monaco, Australia, Canada, Japan, New Zealand, South Korea and the United States do not require a provisional residence permit to enter the Netherlands and are therefore exempted from the civic integration exam.	http://research.icmpd.org/fileadmin/Research-Website/Project_material/NODE/Family_Migration_Pol_NL_final_01.pdf [accessed on 17.06.2013]	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	Specific nationalities	EU, Switzerland, Monaco, Australia, Canada, Japan, New Zealand, South Koreal United States	Less restrictive		
4718	Netherlands	proposal for modern migration policy, more targetted	2006	In May 2006 the Cabinet introduced the policy memorandum Towards a modern migration policy - proposing a far-reaching revision of the current admission system (with the exception of the asylum-related part), introducing more selectivity into the existing restrictive admission policy   > Suggestions include: * a proposed talent scheme, based on a points system, for innovative entrepreneurs, independent researchers or creative top talents; * a proposal for a new non-extendable permit for one year, for the purpose of temporary employment, such as seasonal work; * the obligation for companies, universities and other institutions that wish to act as sponsors in the framework of labour migration, a study or exchange to have entered into a covenant with the Immigration and Naturalisation Service, which will result in them assuming more responsibility in the admission procedure and which will accelerate this procedure. These proposals were implemented between 2008 and 2013.	EMN 2006: 14	N/A	N/A	Legal entry and stay	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
4719	Netherlands	Proposal for strenghtening of sliding scale principle	2006	Cabinet proposal to toughen up the sliding scale on 15 September 2006 > The proposal involves measures whereby foreign nationals who are sentenced for an offence during the first three years of their lawful residence could lose their residence permits, and then could be forcibly removed from the country.  Residence for foreign nationals who have resided in the Netherlands for between 3 and 5 years can be terminated:  in the event of offences with unconditional sentences of at least one month. This used to be nine months; or  if there are three convictions for offences. The withdrawal of residence permits is based on the principle of the 'sliding scale'. This means that the longer a foreign national has enjoyed lawful residence in the Netherlands, the more serious the breach of public order - and therefore the more heavily punished the foreign national - has to be to lead to the termination of his residence rights.	EMN 2006: 14	N/A	N/A	Exit	Expulsion	Specific categories	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
4720	Netherlands	proposal for high-skilled migration policy	2006	In a position paper, the Dutch government proposed a new migration policy to promote highly skilled immigration > This would include a point system for selfemployed immigrants, improvements in residence opportunities for international students who complete their studies in the Netherlands are also envisaged. The Dutch government plans to extend the period of job search during which a graduate is allowed to stay in the country and to lower the current income thresholds for jobs. This was implemented in 2007 and 2008.	SOPEMI 2007: 268	N/A	N/A	Legal entry and stay	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
4721	Netherlands	integration exam compulsory for all to access benefits and residency	2007	Civic Integration Act (Wet inburgering, came into force in 2007) - creates a compulsory integration exam which new arrived immigrants and current immigrants with residence status have to pass after a period of three-and-a-half years (five years for some) for obtaining a residence permit or receiving certain social benefits. > It consists of two parts, a Dutch language exam and a test of knowledge of Dutch society. The new law concerns both newly arrived immigrants and established migrants from non-EEA countries, if the latter are aged between 18 and 65 years old and did not live in the country for at least eight years during their years of compulsory education.  Sanctions can be either financial (an administrative fine) or juridical (refusal of a permanent residence permit). The compulsory integration courses did exist since 1998, but the integration exam only became compulsory in 2007. Due to delays in implementation, the effective link between integration exam and permanent residency only entered into force in 2010.	SOPEMI 2007: 110; SOPEMI 2008: 264	N/A	N/A	Integration	Access to permanent residency	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
4722	Netherlands	labour market restrictions for RO and BG	2007	2007 EU enlargement - The Dutch government decided not to open the labour market for nationals from Romania and Bulgaria and still requires Bulgarian and Romanian workers to obtain a work permit > work permits will be issued if no workers are available in the Netherlands or other EU countries and if the employer can offer proper working conditions and accommodation.	SOPEMI 2007: 268; SOPEMI 2008: 264	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	All migrant workers	EU citizens	Romania, Bulgaria	No change		
4723	Netherlands	free mobility for 10 new EU countries	2007	Since May 2007, work permits are no longer required for labour migrants from the ten new EU countries > Their movements up to 2007 were subject to a numerical limit of 22 000 per year.	SOPEMI 2007: 268; SOPEMI 2008: 264	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Free mobility rights/agreements	All migrant workers	EU citizens	Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, Poland, Slovakia and Slovenia	Less restrictive		
4724	Netherlands	students can stay longer to look for work	2007	Effective from 20 December 2007, the job search period for foreign students who have graduated in the Netherlands has been extended to a maximum of one year, without entitlement to benefits - The graduate has full access to the labour market during this year.  > Also, a reduced salary criterion of 25,000 has been introduced for this group within the highly-skilled migrant scheme.	EMN 2007: 33	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Integration	Work visa/permit	International students	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4725	Netherlands	eased entry for family members of high skilled	2007	Family members of highly-skilled migrants who arrive in the Netherlands later can submit their applications to the IND front office for Highlyskilled and Labour Migration starting in the summer of 2007. > As is the case for the application of the highly-skilled migrant, the target period for the processing of these applications is two weeks.	EMN 2007: 33	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members of high-skilled workers, investors or students	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4726	Netherlands	easier access for research scientists	2007	Facilitation of the admission of research scientists -  scientists are exempted from the requirement to apply for a provisional residence permit once they have obtained a residence permit for conducting research in another EU country.	SOPEMI 2008: 264	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4727	Netherlands	regularisation of asylum seekers	2007	General Amnesty Scheme for asylum seekers - regularized asylum seekers who applied for asylum before April 2001 and were still in the Netherlands. > Background: Following general elections, a new government took office in February 2007. It has announced a regularisation programme. In 2007, the Dutch parliament decided to give a general pardon to asylum seekers who had applied for asylum before 2001 and who were still present in the Netherlands (a population that did not benefit from improvements in the asylum procedure for people who entered 2001 and thereafter).	SOPEMI 2007: 268; SOPEMI 2008: 264; SOPEMI 2010: 226;  http://www.oecd.org/dataoecd/42/53/44067975.pdf[accessed 23.05.2013]	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Regularisation	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4728	Netherlands	Integration Plan	2007	Integration Memorandum 2007-2011 - whereby the Cabinet launched a Civic Integration Delta Plan in September in 2007 to improve the quality of civic integration and increasing the number of people who participate in a civic integration programme.	EMN 2008: 38	N/A	N/A	Integration	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
4729	Netherlands	Report favours dual citizenship	2007	In September 2007 the Scientific Council for Government Policy (WRR) published a report on Dutch Identity (Identificatie met Nederland) - arguing that dual citizenship should be allowed in the case of both immigrants and Dutch emigrants.	Focus Migration 2007: 8	N/A	N/A	Integration	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	All	All	N/A	N/A		
4730	Netherlands	introduction of points system for entrepreneurs and self employed	2008	A scoring system for the admissions of self-employed persons implemented was implemented in January 2008 - Foreign nationals may now be admitted to the Netherlands to establish as self-employed persons if this serves an essential Dutch economic interest.  > On the criteria of personal experience, substantiation of economic activities, and the added value of the economic activities to Dutch economy, points will be allocated on the basis of the business plan and other documents. Elements that play a role in assessing personal experience are education, entrepreneurial experience, work experience, income, and experience with the Netherlands. The business plan will be assessed on the criteria of market potential, organisation, and financing. The added value to the Netherlands will be assessed on the criteria of innovation, creating employment, and investments.	EMN 2008: 33	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Points-based system	Investors, entrepreneurs and business people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Change in restrictiveness cannot be assessed		
4731	Netherlands	municipalities obliged to offer civic integration facilities	2008	On 30 December 2008, amendments to the Civic Integration Act (Wet inburgering) entered into force - From this date, the municipalities have been able to offer civic integration facilities to all foreign national citizens who are obliged to participate in civic integration. > In the past, the municipality could only offer this facility to foreign national citizens who were obliged to participate in civic integration and who are on welfare or to settled immigrants without current income from employment, social assistance, or benefits. It was expected that restoring the role of the municipalities would help to raise the number of participants in the courses, which had dropped dramatically immediately after the WI entered into force.  Background: In the second half of 2007, the number of participants in civic integration courses was most disappointing. Course providers and the municipalities did not succeed in offering civic integration courses to a sufficient number of people	EMN 2008: 38; https://openaccess.leidenuniv.nl/bitstream/handle/1887/20436/S.Bonjour%20-%20Governing%20Diversity%20-%20Citizenship%20Studies%20-%20Manuscript%20for%20review.pdf;jsessionid=9F8046A9B0D2C74C3E314D59133DF758?sequence=2 [accessed on 24.09.2013]	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Language, housing and cultural integration programmes	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4732	Netherlands	new return scheme for asylum seekers	2008	The new Return and Reintegration Regulation entered into force on 1 October 2008 and will remain effective until 30 September 2010 - granting support to asylum applicants who have a temporary residence permit and who are willing to have this permit withdrawn or asylum applicants who still have lawful residence in the Netherlands and who are willing to return	EMN 2008: 49	Mid-level change	National policy	Exit	Reintegration/return programmes	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4733	Netherlands	proposal for modern migration policy	2008	The Blueprint for Modern Migration Policy' was presented in June 2007 - suggesting a new model for the admission and residence of foreign nationals  > it aims to simplify admission procedures (combining whenever possible residence permits and work permits, and shortening admission procedures), to introduce a sponsor system, and to improve supervision using risk assessment.	SOPEMI 2010: 226	N/A	N/A	Legal entry and stay	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
4734	Netherlands	Creation of points based system for highly educated migrants	2009	Introduction in January 2009 of an Admission Scheme for Highly Educated Migrants - a points-based system that gives a one-year permit in order to look for a job or start an innovative firm to those individuals with at least a Masters degree from an internationally recognized university. > Within that year, the foreign national must consequently have achieved the following:  Finding a job that meets the income requirement that applies to foreign nationals who graduated in the Netherlands (the income requirement is currently a gross salary of at least  25,000 a year);  Setting up a business that meets the requirements for being admitted as a self-employed person. The business must serve an essential Dutch economic interest, and the business must yield sufficient means of existence. The target is to have 500 persons taking advantage of this scheme a year. The scheme provides for the possibility to establish a formal quota, but this possibility will not be used for the time being.	http://www.oecd.org/dataoecd/42/53/44067975.pdf ; SOPEMI 2010: 226 [accessed 23.05.2013]	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Points-based system	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4735	Netherlands	introduces possibility to revoke citizenship	2009	1985 Nationality Act was amended in May - making it possible to withdraw citizenship as a sanction to immigrants who have severely harmed Dutch interests.	SOPEMI 2011: 304	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	Specific categories	Citizens	N/A	More restrictive		
4736	Netherlands	introduction of statement of allegiance in naturalisation ceremony	2009	1985 Nationality Act was amended in May - adding statement of allegiance to the naturalisation ceremony now concludes with whereby the future citizen swears an oath to respect the values and rights implied by Dutch citizenship.	SOPEMI 2011: 304	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4737	Netherlands	restored immediate naturalisation of children recognized by NL citizen	2009	1985 Nationality Act was amended in May - restoring the practice to immediately grant citizenship to children aged under seven who are recognised by a Dutch citizen after it had been abandoned in 2003.	SOPEMI 2011: 304	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4738	Netherlands	proposal to delete categorical protection for asylum seekers	2009	On 11 December 2009, the Cabinet presented its Memorandum entitled 'Views on Protection' (Visie op bescherming) - suggesting to delete the possibility of group protection of asylum seekers (categorial protection) from the Aliens Act  > The Cabinet arrived at this conclusion because the European asylum system by now offered sufficient safeguards to also take the overall situation in the country of origin into consideration in the individual assessment of whether someone needs protection. Debates on these proposals in the Lower House of Parliament have been postponed, due to the downfall of the Cabinet on 20 February 2010	EMN 2009: 23	N/A	N/A	Legal entry and stay	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
4739	Netherlands	measure to grant citizenship to specific categories	2010	1985 Nationality Act was amended in October 2010 - enabling latent Dutch to acquire Dutch citizenship by option > This applies to children of Dutch mothers and non-Dutch fathers born before 1985, since they were not granted Dutch citizenship at birth	SOPEMI 2011: 304	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	Family members	Citizens	N/A	Less restrictive		
4740	Netherlands	pilot project for religious residence permit	2010	Ahead of the introduction of the Modern Migration Policy, in April 2010 a pilot project for religious residence was started - concerning the admission of religious people through the mediation of religious organisations. The aim of this pilot project is to gain experience in the execution of the new legislation and regulations and the changed procedures.	EMN 2012: 23	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Specific categories	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4741	Netherlands	new asylum procedure	2010	Improved Asylum Procedure entered into force on 1 July 2010 - the general asylum procedure in the application centre has been extended to eight days, leaving more room to provide legal aid to asylum seekers. Prior to the procedure, the asylum seeker will be given a period of rest and preparation, in which period the medical examination may be performed and the asylum seeker will be identified. > It is intended to ensure a faster and more careful handling of asylum applications. In addition, it is expected that the number of applications will decrease	EMN 2010: 45	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4742	Netherlands	new expulsion procedure for rejected asylum seekers	2010	Improved Asylum Procedure entered into force on 1 July 2010 - after an application submitted at the application centre has been rejected, the asylum seeker is given a departure period of four weeks.  > In order to prevent rejected asylum seekers from ending up in the street, they will be provided accommodation during this period, from which location the rejected asylum seekers can work on their departure. At the end of the departure period, the rejected asylum seekers may also be placed at a centre with restricted movement for a period of twelve weeks, where they will receive additional guidance in their return. If necessary, on the basis of individual considerations, a decision may be made to transfer an asylum seeker from a freedom-restricting location to a detention centre. In order to prevent evident abuse and improper use of the procedure, it may be decided in certain cases to place an asylum seeker in detention directly after the asylum procedure.	EMN 2010: 45	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Exit	Expulsion	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4743	Netherlands	income requirements for family reunification lowered	2010	Changes to family reunification - lowered the income requirement to 100% of the legal minimum wage > in 2010, the European Court of Justice ruled that current Dutch marriage migration policies must be modified, most notably because an income req of 120% is higher than the EU directive on family reunification from 2003 allows	SOPEMI 2011: 304	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4744	Netherlands	minimum age for family migration raised	2010	Changes to family reunification - the minimum age for family migration was raised from 18 to 21 years because the Court prohibited the distinction between family reunification and family formation.	SOPEMI 2011: 304	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4745	Netherlands	pilot project on circular migration with south africa and indonesia	2010	A pilot project on circular migration was launched on 1 January 2010 with South Africa and Indonesia - The purpose of the pilot project was that respectively 100 migrants from those countries  would come to the Netherlands for two years to work in jobs at secondary-school level. At the end of this two-year period, they were to return to their country of origin. > On 1 September 2011, the circular migration pilot project was ended prematurely. The party conducting the pilot project did not succeed in finding a sufficient number of vacancies in the Netherlands. Apart from the economic crisis, as a result of which the demand for labour dropped sharply, the employers considered the limited period of employment (not more than two years) too short.	EMN 2011: 27	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Recruitment/assisted migration programmes	Low-skilled workers	Specific nationalities	South Africa, Indonesia	Less restrictive		
4746	Netherlands	civic integration requirements for permanent residency (implementation)	2010	The link between the Civic Integration Act and permanent right of residence has taken effect as of 1 January 2010 (effective implementation of 2007 act) - this means that the aliens who want to settle permanently in the Netherlands must prove with effect from 1 January 2010 that they meet the civic integration requirement or that they have been exempted from it. > This applies to the aliens who are applying for a regular residence permit for continued residence (after three years of residence with a person with a non-temporary right of residence, for example 'residence with Dutch spouse') or who want to qualify for a permanent regular residence permit or asylum. The rationale behind this link is that it may be expected from aliens who want to settle permanently in the Netherlands that they have sufficient knowledge of the Dutch language and Dutch society.	EMN 2010: 31	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to permanent residency	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4747	Netherlands	modern migration policy act enacted	2010	Modern Migration Policy Act (Wet modern migratiebeleid) was enacted in Parliament in July 2010 - but only entered into force in June 2013 due to delays > It introduced a sponsorship system for labour migrants, introduced a new recruitment system for high skilled and simplified the application procedure for entry and residence	SOPEMI 2012: 254; http://www.ind.nl/en/Employers/News/Pages/ModernMigrationPolicyActentersintoforceon1June2013.aspx [accessed on 17.06.2013]	N/A	N/A	Legal entry and stay	Contextual elements	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
4748	Netherlands	tightened requirements for highly skilled migration scheme	2011	The Highly Skilled Migrants Scheme has been tightened since 19 June 2011 - The Immigration and Naturalisation Service (IND) currently has the possibility of refusing an application for a residence permit for highly skilled migrants if the salary is disproportionally high for the relevant employment (verification of whether the salary is competitive).	EMN 2011: 22	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4749	Netherlands	EU blue card implemented in the Netherlands	2011	In 2011 the Netherlands transposed the EU Blue Card directive - adding a new residence permit for highly skilled workers.  > The EU Blue Card is offered to those earning salaries above the threshold of EUR 60 000	SOPEMI 2013: 278	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4750	Netherlands	EU blue card implemented in the Netherlands	2011	In 2011 the Netherlands transposed the EU Blue Card directive - allows Blue Card holders to bring family members under more favourable conditions than those applied in the existing Highly Skilled Migrant Scheme.  > Family members of EU Blue Card holders are allowed to take up any work in the Netherlands.	SOPEMI 2013: 278	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Family members of high-skilled workers, investors or students	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4751	Netherlands	higher language requirements for family migrants	2011	Language requirements for family members passing the Civic Integration Examination Abroad test have been increased > higher level of spoken Dutch and a written test is required for passing the Civic Integration Examination Abroad which prospective family migrants have to take in their home countries: the pass score on the Spoken Dutch component of the civic integration examination abroad was raised from A1-minus to A1, and a Reading and Comprehension Skills test was added to the examination	SOPEMI 2011: 304; SOPEMI 2012: 254	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4752	Netherlands	restriction of temporary work permits	2011	Restriction of the issuance of TWV (temporary work permits) to exceptional cases - in an attempt to reduce unemployment of Dutch citizens by lowering the number of labour migrants.	SOPEMI 2012: 254	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4753	Netherlands	restrictive memorandum on integration	2011	In June 2011, the government presented its memorandum Integration, Cohesion and Citizenship - Under this policy, migrants and asylum seekers should be responsible for their own integration in Dutch society and bear the costs of the integration courses.  > For those who do not have sufficient resources of their own, the government introduced a system of loans. In principle, failing the civic integration exam leads to revocation of the temporary regular residence permit. This was implemented in 2013.	SOPEMI 2013: 278	N/A	N/A	Integration	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
4754	Netherlands	family reunification restricted	2012	Regulations restricting family reunification came into force as from 1 October 2012 - sponsors who have a temporary regular residence permit can only bring over a family member to the Netherlands if they have already stayed legitimately in the Netherlands for at least 1 year and, most importantly, family reunification and family formation are now only possible for partners who are married or who have a registered partnership, as well as their minor children.	EMN 2012: 23	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4755	Netherlands	access for family members independent residence permit extended	2012	Regulations restricting family reunification came into force as from 1 October 2012 - extends the period for becoming eligible for an independent residence permit on grounds of continued residence from 3 to 5 years.	EMN 2012: 23	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4756	Netherlands	changes in the civic examination for foreigners	2013	Changes to the Civic Integration Act passed by the Senate on 11 September 2012 - As from 2013 immigrants who hold a residence permit must arrange and pay for their own obligatory civic integration programmes.  > If they have a low income then there is the opportunity for them to take out a loan from one of the Dutch social banks for their course and examination. They are only required to pay back this loan if their earnings are high enough. Those people who culpably do not pass the obligatory civic examination within three years run the risk of losing their temporary residence permit.	EMN 2012: 29	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to permanent residency	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4757	Netherlands	creation of sponsorship system	2013	The Modern Migration Policy Act (Wet modern migratiebeleid) was enacted in Parliament in July 2010 and entered into force in June 2013 - introducing a sponsorship system for immigration for labour migrants (sponsor: employer), students (sponsor: educational institution), family members (sponsor: family) etc.	SOPEMI 2012: 254; http://www.ind.nl/en/Employers/News/Pages/ModernMigrationPolicyActentersintoforceon1June2013.aspx [accessed on 17.06.2013]	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4758	Netherlands	employer liabilities strenghtened	2013	The Modern Migration Policy Act (Wet modern migratiebeleid) was enacted in Parliament in July 2010 and entered into force in June 2013 - requiring employer to adequately include the documents for a labour migrant in their administration. If they fail, they run the risk of being fined a maximum sum of  3,000.	SOPEMI 2012: 254; http://www.ind.nl/en/Employers/News/Pages/ModernMigrationPolicyActentersintoforceon1June2013.aspx [accessed on 17.06.2013]	Minor change	National policy	Border and land control	Employer liabilities	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
4759	Netherlands	quicker procedure for sponsors of high skilled migrants	2013	The Modern Migration Policy Act (Wet modern migratiebeleid) was enacted in Parliament in July 2010 and entered into force in June 2013 - creating an accelerated and better controlled system for the highly skilled migrant procedure > Under the MMPA, the employer will become the legal sponsor of its migrant laborers and can request residence permits for them. Only those employers that obtain authorized sponsor status will be allowed access to the Highly Skilled Migrant procedure (HSM). The authorized sponsor will be entitled to request a residence permit via an accelerated procedure, under which the request can be submitted without the underlying documentation. For instance, no longer will it be required to submit such supporting documentation as a contract, etc. In those cases, the sponsor only needs to state that the immigrant meets the conditions for residence (sponsor statement) and, in fact, the sponsor ultimately decides if the permit is granted. Government assessment will only be done after the fact.	SOPEMI 2012: 254; http://www.ind.nl/en/Employers/News/Pages/ModernMigrationPolicyActentersintoforceon1June2013.aspx [accessed on 17.06.2013]	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
4760	Netherlands	simplification of residence application	2013	The Modern Migration Policy Act (Wet modern migratiebeleid) was enacted in Parliament in July 2010 (entered into force in June 2013) - combines the application procedure in order to be allowed entry into the Netherlands (the regular provisional residence permit) and the application procedure for being allowed to stay in the Netherlands for a longer period of time (the residence permit) into a single procedure.  > Migrants or their sponsor only need to submit a single application for a provisional residence permit and for the residence permit. In addition, regular residence permits can be granted for longer periods which means less renewal procedures.	SOPEMI 2012: 254; http://www.ind.nl/en/Employers/News/Pages/ModernMigrationPolicyActentersintoforceon1June2013.aspx [accessed on 17.06.2013]	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
