5115	Poland	refugee status determination rules introduced	1991	1991 Amendment of the 1963 Aliens Act (Art. 10) and to Polish Constitution of 1952 (art. 88 on the right to asylum) - formally established a system for granting refugee status. It was stated that the decision on granting the refugee status was to be issued by the Minister of the Interior in agreement with the Minister of Foreign Affairs.  > This was after Poland ratified the United Nation's 1951 Refugee Convention and the 1967 Protocol, in September 1991. Until that time, Poland had only granted asylum to people for a limited set of reasons, and most of those who received asylum were communists from Greece and Chile escaping Greece's junta regime and Pinochet's regime in Chile, respectively.	MPI 2010; http://ec.europa.eu/dgs/home-affairs/what-we-do/networks/european_migration_network/reports/docs/emn-studies/non-eu-harmonised-protection-status/20a._poland_national_report_non-eu_harmonised_forms_of_protection_final_version_12july2010_en.pdf [accessed on 31.10.2013]	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
