5195	Poland	eased access to employment for seasonal workers from bordering countries, extended to Moldova and Georgia	2010	In 2010, the simplified procedure introduced in 2006/7 for the seasonal employment of migrants from co-operating bordering countries was extended indefinitely. > Migrants from Belarus, Russia, Ukraine and now also Moldova and Georgia are exempt from work permits, although employers must declare their employment at the local labour office and they may not work more than 6 months during a year.	SOPEMI 2010: 232; SOPEMI 2011: 310	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Low-skilled workers	Specific nationalities	Belarus, Russia, Ukraine,  Moldova, Georgia	No change		
5196	Poland	new migration policy strategy adopted by interministerial working group	2010	In 2010, the inter-ministerial Working Group on Migration Strategy adopted the Polish migration policy  current state and prospects - setting out recommendations for a new migration policy for Poland. The document is expected to form the basis for a New Foreigners Act. > Among the main recommendations is the introduction of a migration policy according to labour market needs with a broader set of privileged categories (including migrant workers with needed skills, self-employed, students and researchers as well as immigrants of Polish descent), a clear pathway for regularisation for irregular migrants, as well as the implementation of a new strategy for integration focused at enhancing Polish language knowledge among immigrants. Other recommendations relate to the strengthening of the ties of Polish emigrants with Poland and at facilitating the re-insertion of return migrants.	SOPEMI 2011: 310	N/A	N/A	Legal entry and stay	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
5197	Poland	integration measures for foreign children in schools	2010	In January 2010, new provisions came into force - to facilitate the integration of foreign children into the Polish school system. The amendments include a right to a year-long assistance during school classes for foreign pupils who have difficulties with the Polish language.  > The right of foreign students to free-of-charge education, which applied previously only to primary and lower secondary schools, has been extended to general secondary, technical secondary and basic vocational public schools.	SOPEMI 2011: 310	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Access to social benefits and socio-economic rights	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5198	Poland	agreement with Belarus creates special permit for border area residents	2011	The bilateral agreement on local border traffic between Poland and Belarus was implemented  in April 2011 - creating a specific permit for residents of the border areas to allow them to regularly cross the border and stay in the area for a maximum of 60 days each time.   > Permits can be issues to persons who are able to prove that they lived in the border region for no less than 3 years.	SOPEMI 2011: 310	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Travel visa/permit	All	Specific nationalities	Belarus	Less restrictive		
5199	Poland	employer sanctions introduced	2012	Act on the Effects of Hiring Foreigners Unlawfully Present in Polish Territory of 15 June 2012 went into effect on 21 July 2012 - imposing new sanctions for hiring foreigners unlawfully present in Poland and increasing the competencies of authorities responsible for monitoring the hiring of illegal aliens. > The act imposes a new obligation on entities hiring foreigners to perform work in Poland. Before admitting a foreigner to perform work, the entity must demand that the foreigner present a valid document entitling him or her to stay in Poland. The entity is then required to retain a copy of the document for the entire working period.  The act establishes new criminal offences. A person who hires a foreigner who is a minor, or numerous adults, unlawfully present in Poland, or persistently hires such foreigners, will be subject to a fine or probation. Apart from imposing sanctions on entities hiring foreigners without a valid basis for being in Poland, the act of 15 June 2012 also provides for immediate protection of the rights of foreigners working in Poland. If the foreigner seeks unpaid salary and benefits or a declaratory judgment that he or she is an employee, there is a presumption under the act of the existence of an employment relationship for a period of three months. If the foreigner seeks unpaid salary and benefits under a legal basis other than employment, there is a presumption that the payment for the work would be PLN 4,500 gross per month (i.e. three times the minimum wage). These presumptions may be rebutted by either party based on relevant evidence.	SOPEMI 2012: 260; http://proces.wardynski.com.pl/en/zmiany-w-prawie-en/already-in-force/art44,new-sanctions-for-hiring-foreigners-in-poland-unlawfully.html [accessed on 27.01.2014]	Mid-level change	National policy	Border and land control	Employer liabilities	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
5200	Poland	regularisation	2012	In 2011 the Polish Parliament passed the Act on Legalisation of Stay of Foreigners implemented in 2012 - introducing a regularisation in the first half of 2012, open to foreigners who have been living continuously in Poland illegally at least since the end of 2007 (since January 2010 for specific groups of asylum applicants).  > The 2012 regularisation is Polands third, after 2003 and 2007, and the most liberal, as it is not conditional on any economic requirement. Successful applicants will be granted a 2-year stay permit allowing working in Poland without a work permit but only on the basis of an employment contract.	SOPEMI 2012: 260	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Regularisation	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5201	Poland	local border traffic agreement with Russia on Kaliningrad District	2012	The bilateral agreement on local border traffic between Poland and Kaliningrad District (Russia) came into force  - allowing the inhabitants of these areas to travel more freely across the border as theyll be required to hold only the valid travel document confirming their identity and a special multiple exit and re-entry permit (issued initially for 2 years and under certain conditions each subsequent for 5 years).  > Permits can be issues to persons who are able to prove that they lived in the border region for no less than 3 years.	http://www.emn.gov.pl/ese/news/9197,dok.html [accessed on 27.01.2014]	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Travel visa/permit	All	Specific nationalities	Russia	Less restrictive		
