5324	Portugal	rearrangement of work permits	1998	Decree-Law 244/98 of 8 August or Law of Entry, Stay, Exit and Expulsion of Aliens National Territory (repealing Law 59/93) - placed numerous restrictions on foreign citizens wishing to enter and remain in Portugal for the purposes of undertaking a paid or unpaid professional activity and increased the variety of visas granted, complicating further the diversity of statuses that regulated the residence of foreigners in the country.  > The work visa was created and divided into four distinct situations: work visa I for professional activities in the sporting arena, work visa II for professional activities in the area of entertainment, work visa III for independent activities in the area of service provision and, finally, work visa IV for undertaking salaried work. These work visas were granted in accordance with an annual prediction of employment opportunities, according to the annual reports composed by the Institute for Employment and Professional Training (IEFP) and approved by the Government. These reports stipulated that the priority was for job offers to be filled by EU workers or non-EU workers with legal residence in Portugal.	De Sousa 2002: 49, 50; Oliveira 2008: 115	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
5325	Portugal	voluntary return mechanism	1998	Decree-Law 244/98 of 8 August or Law of Entry, Stay, Exit and Expulsion of Aliens National Territory (repealing Law 59/93) - adopts a new legal mechanism supporting the voluntary return of foreigners to their countries of origin, as an alternative to their expulsion	SOPEMI 1999: 194; EMN 2006: 14	Major change	National policy	Exit	Reintegration/return programmes	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5326	Portugal	quota of workers per firm abolished	1998	New law on foreign labour or Law nº20/98 of May 12 - abolished the restrictive system of immigrant recruitment created in 1977 based on the need of a minimum proportion of national workers in each firm.  > The limitations to the number of foreign employees by company (formerly an enterprise could not exceed 10% of foreign employees) were removed from labour law.	SOPEMI 2001a: 242; Sabino et al. 2010: 28	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Quota/target	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5327	Portugal	more protection situations for asylum seekers	1998	Law 15/98 of 26 March 1998 establishing a new legal regime on asylum and refugees - expanded the scope of situations of protection: The Residence Permit on Humanitarian Grounds shall  be granted to aliens and stateless persons to whom the provisions of article 1 (refugee definition) are not applicable but who are not allowed or who feel unable to return to the State of their nationality or their habitual residence because of a lack of security resulting from armed conflicts or systematic violations of human rights found to exist in the said State. > Law 15/98 herewith provides a broader procedural flexibility in relation to the previous law 70/93.	MPI 2002; EMN 2006: 14; http://www.sef.pt/portal/v10/PT/aspx/legislacao/legislacao_detalhe.aspx?id_linha=4219 [accessed on 07.10.2013]; http://www.refugiados.net/cid_virtual_bkup/integra/rint_in1.html [accessed on 07.10.2013]	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5328	Portugal	creation of temporary protection status	1998	Law 15/98 of 26 March 1998 establishing a new legal regime on asylum and refugees - creates the  temporary protection status for 'displaced persons from their countries as a result of situations of serious international armed conflicts which cause a large-scale influx of refugees'.  > The temporary protection should not exceed two years and should be based on the criteria according to the specific situation, by resolution of the Council of Ministers which will be in compliance with the provisions adopted by the European Union relating to concerted actions for the reception and provisional permanence of displaced persons.	http://www.refugiados.net/cid_virtual_bkup/integra/rint_in1.html [accessed on 07.10.2013]	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5329	Portugal	work permit for asylum seekers	1998	Law 15/98 of 26 March 1998 establishing a new legal regime on asylum and refugees - provides the possibility of employment for asylum seekers provided that applicants held a provisional residence permit (Article 55)	MPI 2002; EMN 2006: 14; http://www.sef.pt/portal/v10/PT/aspx/legislacao/legislacao_detalhe.aspx?id_linha=4219 [accessed on 07.10.2013]	Major change	National policy	Integration	Work visa/permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5330	Portugal	institutional responsibilities for asylum clarified	1998	Law 15/98 of 26 March 1998 establishing a new legal regime on asylum and refugees - recognized the Portuguese Council for Refugees (CPR) as a key institution in the juridical support of asylum seekers, as well as the role of the shelter institution in the process of receiving such people in Portugal.  > The acknowledgement of the activities undertaken by this Non-Governmental Organization (NGO), free from religious and/or political connotations, is an important step in the sense that all the asylum applications will henceforth be examined individually, objectively and impartially.	MPI 2002; EMN 2006: 14; http://www.sef.pt/portal/v10/PT/aspx/legislacao/legislacao_detalhe.aspx?id_linha=4219 [accessed on 07.10.2013]; http://www.refugiados.net/cid_virtual_bkup/integra/rint_in1.html [accessed on 07.10.2013]	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Institutional capacities	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5331	Portugal	regime for migrant associations approved	1999	Decree-Law 115/99 - approved the juridicial regime for migrants' associations, although existing since the 1970s	Fonseca et al. 2002: 139	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to justice and political rights	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5332	Portugal	anti discrimination commission	1999	Law 134/99 of 28 August - forbids discrimination based on race, nationality or ethnicity and creates the Commission for Equality and Against Racial Discrimination, a place where immigrants associations and other organizations have a permanent seat	Fonseca et al. 2002: 141	Major change	National policy	Integration	Institutional capacities	All	All	N/A	Less restrictive		
5333	Portugal	Access to social assistance to elderly portuguese abroad	1999	Social Assistance introduced for elderly Portuguese living abroad - entitles elderly (over 65) persons of Portuguese origin living legally abroad and who are experiencing socio-economic needs that the local systems of social security or public aid can not satisfy to a monthly social subsidy corresponding to half of the difference between the Portuguese state pension and the social benefits avaliable in the foreign country.	SOPEMI 2001b: 230	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Access to social benefits and socio-economic rights	Diaspora	Citizens	N/A	Less restrictive		
5334	Portugal	Training programme for young portuguese abroad	2000	'Train in Portugal programme' - targeted at young Portuguese nationals between 18 and 30 or young people of Portuguese descent living abroad, offering 1000 fellowships of 9 months duration in order to enable them to complement and perfect their socio professional skills through training and experience in the Portuguese labour market.  > It aims to enhance the professional skills of the target groups in a context that increases their knowledge of the Portuguese entrepreneurial fabric and strenghts their links with the effective or ancestral origin country.	SOPEMI 2001b: 230	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Work visa/permit	Diaspora	All	N/A	Less restrictive		
5335	Portugal	Readmission agreement with the US	2000	Portugal and the United States of America have signed on the 3 October 2000 (Decree n.º 24/2000) an agreement regarding the deportation of Portuguese citizens from the USA and of American citizens from Portugal.  > Reasons for deportation in the framework of such agreements include criminal behaviour or remaining in the territory of the contracting states in violation of internal law  first and foremost for reasons of unauthorized work.	Sabino et al. 2010: 53	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Exit	Readmission agreements	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	Those transiting through or originating from US	More restrictive		
5336	Portugal	new stay permit for regular and irregular migrants with work contract	2001	Law 4/2001 of 10 January 2001 on immigrant workers in Portugal - created, as its cornerstone, a new document for economic immigrants, a stay permit, which is to be granted to all foreign citizens with an employment contract >  Since this stay permit will only be granted to people with a contract of employment, the labour market will regulate the flow of immigrants. As many immigrants as the labour market can absorb will be admitted. The stay permit was created to resolve the illegal situation of thousands of foreign citizens. All foreign citizens working in Portugal can apply for this permit, whether they have entered Portugal legally or illegally and hence could correspond in practice to a new regularisation process. However, this new document is not the same as having a special amnesty to allow people to obtain legal papers, since it is a permanent opportunity for foreign citizens working in Portugal and who have not got a serious criminal record, to make their stay in the country legal.	SOPEMI 2003a: 242; De Sousa 2002: 50, 59; Baganha 2005: 34	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Regularisation	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5337	Portugal	quasi-introduction of a quota for immigration entries	2001	Law 4/2001 of 10 January 2001 on immigrant workers in Portugal - stipulated that the government will produce a yearly report to estimate the numbers of migrants needed for the coming year.  > Although the term quota is not mentioned, the idea is present.	SOPEMI 2003a: 242; ACIME 2006: 25	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Quota/target	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
5338	Portugal	new task force for integration matters	2001	Law 4/2001 of 10 January 2001 on immigrant workers in Portugal - created the Cabinet Task Force for the Follow up of the Integration of Immigrants in the Portuguese society to develop integration possibilities for the foreign population.	SOPEMI 2003a: 242	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Institutional capacities	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5339	Portugal	longer validity of work visa	2001	Law 4/2001 of 10 January 2001 on immigrant workers in Portugal - prolongued substantially the work visa holders length of stay. > Prior to 15 January 2001, holders of work visas could only stay in Portugal for up to 2 years. Once that period had terminated, work visa holders had to return home or remain in Portugal illegally, since they could not obtain a residence permit directly. Nowadays, work visas are valid for up to one year, and can be renewed for a further 2 years or for a longer unlimited period as and when justified.	De Sousa 2002: 50, 57	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Work visa/permit	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5340	Portugal	access to residency permit granted	2001	Law 4/2001 of 10 January 2001 on immigrant workers in Portugal - granted all work visa holders who have been in Portugal for a continuous period of 3 years the entitlement to apply for a residence permit.	De Sousa 2002: 50, 57	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to permanent residency	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5341	Portugal	enlarged family reunification and rights	2001	Law 4/2001 of 10 January 2001 on immigrant workers in Portugal - grants holders of residence permits or work permits the rights to family reunification when their relatives are in Portugal, whether legally or illegally > The new Article 38, sub-section 1, paragraph b foresees that visitors visas be issued to spouses, children under the age of 21 or disabled children, adopted minors, dependent parents or grandparents and younger siblings whose guardian is the work visa holder, thereby allowing these family members to stay with the migrant worker while in Portugal. The right to stay in Portugal, however, does not give them the right to exercise a professional activity.	De Sousa 2002: 50, 57	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5342	Portugal	tougher measures for employers of irregular migrants	2001	Law 4/2001 of 10 January 2001 on immigrant workers in Portugal - introduced tougher measures to fight exploitation of illegal workers. > Firms employing illegal foreign workers will be subject to heavy fines. All public sector departments and services must ensure that subcontractors do not employ illegal workers and reserve the right to rescind signed contracts, as and when this is not the case.	De Sousa 2002: 50, 64	Mid-level change	National policy	Border and land control	Employer liabilities	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
5343	Portugal	tougher measures against irregular migrations	2001	Law 4/2001 of 10 January 2001 on immigrant workers in Portugal - introduced tougher measures to fight illegal immigration > A new type of crime has been defined  raising illegal labour. Thus, those who supply foreign workers who do not have a residence permit, stay permit or work visa, to the labour market, for the purposes of profit, will be sentenced to between 1 and 4 years in prison, or 2 to 5 years for more than one count.	De Sousa 2002: 50, 64	Mid-level change	National policy	Border and land control	Other sanctions	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
5344	Portugal	expulsion introduced as additional sentence for specific crimes	2001	Law 4/2001 of 10 January 2001 on immigrant workers in Portugal - allowed Portuguese courts to impose expulsion as an additional sentence, when foreign citizens are sentenced to over six months in prison.  > Should immigrants hold temporary residence permits, they can only be expelled if sentenced to over a year in prison. In such cases, the judge must take account of the nature of the crime, how well integrated foreign citizens are into Portuguese society or how long they have been living in Portugal. The additional sentence of expulsion can only be applied to foreign citizens with permanent residence permits, who have been sentenced to over a year in prison, if their behaviour is a serious threat to law and order. In any case, expulsion of legal immigrants cannot be an automatic and requisite effect of a prison sentence, otherwise it would contravene Article 30 of the Portuguese Constitution. Law 4/2001 also sets out certain categories of foreign citizens who cannot be expelled, even if they commit crimes:  Foreign citizens who were born in Portugal or who have been living in the country since they were less than 10 years old;  Foreign citizens with dependent children.	De Sousa 2002: 66	Mid-level change	National policy	Exit	Expulsion	Specific categories	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
5345	Portugal	Labour agreements with Romania	2001	Bilateral labour agreements were signed with Romania to facilitate recruitment of workers.	SOPEMI 2003a: 242	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Recruitment/assisted migration programmes	Low-skilled workers	Specific nationalities	Romania	Less restrictive		
5346	Portugal	Readmission agreement with Lithuania	2001	Readmission agreement signed with Lithuania on 11 February 1999, ratified by Parliament Resolution 11/2001	Sabino et al. 2010: 53	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Exit	Readmission agreements	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	Those transiting through or originating from Spain	More restrictive		
5347	Portugal	Readmission agreement with Hungary	2001	Readmission agreement signed with Hungary on 28 January 2000, ratified by Parliament Resolution 62/2001	Sabino et al. 2010: 53	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Exit	Readmission agreements	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	Those transiting through or originating from Spain	More restrictive		
5348	Portugal	Readmission agreement with Canada	2001	Portugal has signed an agreement with Canada on the 29 January 2001 (Decree n.º 10/2001)  regarding the deportation of Portuguese citizens from Canada and of Canadian citizens from Portugal. > Reasons for deportation in the framework of such agreements include criminal behaviour or remaining in the territory of the contracting states in violation of internal law  first and foremost for reasons of unauthorized work.	Sabino et al. 2010: 53	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Exit	Readmission agreements	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	Those transiting through or originating from Canada	More restrictive		
5349	Portugal	access to health care for foreigners	2001	2001 law establishing a framework on health (Despacho 25360/2001, December 12) - stipulates that any foreign citizen living legally in Portugal has access to health care and services of the National Health Service (NHS), like all nationals.  > Those staying irregularly may have access to NHS by presenting a residence certificate (that can be obtained in the local councils) at the health service located in their area of residence, proving that they had been in Portugal for at least 90 days. Many of the irregular immigrants are not aware of their rights and are afraid of being denounced to the authorities. The residence certificate may not be also so easy to obtain because of bureaucratic procedures or the refusal of local authorities.	Sabino et al. 2010: 28	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to social benefits and socio-economic rights	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	No change		
5350	Portugal	right to vote in presidential elections for emigrants	2001	Beginning of 2001, Portuguese emigrants are given the opportuniy to vote for presidential elections.	SOPEMI 2003a: 242	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to justice and political rights	Diaspora	Citizens	N/A	Less restrictive		
5351	Portugal	Creation of reception programme for new immigrants	2002	Establishment of the reception programme 'Portugal Acolhe' (Portugal Hosts) - making Portuguese language courses available to new immigrants and providing them with information on Portuguese society and citizenship. > This is done in response to the arrival of new waves of migration from Eastern Europe and Russia and of a sizeable number of nationals of Bangladesh, China and Pakistan. In order to encourage immigrants, certain benefits are provided in case of need, such as food assistance and transport grants. An effort has been made to ensure that courses are scheduled outside migrants working hours. Information centres and telephone call-in lines for immigrants have also been established to enable them to become more familiar with their rights in Portugal and to obtain information on various services (such as Social Security, education, health care, etc.).  Migrants can also receive assistance from a mediator.	SOPEMI 2003b: 258; ACIME 2006: 25	Major change	National policy	Integration	Language, housing and cultural integration programmes	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5352	Portugal	Action Plan to clarify rights and duties of immigrants	2002	In November 2002, a social pact was signed - to clarify the rights and duties of immigrants, to involve all Portuguese institutions in combating all forms of exploitation and discrimination against immigrants, and to promote the development of poor countries so as to reduce the incentive to emigrate.	SOPEMI 2003b: 258	N/A	N/A	Integration	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
5353	Portugal	More integration structures and efforts	2002	In 2002, the High Commissioner for Immigration and Ethnic Minorities (ACIME) functions evolved from an individual assignment as a governmental post, into a Public governmental body structure with more resources and a broader field of intervention - leading to the creation of the High Commissariat for Immigration and Ethnic Minorities (ACIME) which promotes exchange and dialogue between immigrants and ethnic minorities and the majoritarian society in Portugal and develops a policy aimed at promoting the integration of immigrants in Portuguese society. > In concrete terms, the activities developed by ACIME between mid-2002 and mid-2003 involved the following: The creation of a National Immigrant Information Network, which includes the publication of a monthly information bulletin, educational leaflets and brochures in several languages (on health, education, acquisition of nationality, etc.), as well as the establishment of an information call centre (accessible in three languages). The creation of a National Immigrant Assistance System (Sistema Nacional de Apoio ao Imigrante), involving the installation of one-stop  entres at national level (in Lisbon and Porto) and small assistance points at local level.	SOPEMI 2005: 257	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Institutional capacities	All	All	N/A	Less restrictive		
5354	Portugal	increase of employer sanctions	2003	Decree-Law No. 34/2003 of 25 February 2003 regulating the entry, residence, exit and expulsion of foreign citizens from the national territory - strengthened the sanctions and penalties for illegal immigration and irregular work.  > The companies that have illegal workers are also under the obligation of covering all the necessary expenses for the stay and removal of the foreign citizens. On the other hand, employers that do not pay the wages to foreign workers (legal or illegal) or that do not make their welfare and tax contributions regarding the amounts withheld over the workers wages are also fined.	ACIME 2006: 16	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Border and land control	Employer liabilities	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
5355	Portugal	additional criteria for family reunification	2003	Decree-Law No. 34/2003 of 25 February 2003 regulating the entry, residence, exit and expulsion of foreign citizens from the national territory - requires petitioners under family reunification to have an actual connection to the country through a legal stay in the country during a certain amount of time (as established through Community regulations, although for a shorter period, invoking a humanist policy)	ACIME 2006: 14	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
5356	Portugal	slightly quicker access to permanent residency	2003	Decree-Law No. 34/2003 of 25 February 2003 regulating the entry, residence, exit and expulsion of foreign citizens from the national territory - reduces the minimum residence period to obtain a long-term residence permit from six to five years (Portugese-speaking countries) and from ten to eight years (other countries).	SOPEMI 2005: 257	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to permanent residency	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5357	Portugal	end of 2001 work permit possibility for legal and irregular workers	2003	Decree-Law No. 34/2003 of 25 February 2003 regulating the entry, residence, exit and expulsion of foreign citizens from the national territory - terminated the possibility to regularize one's status when holding a work contract, this retrieves the stay permit introduced in 2001. > With this law, the stay permits were definitely abolished for new arrivals/requests (although, in practice, they were not issued since 2001), although the conditions remained the same for those immigrants having already a stay permit or waiting for a prorogation.	SOPEMI 2006: 208; Sabino et al. 2010: 16; ACIME 2006: 14	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Regularisation	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
5358	Portugal	regularisation agreement with Brazil	2003	On 11th July 2003 Portugal and Brazil signed a mutual labour recruitment agreement (Decree n.º 40/2003 of 19 September) - aiming at facilitating the movement of Portuguese and Brazilians workers between the two countries and allowing the regularization of irregular Brazilian workers in Portugal as well as irregular Portuguese workers in Brazil.  > This process allowed the granting of long-term work visas to Brazilians that could prove the possession of a labour contract.	SOPEMI 2005: 258; Sabino et al. 2010: 17	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Regularisation	Irregular migrants	Specific nationalities	Brazil	Less restrictive		
5359	Portugal	Agreement with Brazil on border control	2003	On the 11 July 2003 Portugal signed an agreement with Brazil on the prevention and fight against trafficking of migrants (Decree n.º 42/2003 of 20 September) > Cooperation in the area of training includes mutual training on legal systems and processes of law, informatics systems, falsified documents and procedures for identification of illegal migrants. Special channels for information exchange  namely by posting immigration liaison officers in diplomatic representations or by use of electronic means of communication  seem to offer a more systematic and consistent nature to this agreement when compared to that signed with Morocco. In practice, this agreement has facilitated the exchange of information between Portugal and Brazil. The presence of a liaison officer from SEF in Brasilia has also helped on this task.	Sabino et al. 2010: 54	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Border and land control	Surveillance technology/control powers	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	Those transiting through or originating from Brazil	More restrictive		
5360	Portugal	Recruitment agreement with Bulgaria on temporary workers	2003	Portugal and Bulgaria signed an agreement on temporary recruitment of Bulgarian citizens to Portugal on 26 Sept 2002 (approved in 2003 by Decree nº23/2003) - to prevent illegal migration by focussing on the procedures to be followed by Portuguese employers who wish to recruit nationals from Bulgaria.  > Similarly to the agreement with Cape Verde, explained above, there is an collaboration between employers, the General Inspection of Work (IGT), IEFP and the relevant institutions in the country of origin.	Sabino et al. 2010: 52	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Recruitment/assisted migration programmes	Low-skilled workers	Specific nationalities	Bulgaria	Less restrictive		
5361	Portugal	Readmission agreement with Estonia	2003	Readmission agreement signed with Estonia on 12 November 2001, ratified by Parliament Resolution 46/2003	Sabino et al. 2010: 53	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Exit	Readmission agreements	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	Those transiting through or originating from Spain	More restrictive		
5362	Portugal	Readmission agreement with Romania	2003	Readmission agreement signed with Romania on 26 September 2002, ratified by Parliament Resolution 43/2003	Sabino et al. 2010: 53	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Exit	Readmission agreements	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	Those transiting through or originating from Spain	More restrictive		
5363	Portugal	Agreement with Morocco on border control	2004	Portugal and Morocco signed an agreement on the 7 September 1999 (approved with the Decree n.º 35/2004) - on the prevention and fight against human trafficking and illegal migration, focusing on border controls and migration flows.  > Cooperative activities foreseen in this agreement include: information exchange on borders control, migration management and fight against irregular migration; exchange of data on falsified documents and technical knowledge for countering falsifications; exchange visits and sharing of information for a better management of borders control; organization of internships, conferences and seminars.	Sabino et al. 2010: 53	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Border and land control	Surveillance technology/control powers	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	Those transiting through or originating from Morocco	More restrictive		
5364	Portugal	new regularisation mechanism introduced	2004	Regulatory-Decree 6/2004 of 26 April - allowed the regularization of immigrants already active in the labour market that could prove that they entered until March 12, 2003 and have made compulsory payments for social security and tax administration for a minimum period of 90 days prior to the law and (article 71)	SOPEMI 2006:208; Sabino et al. 2010: 17; Baganha 2005: 36	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Regularisation	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5365	Portugal	registration of minor irregular migrants	2004	Decree-law n. 67/2004, of 25 March - allows the registration of irregular foreigners under 18 years old, with the intent to channel them, if necessary, to the national health and education system.	Baganha 2005: 36	Mid-level change	National policy	Border and land control	Access to social benefits and socio-economic rights	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5366	Portugal	EU enlargement restricted labour market access	2004	2004 EU enlargement - Portugal introduced restrictions to labour market access of the newly acceded MS, except on Malta and Cyprus.  > The restrictions include an annual limit of 6500 workers and were lifted in May 2006.	IPPR 2004: 8	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Quota/target	All migrant workers	EU citizens	Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, Poland, Slovakia and Slovenia	More restrictive		
5367	Portugal	Recruitment agreement with Ukraine on temporary workers	2005	Portugal and Ukraine signed an agreement on temporary recruitment of Ukrainian citizens to Portugal on 12 Feb 2003 (approved in 2005 by Decree nº3/2005) - to prevent illegal migration by focussing on the procedures to be followed by Portuguese employers who wish to recruit nationals from Ukraine.  > Similarly to the agreement with Cape Verde, explained above, there is an articulation between employers, the General Inspection of Work (IGT), IEFP and the relevant institutions in the country of origin.	Sabino et al. 2010: 52	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Recruitment/assisted migration programmes	Low-skilled workers	Specific nationalities	Ukraine	Less restrictive		
5368	Portugal	Recruitment agreement with Romania on temporary workers	2005	Portugal and Romania signed an agreement on temporary recruitment of Romanian citizens to Portugal on 19 July 2001 (although only approved in 2005 by Decree nº18/2005) - to prevent illegal migration by focussing on the procedures to be followed by Portuguese employers who wish to recruit nationals from Romania.  > Similarly to the agreement with Cape Verde, explained above, there is an articulation between employers, the General Inspection of Work (IGT), IEFP and the relevant institutions in the country of origin.	Sabino et al. 2010: 52	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Recruitment/assisted migration programmes	Low-skilled workers	Specific nationalities	Romania	Less restrictive		
5369	Portugal	widening of right to minimum income to all legal migrants	2006	Decree law 42/2006 of 23 February - extends the benefit of social insertion income (minimum guaranteed income) to foreigners who hold a residence permit, work visa or temporary stay visa and who have remained in Portugal for the previous three years.  > The social insertion income was formerly granted to foreigners holding a Portuguese residence permit only. Apart from financial support, the policy includes housing and health initiatives, educational programmes, employment services etc.	EMN 2006: 15	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to social benefits and socio-economic rights	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5370	Portugal	EU enlargement free labour market access	2006	2004 EU enlargement - Portugal lifted its restrictions to labour market access of the 2004 EU enlargement countries on 1 May 2006.	https://ec.europa.eu/eures/main.jsp?acro=free&lang=en&step=2&accessing=0&content=1&restrictions=1&fromCountryId=RO&countryId=PT&langChanged=true [accessed on 19.08.2013]	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Free mobility rights/agreements	All migrant workers	EU citizens	Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, Poland, Slovakia and Slovenia	Less restrictive		
5371	Portugal	widening of social allowance to children to all legal migrants	2006	Decree Law 41/2006 of 21 February - extended the attribution of family social allowance to foreign children and youngsters who hold a legal title of permanence, to refugees, and to holders of temporary protection titles.  > Thereby, the mentioned Decree Law puts on the same level resident foreigners, the holders of permanence permit, the refugees, and the holders of temporary protection title for attribution of family social allowance to children and youngsters. Such social benefits were formerly only granted to foreigners holding residence permits.	EMN 2006: 15	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to social benefits and socio-economic rights	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5372	Portugal	new portuguese passport	2006	Decree Law 138/2006 of 26 July - modified the legal system on granting and issuing Portuguese passports by adjusting it to the new information technology, encompassed in the process of creating and implementing a new Electronic Portuguese Passport.	EMN 2006: 15	Major change	National policy	Border and land control	Identification documents	All	Citizens	N/A	More restrictive		
5373	Portugal	EU directive on reception of asylum seekers implemented	2006	Law 20/2006 of 23 June amended the Law on Asylum - transposed into the Portuguese juridical order Directive 2003/9/CE of the Council of 27 January, laying down minimum standards for the reception of asylum seekers in the Member States, defining the material conditions for the reception and health care, as well as administrative and juridical guarantees.	EMN 2006: 17	Minor change	National policy	Border and land control	Institutional capacities	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5374	Portugal	shorter residence requirements for naturalisation	2006	Organic Law 2/2006 of 17 April amended the Law of Nationality - lowers the residency requirement for the naturalisaiton of citizens from non-portuguese speaking countries from ten to six years, herewith egalizing the conditions with those for nationals of Portuguese speaking countries (this basically returned to the situation before 1994) > Law 2/2006 changed the Law of Nationality 37/81 in precisely the same lines they had been proposing for years: any waiting privilege as a function of nationality of the origin disappeared so that a period of six years of residence would be asked from all applicants, Lusophone or not.	Sabino et al. 2010: 30; Espinoza 2010: 10	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	Specific nationalities	Non-Portuguese speaking countries	Less restrictive		
5375	Portugal	eased access to Portugal-born children of foreigners	2006	Organic Law 2/2006 of 17 April amended the Law of Nationality - will give third generation migrants automatic access to Portuguese citizenship from the time of birth and ease access for second generation migrants > If one parent is native-born in Portugal, the child gets Portuguese citizenship at birth. If both parents are foreign-born, the child born in Portugal can obtain Portuguese nationality once one of the ancestors has had 5 years continuous legal residence in Portugal. Other dispositions included in the law facilitate naturalisation for persons who have attended basic schooling in Portugal and for persons who passed part of their childhood in the country (10 years of continuous residence in Portugal by the age of 18). Law 2/2006 changed the Law of Nationality 37/81 in precisely the same lines they had been proposing for years: jus soli was reintroduced as a legal principle to acquire nationality.	EMN 2006: 17; SOPEMI 2006: 208; Espinoza 2010: 10	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5376	Portugal	Resettlement programme created	2007	In 2007, the Portuguese government became an official resettlement country - by establishing an annual quota of a minimum of 30 refugees to be resettled in the country through a Resolution of the Council of Ministers. > Resettlement in Portugal began under an ad-hoc programme in 2006 - when two groups of refugees were resettled. Firstly, twelve persons of various nationalities (DRC, Ivory Coast and Liberia) from the Moroccan border with Algeria who had been repeatedly refouled by Moroccan authorities to the desert, followed by a smaller group of five persons (Ethiopian and Eritrean) who were found in very severe conditions aboard a boat in the Mediterranean Sea near Malta. All 17 persons were recognised as refugees by the Portuguese government and accordingly were issued refugee cards.	http://www.resettlement.eu//country/portugal [accessed on 30.09.2013]	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Resettlement programmes	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5377	Portugal	new traveller control system	2007	In 2007 Portugal developed and implemented the project RAPID (Automatic Recognition of Automatically Identified Passengers) - the worlds first system to allow for an automated control of passengers holding electronic passports, via biometric facial recognition.	EMN 2007: 8	Major change	National policy	Border and land control	Surveillance technology/control powers	All	All	N/A	More restrictive		
5378	Portugal	simplification of the permit system	2007	Law 23/2007 of 4 July on the Entry, Stay, Departure and Expulsion of Foreigners - introduced a unique residence title granting residence permits according to the type of activity undertaken (professional activities, research and highly skilled activities, study, volunteer or apprenticeships and family reunification) > The changes reduce the former nine juridical categories to two types of visa: a temporary stay visa and a residence visa. The former is intended for people who come temporarily to Portugal to pursue medical treatment, for research, or for temporary professional tasks for periods of less than six months. The residence visa is given to people who intend to set up permanent residence in Portugal for purposes such as regular work, highly qualified work, entrepreneurial activities, study or family reunion. Persons with a residence visa are therefore supposed to have this transformed into a residence permit within four  months after arrival.	EMN 2007: 2, 13	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5379	Portugal	slightly quicker access to permanent residency	2007	Law 23/2007 of 4 July on the Entry, Stay, Departure and Expulsion of Foreigners - transposed Directive 2003/7109/EC of 25 November concerning long term residents, granting the status of long term resident to those individuals who have been residents for over 5 years.	EMN 2007: 2, 13	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to permanent residency	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5380	Portugal	family reunification broadened	2007	Law 23/2007 of 4 July on the Entry, Stay, Departure and Expulsion of Foreigners -  expands the concept of residents´ family member   > The legal concept of family member includes the spouse; minor or incapacitated children in their care and adopted minors, as well as unmarried adult children, dependant on the couple or on one of the spouses, who are studying in an educational establishment in Portugal; direct first degree ascendants of the resident or their spouse (who are their responsibility) and minor siblings (who are under the tutelage of the resident). Also, the legal regime for family encompasses the family members of a foreign citizen resident in Portugal who are outside the national territory or who have entered the country legally. Family reunification can also be recognised in favour of a partner who is in a common law union, present in the national territory or outside it, with the resident foreign citizen and minor or incapacitated unmarried children, including the adopted children of the common law partner, as long as they have been legally entrusted to the said partner.	EMN 2009: 37	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5381	Portugal	case by case regularisation mechanism introduced	2007	Law 23/2007 of 4 July on the Entry, Stay, Departure and Expulsion of Foreigners - allows irregular migrants to regularise their status on a case-by-case basis.  > The requirements are to have legally entered Portugal, to have a work contract and to pay Social Security contributions.	SOPEMI 2011: 312	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Regularisation	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
