5604	Romania	Law 331/2015, in force since 24 December 2015  introduced a new asylum procedure with respect to the EU Common European Asylum System	2015	Law 331/2015, in force since 24 December 2015  introduced a new asylum procedure with respect to the EU Common European Asylum System - each applicants fingerprints are taken and sent to a database called Eurodac (Eurodac Regulation). These data are used to help identify the country responsible for the asylum application (Dublin Regulation). Asylum applicants receive practical material support on their reception, such as housing and food (Reception Conditions Directive). An asylum applicant is interviewed by a case worker, with the help of an interpreter, to determine whether he/she may qualify for any form of international protection (Qualification Directive and Asylum Procedures Directive).If asylum is not granted to the applicant in the first instance, this refusal may be appealed in court.	Vasile, O., & Androniceanu, A. (2018). An overview of the Romanian asylum policies. Sustainability, 10(5), 1461.   Page 10	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
