5696	Slovakia	restitution of citizenship	1990	Act No. 88/1990 was adopted - allowed for restitution of Czechoslovak citizenship to emigrants who had lost it in the period of communist rule.	Barsova 2013: 1; Drbohlav et al 2009: 54	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	Diaspora	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5697	Slovakia	refugee status created	1990	In November 1990, the Refugee Act  was passed by the Czechoslovak Parliament - giving the Ministry of Interior responsibility for dealing with this issue. > The law was taken over by the Czech and Slovak Republics in 1993.	Drbohlav 1994: 97; SOPEMI 1995: 141	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5698	Slovakia	geneva convention ratified	1991	The 1951 Convention and the 1967 Protocol relating to the Status of Refugees were passed (and ratified) in October 1991 by Czechoslovakia > The ratification was taken over by the Czech and Slovak Republics in 1993.	Drbohlav 1994: 93	N/A	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
5699	Slovakia	very liberal rules on labour migrants	1991	1991 Employment law - granted foreigners the same right to work as citizens	http://www.zakonyprolidi.cz/cs/1991-1/zneni-0 [accessed on 18.02.2014]	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5700	Slovakia	integration programme for refugees	1991	In December 1991 the Czechoslovak government adopted  a regulation targeting the integration of refugees. > The programmes involved the provision of housing and the mediation of employment and social assistance. These programmes work at some level untill today.	Drbohlav et al 2009: 46; Sisova 2005	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Language, housing and cultural integration programmes	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5701	Slovakia	liberal residency permit system introduced	1992	1992 Law on the stay of foreigners (Aliens Act) - introduced a standard modern structure of residence statuses: a short-term residence permit up to six months, a long-term residence permit up to one year and a permanent residence permit.  > The Act allowed foreigners to submit an application for a long-term stay on Czech territory.	SOPEMI 1995: 141; Drbohlav et al 2009: 46; http://www.psp.cz/sqw/sbirka.sqw?cz=123&r=1992 [accessed on 18.02.2014]	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5702	Slovakia	permanent residency possible for humanitarian reasons	1992	1992 Law on the stay of foreigners (Aliens Act) - made only humanitarian cases eligible to permanent residence permits. > Other migrants were not permitted to change their statuses from a long-term to a permanent one.	SOPEMI 1995: 141; Drbohlav et al 2009: 46; http://www.psp.cz/sqw/sbirka.sqw?cz=123&r=1992 [accessed on 18.02.2014]	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Access to permanent residency	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5703	Slovakia	permanent residency possible for family members of citizens	1992	1992 Law on the stay of foreigners (Aliens Act) - made only family members of Czech citizens eligible to permanent residence permits. > Other migrants were not permitted to change their statuses from a long-term to a permanent one.	SOPEMI 1995: 141; Drbohlav et al 2009: 46; http://www.psp.cz/sqw/sbirka.sqw?cz=123&r=1992 [accessed on 18.02.2014]	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to permanent residency	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5704	Slovakia	free access to labour market for Czech nationals	1992	In anticipation of the dissolution of the CSFR, the Czech and Slovak Republics signed a treaty - granting the citizens of either state free access to the labour market of the other signatory state.	SOPEMI 1995: 141	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Free mobility rights/agreements	All migrant workers	Specific nationalities	Czech Republic	Less restrictive		
5705	Slovakia	free access of citizens to Czech labour market	1992	In anticipation of the dissolution of the CSFR, the Czech and Slovak Republics signed a treaty granting the citizens of either state free access to the labour market of the other signatory state.	SOPEMI 1995: 141	Major change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Exit	Free mobility rights/agreements	All migrant workers	Citizens	N/A	Less restrictive		
5706	Slovakia	Slovak Republic created	1993	1 January 1993 Dissolution of Czechoslovakia into the Czech and Slovak Federal Republic. > As of January 1993, the new Slovak Republic assumed all laws and documents passed by the Federal Parliament concerning migration on the territory of the former Czech and Slovak Federal Republic after 1989.	SOPEMI 1995: 141	N/A	N/A	N/A	Contextual elements	N/A	N/A	N/A	N/A		
5707	Slovakia	first migration policy strategy	1993	Principles of the Migration Policy passed via the Government Resolution no. 846/1993 - a short and vague document listed 10 principles on mobility and residence by foreigners in Slovakia. > These were:  1 Obligation of the State to maintain basic human rights and freedoms. 2 Respect the general rules of international law and international treaties governing the legal status of foreigners in respect of reciprocity and equality . 3 Promoting and supporting coordinated, joint action of the international community to flexibly respond to the trends of migration in Central and Eastern Europe. 4 Interdependence of addressing migration issues with finding and implementing steps to ensure safety , stability and peaceful coexistence states qualitatively new international cooperation based on trust and understanding states, particularly in Europe. 5 Subordination to foreigners sovereign power of the SR and respect its legal system . 6 Legal regulation of migration issues and the application of these laws . 7 SR sovereign right to decide on the entry of aliens into their territory carried out by applying visa policy . 8 Balance of the extent of the humanitarian assistance to refugees , displaced persons and displaced persons with economic opportunities and social potential of the state . 9 Comprehensive and coordinated solution to the situation of migrants interested bodies , organizations and institutions . 10 Tightening regime , control and technical measures to prevent unwanted migration.	SOPEMI 1997: 155; Balasz 2012: 45; Burianova 2009: 25	N/A	N/A	Legal entry and stay	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
5708	Slovakia	creation of the Migration Authority	1993	Government Resolution Nr . 501/1993 - established the Migration Authority, as the institution responsible for providing comprehensive care for asylum seekers and refugees themselves	Burianova 2009: 25	Major change	National policy	Integration	Institutional capacities	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Change in restrictiveness cannot be assessed		
5709	Slovakia	definition of slovak citizenship	1993	Act No. 40/ 1993 Coll. on Citizenship of the Slovak Republic - set transitory provisions regulating the initial determination of the citizens of the new state: natural persons, who were citizens of the Slovak Republic as of 31 December 1992, are citizens of the Slovak Republic as of 1 January 1993.  > The Czech legislators adopted the same approach as regards overall (collective) initial determination. This prevented de iure statelessness in the wake of the break-up of Czechoslovakia.	EMN 2008: 14	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All	Citizens	N/A	Less restrictive		
5710	Slovakia	ius sanguinis enshrined in law	1993	Act No. 40/ 1993 Coll. on Citizenship of the Slovak Republic - based the acquisition of citizenship on the ius sanguinis principle: A child might acquire Slovak citizenship only if at least one of his parents is a Slovak citizen.	Drbohlav et al 2009: 55	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All	All	N/A	Less restrictive		
5711	Slovakia	naturalisation requirements set	1993	Act No. 40/ 1993 Coll. on Citizenship of the Slovak Republic -  established rules for the naturalisation of immigrants: Applicants have to stay in the Slovak Republic on a permanent residence permit for at least 5 years and during that time usually reside in the country.  > Also, they have to give up the former citizenship, except in specific cases such as asylum. Thus, officially dual citizenship is not permitted, however, in many cases it can be allowed for. The applicant must further prove that he/she has not been lawfully convicted of a premeditated criminal offence during the last 5 years and has to fulfil obligations related to health and social insurance, taxes etc.	EMN 2008: 14; Drbohlav et al 2009: 55	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5712	Slovakia	preferential naturalisation procedure for czechs	1993	Act No. 40/ 1993 Coll. on Citizenship of the Slovak Republic - created a simplified mechanism for Czech citizens, enabling them to acquire Slovak citizenship after permanent residence in the Slovak Republic for at least 2 years, abandonment of czech citizenship and no lawful conviction of a premeditated criminal offence during the last 5 years.	Kusa 2013: 8	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	Specific nationalities	Czech Republic	Less restrictive		
