5798	Slovakia	investors allowed to start working immediately	2010	Amendment to the Aliens Act came into force on 1 January 2010 - allows investors to start working immediately and have up to 90 days to apply for a residence permit.	SOPEMI 2010: 238; SOPEMI 2011: 318	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Investors, entrepreneurs and business people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5799	Slovakia	ICTs allowed to start working immediately	2010	Amendment to the Aliens Act came into force on 1 January 2010 - allows intra-corporate transferees to start working immediately and have up to 90 days to apply for a residence permit.	SOPEMI 2010: 238; SOPEMI 2011: 318	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5800	Slovakia	students allowed to work	2010	Amendment to the Aliens Act came into force on 1 January 2010 - allowed foreign students to work during their studies, stay and look for a work after completion of their studies, and obtain a work permit without having to leave and re-enter the country.	SOPEMI 2010: 238; SOPEMI 2011: 318	Major change	National policy	Integration	Work visa/permit	International students	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5801	Slovakia	employers to inform police of expiration of workers' contracts	2010	Amendment to the Aliens Act came into force on 1 January 2010 - requires Slovak employers to inform the Police of the expiration of foreign employees job contracts within three days of expiration > The aim was to reduce the overstaying of foreigners who lose their jobs due to the economic crisis	SOPEMI 2010: 238	Minor change	National policy	Border and land control	Employer liabilities	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
5802	Slovakia	department for migration and integration abolished	2010	The Department for the Migration and Integration of Foreigners of the Ministry of Labour, Social Affairs and Family established in 2007 for the area of labour migration and integration of foreigners was abolished on 1 April 2010	EMN 2010: 17	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Institutional capacities	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Change in restrictiveness cannot be assessed		
5803	Slovakia	readmission agreement with Serbia	2010	2010 Protocol between the Government of the Slovak Republic and the Government of the Republic of Serbia on the implementation of the Agreement between the European Community and the Republic of Serbia on the readmission of persons residing without authorization , signed in Brussels on 18 September 2007	http://www.mzv.sk/servlet/content?MT=/App/WCM/main.nsf/vw_ByID/zahranicna__politika&TG=BlankMaster&URL=/App/WCM/main.nsf/vw_ByID/medzinarodne_zmluvy-zmluvy_podla_predmetu&CTYPE=readmisia&OpenDocument=Y&LANG=SK&PAGE_VSETKYZMLUVY-DWMCEA-7XEM76=2 [accessed on 18.02.2014]	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Exit	Readmission agreements	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	Those transiting through or originating from Serbia	More restrictive		
5804	Slovakia	new sanctions against irregular employment	2011	Act No. 223/2011 amending the 2005 Act on Illegal Work and Illegal Employment - implemented the directive  2009/52/EC regarding sanctions against employers of irregular third-country nationals. > It extends the former general prohibition of illegal employment to illegally staying third-country nationals, and the category of persons bound by this prohibition is extended to include natural persons who are not entrepreneurs. In case this prohibition is violated, the sanctions include, besides fines, employers exclusion from participating in public procurement	EMN 2011: 35, 49; http://migrationtothecentre.migraceonline.cz/en/an-overview-of-the-migration-policies-and-trends-slovakia [accessed on 07.11.2013]	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Border and land control	Employer liabilities	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
5805	Slovakia	migration policy strategy	2011	Government Resolution no. 59/2011 of 31 August 2011 approved a comprehensive national migration policy document entitled Migration Policy of the Slovak Republic with Horizon 2020 - focusing on attracting the highly skilled and those able to fill labour shortages. The document also calls for a plan on return migration and specific programmes to facilitate the economic integration of Slovaks returning from abroad.	SOPEMI 2012: 268	N/A	N/A	Legal entry and stay	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
