5807	Slovakia	stricter criteria for temporary residence	2012	Act 404/2011 on Residence of Aliens came into effect in January 2012 - tightened particular conditions of application for temporary residence  > It preserves the complicated distribution of migrants in a wide range of categories according to the type and purpose of stay (more than 20 different stays)	SOPEMI 2013: 292; http://www.migraceonline.cz/cz/e-knihovna/novy-zakon-o-pobyte-cudzincov-v-sr [accessed on 18.02.2014]	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
5808	Slovakia	Blue card implemented	2012	Act 404/2011 on Residence of Aliens came into effect in January 2012 - implemented the directive no. 2009/50/EC on the Blue Card > The Blue Card is work permit issued for three years for the highly skilled immigrants. Immigrants with the university education or history of five years professional employment are considered highly skilled. The applicants for the Blue Card must produce confirmation on job contract with salary exceeding 1.5 times Slovak average salary, diploma on qualification, confirmation on job vacancy issued by Slovak Central Office for Work, Social Affairs and Family, and health confirmation.	http://migrationtothecentre.migraceonline.cz/en/an-overview-of-the-migration-policies-and-trends-slovakia [accessed on 07.11.2013]; http://www.migraceonline.cz/cz/e-knihovna/novy-zakon-o-pobyte-cudzincov-v-sr [accessed on 18.02.2014]	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5809	Slovakia	business permit consolidated	2012	Act 404/2011 on Residence of Aliens came into effect in January 2012 - consolidated the business permit designed for individual entrepreneurs and/or representatives of the companies.  > The applicants have to produce business plan and prove financial resources for doing business in Slovakia; at least 20 times living wages for individual businessmen and 100 times living wages for representatives of companies. The permit is granted for a maximum of three years.	Balaz and Lubyova 2012: 53-54	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Investors, entrepreneurs and business people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	No change		
5810	Slovakia	work permit system consolidated	2012	Act 404/2011 on Residence of Aliens came into effect in January 2012 - created the work permit  designed for the third country nationals, who either already have the permit, or can produce a contract with employer and indicate level of earnings.  > The work permit is granted for a maximum of two years. The law does not stipulate any skills and/or qualification requirements for work permits.	Balaz and Lubyova 2012: 53-54	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	No change		
5811	Slovakia	eased acces to work for family members	2012	Act 404/2011 on Residence of Aliens came into effect in January 2012 - created the family reunification permit for family members of third country nationals who already hold temporary or permanent residence permit.  > The family members also can look for a job and enter the Slovak public health insurance system. The permit is granted for a period of a maximum five years. Family reunification is not new, but under the previous legislation, the spouse of a migrant could enter employment only after 1 year of residence in the country. The new Act changed this, and they can find employment, enter into employment contract or start business immediately after being granted temporary residence on the basis of family reunification.	Balaz and Lubyova 2012: 53-54; http://www.migraceonline.cz/cz/e-knihovna/novy-zakon-o-pobyte-cudzincov-v-sr [accessed on 18.02.2014]	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Work visa/permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5812	Slovakia	student permit consolidated	2012	Act 404/2011 on Residence of Aliens came into effect in January 2012 - created the study permit to cover students in secondary and tertiary education, and is granted for period of study, but six years as a maximum.	Balaz and Lubyova 2012: 53-54	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	International students	All foreign nationalities	N/A	No change		
5813	Slovakia	researcher permit created	2012	Act 404/2011 on Residence of Aliens came into effect in January 2012 - created the research and development permit for research workers and staff in R&D institutions.  > The permit is given for a maximum of two years, and the applicant has to produce confirmation on contract and financial arrangements by the host institution.	Balaz and Lubyova 2012: 53-54	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5814	Slovakia	family reunification extended	2012	Act 404/2011 on Residence of Aliens came into effect in January 2012 - extends the category of family members of a Union citizen to a partner with whom a Union citizen has a durable relationship.	EMN 2012: 23	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5815	Slovakia	family reunfication for refugees extended	2012	Act 404/2011 on Residence of Aliens came into effect in January 2012 - grants a national visa to the family members of aliens with asylum status and to aliens under subsidiary protection, provided that they do not pose a threat to the state security or public order.	EMN 2012: 23	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members of irregular migrants or refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5816	Slovakia	new system for permanent residency	2012	Act 404/2011 on Residence of Aliens came into effect in January 2012 - introduces three types of permanent residence (permanent residence for five years, for unlimited period of time, and long-term residence), and defines the conditions under which the alien can apply for it.  > The act reduces the minimum required period of a residence permit from five to four years on the basis of which the holder of a permanent residence permit can apply for permanent residence for an unlimited period of time.	EMN 2012: 13; http://migrationtothecentre.migraceonline.cz/en/an-overview-of-the-migration-policies-and-trends-slovakia [accessed on 07.11.2013]	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to permanent residency	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
