5952	Slovenia	continuity of citizenship	1991	1991 Citizenship Act - Art. 39 stipulates that any person, who held citizenship of Slovenia and of Yugoslavia according to existing valid regulations, was considered ex lege to be a citizen of Slovenia on the day when the Act came into force.  > The primary rule of the initial determination of citizens was complemented with the optional acquisition of Slovenian citizenship for citizens of other former Yugoslavian republics who had permanent residence in Slovenia on the day of the Plebiscite for the Independence and Autonomy of Slovenia on 23 December 1990, and who actually lived in Slovenia (art.40).	Medved 2013: 5, 7	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All	Citizens	N/A	Less restrictive		
5953	Slovenia	ius sanguinis laid down	1991	1991 Citizenship Act - laid down the principle of ius sanguinis and only the limited application of ius soli: At birth a natural person obtains Slovenian citizenship ex lege when both parents are Slovenian citizens and when the child is born in Slovenia and at least one parent is a Slovenian citizen. > Children born abroad with one parent of Slovenian citizenship at the time of the childs birth can acquire Slovenian citizenship by registration. Registration can be initiated within eighteen years after birth by the Slovenian parent without the consent of the other parent.	Medved 2013: 11	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All	All	N/A	Less restrictive		
5954	Slovenia	naturalisation criteria laid down	1991	1991 Citizenship Act - laid down the principle of  ordinary naturalisation which can be requested after ten years of residency in Slovenia, of which the five years prior to the application must be without interruption.	Medved 2013: 11	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
5955	Slovenia	facilitated naturalisation for Slovenian descendants	1991	1991 Citizenship Act - laid down the principle of  facilitated naturalisation for Slovenian emigrants and their descendants, which can be naturalised after only one year of uninterrupted residence. > Release from current citizenship is not necessarily required.	Medved 2013: 13	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	Diaspora	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
