5987	Slovenia	permanent residency granted to those deprived in 1992	1999	Settling of the Status of Citizens of Other SFRY Successor States in the Republic of Slovenia Act of 1999 > Background: In 1992 administrative authorities transferred those who did not apply for residency status from the permanent population register to the record of foreigners, without any decision or notification addressed to those concerned to inform them of their new legal position. This secret erasure became known to the public only much later and the exact numbers of these affected remain unknown. The state admitted that 18,305 persons (almost one percent of the population) had been deprived of their legal residence. Later this number was corrected to 25,671 persons. It was only in 1999 that the  Constitutional Court found that the Aliens Act had failed to regulate the transition of the legal status of this group of people to the status of foreigners.	Medved 2013: 8	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Access to permanent residency	All	Specific nationalities	Former Yugoslavian countries	Less restrictive		
5988	Slovenia	sanction of irregular entry and stay raised	1999	1999 Aliens Act - raised the sanction for illegal entry and stay of foreigners.   > The Aliens Act stipulates under Article 99 that persons who assist illegal entry or reside illegally on the territory of Slovenia may be fined between SIT 50,000 (EUR 210,000) and SIT 100,000 (EUR 420,000) for minor offences.	IOM 2004 (Return): 330	Minor change	National policy	Border and land control	Other sanctions	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
