6034	Slovenia	strategy to attract high skilled and students	2009	In December 2009, the Slovene government adopted the Strategy for Economic Migrations for 2010-2020 - recognising an active economic migration policy as a fundamental tool to respond to labour shortages expected to arise in the context of ageing population. The strategy focuses on migration of highly skilled workers, with particular attention to international students and researchers. > There are ten strategic mechanisms elaborated in the action part of the document, such as promotion of migrant entrepreneurship, economic role of diaspora organizations, favourable conditions for mobility of researchers and students (while at the same time taking measures to prevent brain drain from source countries), better integration of immigrants, etc These were however not implemented.	SOPEMI 2012: 270; http://www.migrationonline.cz/en/an-overview-of-the-migration-policies-and-trends-slovenia [accessed on 14.01.2014]	N/A	N/A	Legal entry and stay	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
6035	Slovenia	working group on migration policy established	2009	In 2009 the Inter-departmental working group for the preparation of potential measures for the implementation of the Slovene migration policy was established by the Slovene Government.  > The tasks are - To analyse of the situation in the field of migrations and prepare on that basis adequate measures as well as the starting points to harmonise the national legislation with the EU legal order concerning migrations and eventual abuse of procedures under the national migration legislation, - To steer and coordinate the work of the ministries, bodies and services responsible for migrations, - To perform activities and set grounds for integration policy, - To prepare public awareness raising programmes concerning the aspects, reasons and consequences of migration trends, - To cooperate with scientific and educational institutions and non-governmental organisations working in the field of migrations.	EMN 2010: 7	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Institutional capacities	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Change in restrictiveness cannot be assessed		
6036	Slovenia	shortage occupations now also subject to labour market test	2009	In March 2009, Slovenia abolished the procedure of issuing permits for employment without control of the labour market in professions which are in short supply > In accordance with this, the Employment Service of Slovenia checks for each application for the permit for employment, whether the records of unemployed persons dispose of adequate domestic workers or workers having the same right to employment as citizens of the Republic of Slovenia. In case there are adequate domestic workers available in the records of unemployed persons the employer is refused the application for the issue of the permit for the employment of a foreigner. Before the work permits falling within the quota were no subject to domestic labor market test. Starting in 2009 all work permits were subject to labour market test.	EMN 2009: 3	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
6037	Slovenia	ban on employment in seasonal work	2009	June 2009 Decree on restrictions and prohibition of employment and work of aliens - aims at limiting labour migration from non-EEA countries via a ban on employment in seasonal work for all sectors except agriculture and forestry	SOPEMI 2011: 320; EMN 2009: 11	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Low-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
6038	Slovenia	ban on entrepreneurs and business people from Kosovo	2009	June 2009 Decree on restrictions and prohibition of employment and work of aliens - aims at limiting labour migration from non-EEA countries via a prohibition of issuing new permits for representatives of micro and small companies and for representatives of branch offices to foreigners from Kosovo.	SOPEMI 2011: 320; EMN 2009: 11	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Investors, entrepreneurs and business people	Specific nationalities	Kosovo	More restrictive		
6039	Slovenia	more pressure on employers to use their employment permits	2009	June 2009 Decree on restrictions and prohibition of employment and work of aliens - aims at limiting labour migration from non-EEA countries by not allowing companies to request work permits unless they have a declared vacancy. > This means prohibiting the issuing of permits for employment to employers who did not employ foreigners for whom they already obtained permits for employment within 4 months	SOPEMI 2011: 320; EMN 2009: 11	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Employer liabilities	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
6040	Slovenia	regional distribution of quota introduced, favouring former yugoslavian countries except Kosovo	2009	June 2009 Decree on restrictions and prohibition of employment and work of aliens - aims at limiting labour migration from non-EEA countries by limiting employment of immigrants from certain countries and regions.  > The decree sets a regional distribution of the quotas, 95% of the annual numerical limits are reserved for nationals of one of the successor countries of the former Yugoslavia, with the exception of Kosovars. The remaining 5% are for citizens of Kosovo and all other non-EEA nationals.	SOPEMI 2011: 320; EMN 2009: 11	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Quota/target	All migrant workers	Specific nationalities	All nationalities except former Yugoslav countries and EU countries	More restrictive		
6041	Slovenia	new permits for high skilled	2009	June 2009 Decree on restrictions and prohibition of employment and work of aliens - aims at ensuring the issue of permits for employment to highly qualified workers by allocating 1,000 work permits for highly qualified employments regardless of the state from which the foreigner originates.  >  The foreigner will have to prove at least a higher education, and the employer will have to pay him the salary at least in the amount of 2.5 times the minimum wage.	SOPEMI 2011: 320; EMN 2009: 11	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
