6268	Spain	residency requirement for refugees reduced	1990	In 1990 the Socialist government promoted a new reform of the regulation on nationality - reduced the residency requirements for refugees from ten to five years	Marin et al 2012: 12	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
6269	Spain	residency requirements for all eased	1990	In 1990 the Socialist government promoted a new reform of the regulation on nationality - modified the conditions governing the acquisition of Spanish nationality by residence: Up to then, the period had to be legal and continuous (without long interruptions), immediately before the application for naturalization by residence. After the reform, the continuity condition was dropped, and only the legality of the residence was maintained.	Marin et al 2012: 13	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
6270	Spain	Dublin signed by ES	1990	Spain signed the Dublin convention on 15 June 1990 (entered into force in 1997)	http://www.fdcw.unimaas.nl/staff/files/users/215/Dublin%20System_EGHM.pdf [accessed on 23.07.2013]	N/A	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
6271	Spain	report of foreigners in Spain	1990	Report on the situation of foreigners in Spain (Situacion de los extranjeros en Espana) - was the first concrete government paper that laid out the principles of Spain's migration policy, focussing on the better targetting of immigration (quantitatively and qualitatively), the promotion of integration and the cooperation with third countries to curb irregular migration.	Kreienbrink 2004: 166	N/A	N/A	Legal entry and stay	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
6272	Spain	Migration Policy Plan	1991	Non-legislative proposal from 9 April - outlines a 11-point list laying down the broad directions for Spain's migration policy > It included: - the development of an active immigration policy - the modernisation of border systems - the development of a visa policy - the completion of the regularisation of 1985 - the increased fight against irregular employment - the promotion of social integration of foreigners - the increased possibility of expulsion - the speeding up of asylum procedures - the increased development aid for origin countries - the continuation of european integration and the entry into the Schengen agreement	Kreienbrink 2004: 166; 186	N/A	N/A	Legal entry and stay	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
6273	Spain	regularisation programme for irregular workers	1991	Regularisation programme from 10 June to 10 December 1991 > This operation covered dependent workers and self-employed who were not officially registered but had been living and working in Spain prior to 24 July 1985, and those in Spain prior to 17 May 1991 to whom one of the following conditions applied: 1. They had previousy held residence and work permits, but these were now out of date; 2. They had worked in Spain  for at least nine months during the previous two years and were currently living in Spain; 3. They either had the offer of a job or plans to set up their own business. This second regularisation operation, designed to reduce the number of non-officially registered workers, forms part of a new policy of tightening controls on immigration flows and progamming the intake of new foreign workers	SOPEMI 1992: 76	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Regularisation	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
6274	Spain	Regularisation for family members	1991	A special regularization procedure on grounds of family reunification took place between June 1991 and March 1992 - Although the official goal was to unify families, many unauthorized immigrants with family members legally in Spain used the opportunity to legalize their status.	Cebolla and González Ferrer 2008	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Regularisation	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
6275	Spain	Visa requirements for citizens of Maghreb countries	1991	In May 1991, Spain introduced visa requirement for citizens of Maghreb countries (Morocco, Tunisia, Algeria) wishing to enter Spain in order to conform regulations to 'European community norms'	SOPEMI 1992: 77	N/A	N/A	Legal entry and stay	Travel visa/permit	All migrants	Specific nationalities	Morocco, Tunisia, Algeria	N/A		
