6291	Spain	simplification of asylum procedures	1994	Law No. 9/1994 on asylum and the admission of refugees - abolished the twofold concept of asylum and refuge, as well as aylum on humanitarian grounds and introduced swifter procedures  > The confusing division between the procedures for granting asylum and refugee status was abandoned. Henceforth, only refugee status as outlined in the Geneva Convention existed. Territorial asylum and asylum based on humanitarian grounds were discontinued, with the latter only remaining possible under exceptional provisions in the Aliens Act.	SOPEMI 1995: 118; Focus Migration 2008	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
6292	Spain	work and residence rights for refugees	1994	Law No. 9/1994 on asylum and the admission of refugees - expanded the scope of protection for recognised refugees beyond Geneva Convention standards, so that residence and work permits were automatically granted with the approval of refugee status.	SOPEMI 1995: 118; Focus Migration 2008	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Work visa/permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
6293	Spain	creation of preliminary proceedings allowing exclusion of certain applications from recognition process	1994	Law No. 9/1994 on asylum and the admission of refugees - added, in terms of the harmonisation of asylum rights in the EU, preliminary proceedings as part of the asylum application process which now allowed overtly incorrect or unsubstantiated applications to be excluded from the recognition process (inadmisión a trámite).	SOPEMI 1995: 118; Focus Migration 2008	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
6294	Spain	stronger link between asylum refusal and expulsion	1994	Law No. 9/1994 on asylum and the admission of refugees - introduced a stronger link between the refusal of a request and the applicant's expulsion > Previous regulations had, in principle, enabled a person whose application was rejected to stay in the country. Because this was considered a fundamental reason behind choosing asylum as a path to immigration, the new regulations required persons who were denied asylum to leave the country in accordance with the Geneva Convention, unless they could meet the conditions for obtaining a visa under the provisions of the Aliens Act.	SOPEMI 1995: 118; Focus Migration 2008	Mid-level change	National policy	Exit	Expulsion	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
6295	Spain	First integration Plan	1994	The government published a 'Plan for the social integration of immigrants' > Its aims were: - legal protection against discrimination - equal working conditions as citizens - more education for children and women - spacial regulation of integration, avoiding ghettos - increased participation in public life	Kreienbrink 2004: 291	N/A	N/A	Integration	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
6296	Spain	creation of institutions to foster integration	1994	Creation of a Permanent Observatory on Immigration (OPI) and a Forum for the Social Integration of Immigrants - to foster integration	Kreienbrink 2004: 300	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Institutional capacities	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
6297	Spain	quota raised, but reduced to domestic and agricultural workers only	1995	The 1995 quota, on the results of the 1994 programme, was reduced to only domestic and agricultural workers, and the quota set at a maximum of 25.000	Kreienbrink 2004: 263	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Quota/target	Low-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Change in restrictiveness cannot be assessed		
6298	Spain	introduction of employer sanctions	1995	Law 10/1995 modifies the penal code - introducing sanctions against employers and employees in breach of the law > The law foresees a minimum of 6000 and a maximum of 60000 Euro administrative sanction per irregular worker or a penal sanction of 6 months to 5 years	SOPEMI 1995: 118; Kyrieri 2008	Mid-level change	National policy	Border and land control	Employer liabilities	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
6299	Spain	sanctions created for human trafficking for sexual or work purposes	1995	Law 10/1995 modifies the penal code - introducing a sanction for the trafficking of human beings, with severe penalties for any party directly or indirectly involved in the illegal immigration of workers  > Persons who encourage, induce or facilitate people trafficking from, in transit through or destined for Spain or another EU State for the purpose of sexual exploitation are subject to imprisonment for a period of five (minimum sentence) to ten years. Persons involved in illegal trafficking in labour are subject to imprisonment of between two and five years and to a fine, with no distinction as to whether the victim is a minor or not. Persons who induce or facilitate the illegal immigration of employees into Spain or other EU States are punished in the same way.	SOPEMI 1995: 118	Mid-level change	National policy	Border and land control	Other sanctions	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
