6315	Spain	creation of border surveillance system	1999	The Spanish government approved a plan for intensified surveillance of the Strait of Gibraltar - centered on the implementation of the Integrated System of External Vigilance (SIVE) with a budget of about 150 million euros for the period 1999 to 2004. > The monitoring system (Sistema Integral de Vigilancia Exterior, SIVE) combines long-range radar, thermal cameras, night vision equipment, infrared beams, helicopters, etc. in order to close off these sea routes.	Focus Migration 2008; MPI 2007	Mid-level change	National policy	Border and land control	Surveillance technology/control powers	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
6316	Spain	high-skilled exempted from labour market test	2000	Law 4/2000 on the Rights and Freedoms of Foreigners in Spain and their Integration (LOEX) of January 12, 2000 - exempts from the national employment situation highly qualified professionals, including technical and scientific staff engaged by public bodies, universities or research, development and innovation centres operated by companies.	EMN 2010	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
6317	Spain	permanent regularisation mechanism for those in Spain for 2 years possible	2000	Law 4/2000 on the Rights and Freedoms of Foreigners in Spain and their Integration (LOEX) of January 12, 2000 - laid down the possibility of granting a temporary residence permit to the undocumented alien who could show an uninterrupted stay of 2 years in Spain, was registered in the Municipal Population Register (known as Padrón Municipal) when he applied and had financial resources. > This was one of the most polemic articles in Law 4/2000, which the Popular Parliamentary Group openly disputed. As application of this Law required the development of rules, and Law 4/2000 never had Implementation Rules, the controversial provision (now modified by Law 8/2000) was never applied in practice.	Gortazar 2002	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Regularisation	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
6318	Spain	massive widening of socio-economic rights granted to irregular migrants	2000	Law 4/2000 on the Rights and Freedoms of Foreigners in Spain and their Integration (LOEX) of January 12, 2000 - widened most socio-economic rights to aliens in an irregular situation, such as the right to education in the same conditions as Spanish people; the right of all aliens, whatever their legal situation might be, to emergency public health care, and the right to public health care for all aliens who are minors and for pregnant women before and after the birth; the right to assistance as regards housing for aliens registered in the municipal census; and the right to basic social services and facilities (although such basic facilities were not clarified) > Only the right to work and  to receive facilities and services of the Social Security under the same conditions as Spanish nationals and the right to family reunion were restricted to aliens who were residents in regular situations.	Gortazar 2002	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to social benefits and socio-economic rights	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
6319	Spain	massive widening of access to justice and political rights to irregular migrants	2000	Law 4/2000 on the Rights and Freedoms of Foreigners in Spain and their Integration (LOEX) of January 12, 2000 - widened access to justice and political rights to aliens in an irregular situation. They were now granted the freedom to meet and demonstrate, freedom of association, freedom to strike and freedom to join a Trade Union; and the right to the assistance of a lawyer at any proceedings concerning refusal to permit entry or expulsion or obligatory departure from Spanish territory and in all proceedings regarding asylum. If they were registered in the census, they would also have the right to free legal assistance for any other proceedings, if they could show lack of funds, in order to litigate. > Only the right to freedom of movement throughout Spanish territory and the right to vote in municipal elections were restricted to aliens who were residents in regular situations.	Gortazar 2002	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to justice and political rights	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
6320	Spain	irregular entry and work were not any more reasons for expulsion	2000	Law 4/2000 on the Rights and Freedoms of Foreigners in Spain and their Integration (LOEX) of January 12, 2000 - according to this Law, being in Spain in an irregular situation or working without having obtained the relevant work permit did not constitute infringements which could give rise to expulsion from Spanish territory.	Gortazar 2002	Major change	National policy	Exit	Expulsion	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
6321	Spain	introduction of requirement to justify refusal of visa	2000	Law 4/2000 on the Rights and Freedoms of Foreigners in Spain and their Integration (LOEX) of January 12, 2000 -  includes the need to explain the refusal to provide a visa. > Exceptionally and temporarily the Government could lay down cases in which the refusal might not be explained (citizens of specific countries or geographical zones). However, even in these cases, if the person accredits being entitled to a subjective right to stay in Spain (i.e. in order to exercise his right to family reunion) the refusal must be explained	Gortazar 2002	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Access to justice and political rights	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
6322	Spain	officially establishes the annual quota system	2000	Law 4/2000 on the Rights and Freedoms of Foreigners in Spain and their Integration (LOEX) of January 12, 2000 - laid down that annually the Government will establish a contingent of workers in which it will fix the number and the characteristics of the offers of employment made to alien workers not resident in Spain.  > As is known, these contingents have been approved annually since 1993, but only with Law 4/2000 did it acquire recognition in a regulation with the rank of Organic law.	Gortazar 2002	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Quota/target	Low-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	No change		
6323	Spain	official recognition of right to family reunification	2000	Law 4/2000 on the Rights and Freedoms of Foreigners in Spain and their Integration (LOEX) of January 12, 2000 -  recognised for the first time family reunification as a rule with the rank of Law	Gortazar 2002	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	No change		
