6357	Spain	creation of occupation shortage list	2004	Royal Decree 2393/2004 of December 2004 regulating the Organic Law 4/2000 - created the Catalogue of Hard-to-Fill Jobs (CODC), which is updated quarterly, to link immigration and access to the labour market, after assessing the national employment situation and the need for manual labour by activity sector and by province. > The shortage list applied to the General Scheme entry and does exempt workers from individual labour market tests. For jobs not on the shortage list, employers must submit to a labour market test (negative certification). Most labour migration comes through these channels.	EMN 2007	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
6358	Spain	new seasonal workers program	2004	Royal Decree 2393/2004 of December 2004 regulating the Organic Law 4/2000 - created the Collective Management of Hiring in the Countries of Origin Procedure to allow seasonal workers to work in Spain > This procedure is especially attractive for larger employers to use the foreign recruitment system organized by the Spanish Ministry of Labour in co-operation with counterparts in sending countries (contingent). The latter defines caps for each region and occupation. In some cases, training may be offered, ranging from basic language and workplace safety to custom vocational training, with subsidies from the Spanish government. Immigrants must remain in the same sector and region for the first year, although they may change employer. Seasonal work has no caps. Priority is given mainly to countries with agreements on the management of migration flows, signed with Spain and people are recruited in the origin country	EMN 2007	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Recruitment/assisted migration programmes	Low-skilled workers	Specific nationalities	Those with agreements with Spain	Less restrictive		
6359	Spain	work access for international students after three years	2004	Royal Decree 2393/2004 of December 2004 regulating the Organic Law 4/2000 - provides the possibility that a national of a third country who has remained for three years studying in Spain can directly access a residence and work permit without visa.  > However, it excludes this possibility to those who have been scholarships or subsidized by public or private agencies as part of any cooperation or development programmes in the country of origin.	EMN 2009	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Work visa/permit	International students	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
6360	Spain	regularisation programme for irregular workers	2005	Exceptional Regularisation 2005 > Applications for regularisation, which had to be filed by employers (except for domestic workers), had to contain a job offer guaranteeing a job for the equivalent of a minimum of six-months full-time employment (three months in agriculture). As of spring 2005, employers had to be registered with the social security regime in their sector and employees with their municipality at least since 8 August 2004. They had to meet the job requirements and to have had no police record for at least five years.  For domestic workers, it was admitted for the first time the possibility of adding up all the different contracts they had at different households (they generally work per hour) in order to be able to regularize. However, social secutiry contributions had to be paid by the employee. As a result, many regularized through this method but stop paying their contributions relatively soon afterwards.	SOPEMI 2006: 214	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Regularisation	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
