6368	Spain	regularisation mechanism	2006	Settlement Programme - created a continuous discretionary regularisation mechanism for undocumented immigrants who demonstrate integration.  > The new scheme included two mechanisms: 1. Labour Settlement applies to non-nationals who have lived in the country for at least 2 years and can prove a priori and with the support of trade unions the existence of a labor relationship with an employer of at least 1-year duration.  2. Social Settlement applies to non-nationals who have lived in the country for at least 3 years and can provide a posteriori a work contract of at least 1-year duration at the time the application is submitted. In addition, other requirements need to be met: existence of family links in Spain (spouse or civil partner, direct descendants or direct relatives in the ascending line) or the establishment of social links within the local community. In addition to the foregoing, there are two other permits, Family Settlement and Exceptional Circumstances, which also allow the regularization of migrants but without taking into consideration labor market integration. Family Settlement can only be obtained by non-nationals whose parents were originally Spanish and applicants are not required to have lived in Spain. Exceptional Circumstances includes reasons under the protection of the law on the Right to Asylum and Refugee Status. This permit is granted for humanitarian reasons to victims of human trafficking, domestic violence, and those who suffer from an illness that cannot be treated at the country of origin.	SOPEMI 2008: 278; Sabater and Domingo 2012: 194	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Regularisation	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
