6937	Sweden	reform of language instruction system	1990	February 1990 bill introduced by government - to reform Swedish language instruction for adult immigrants. > At present, this instruction is divided into basic instruction, which is a municipal responsibility, and advanced SFI, substituting an integrated foundation course for which the municipalities will be responsible.	SOPEMI 1991: 67	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Language, housing and cultural integration programmes	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Change in restrictiveness cannot be assessed		
6938	Sweden	Alien Board set up to hear appeals	1992	In January 1992 the Aliens Board was set up by the government - as a separate authority to hear appeals under aliens and citizenship legislation.	SOPEMI 1994: 96	Major change	National policy	Integration	Institutional capacities	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
6939	Sweden	Young workers exchange agreement with Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania	1992	Sweden entered into bilateral agreements on work practice for young people with Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania.	SOPEMI 1994: 96	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	Specific nationalities	Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania	Less restrictive		
6940	Sweden	visa requirements introduced for ex-Yugoslavian countries	1992	In March 1992 visas were introduced for Serbians, for Montenegrans and Macedonians in October 1992 > Background: By 1993, the number of refugees from Bosnia-Herzegovina, Croatia, Macedonia, and Kosovo had grown so large that the government introduced visa requirements for persons coming from the former Yugoslavia. According to Statistics Sweden, the country received 208,700 asylum seekers between 1989 and 1993, of which 115,900 (56 percent) were from the former Yugoslavia.	SOPEMI 1994: 96; MPI 2006	N/A	N/A	Legal entry and stay	Travel visa/permit	All	Specific nationalities	Serbia, Macedonia, Montenegro	N/A		
6941	Sweden	stricter measures on refugee smuggling	1994	1994 amendments to the Aliens Act - introducing stricter measures to combat refugee smuggling, increasing the penalty for human smuggling.	SOPEMI 1995: 122	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Border and land control	Other sanctions	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
6942	Sweden	temporary protection visa created	1994	1994 amendments to the Aliens Act - introduced a temporary protection system  > However, the general rule is still to award a permanent residence permit to persons permitted to stay in Sweden on asylum-related grounds. The new temporary protection system is intended to deal with mass movement situations and other serious crises	SOPEMI 1995: 122	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
6943	Sweden	proposal to easier expel criminal foreigners	1994	1994 amendments to the Aliens Act - made it easier to expel foreigners convicted of criminal offences from Sweden.	SOPEMI 1995: 122	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Exit	Expulsion	Specific categories	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
6944	Sweden	Free movement of workers within EEA	1994	Agreement between Sweden and EEA on free labour migration - forbids any discrimination based on the nationality of European citizens who wish to take up employment in Sweden > As a consequence of the entry into force of the Agreement on the European Economic Area, workers from Austria, Finland and Sweden were granted the right of free movement in the internal market before the accession of those countries to the European Union.	Boguslaw 2012: 39; OECD 2012 (Free mobility): 39	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Free mobility rights/agreements	All migrant workers	EU citizens	EU member states at that time	Less restrictive		
6945	Sweden	family reunification for European workers	1994	Agreement between Sweden and EEA on free labour migration - grants European citizens the right to family reunification, regardless of the nationality of the family members	Boguslaw 2012: 39; OECD 2012 (Free mobility): 39	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	EU citizens	EU member states at that time	Less restrictive		
6946	Sweden	Free movement for Swedish workers	1994	Agreement between Sweden and EEA on free labour migration - forbids any discrimination based on the nationality of Swedish citizens who wish to take up employment in another Member State. > As a consequence of the entry into force of the Agreement on the European Economic Area, workers from Austria, Finland and Sweden were granted the right of free movement in the internal market before the accession of those countries to the European Union.	Boguslaw 2012: 39; OECD 2012 (Free mobility): 39	Major change	National policy	Exit	Free mobility rights/agreements	All migrant workers	Citizens	N/A	Less restrictive		
6947	Sweden	more flexibility in refugee integration system	1994	In 1994, the refugee integration program was revised - to allow greater flexibility in management: refugees were also allowed to decide where they would like to live.	MPI 2006; Boguslaw 2012	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Language, housing and cultural integration programmes	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
