6950	Sweden	extension of refugee definition	1997	1996 amendments to the Aliens Act entered into force in 1997 - applied a broader interpretation of the Geneva convention with regard to providing protection to asylum seekers.  > New categories were added for protection status: i) people in fear of death penalty, torture and other degrading punishment, for ii) persons in war-zones and iii) escaping environmental disasters. War refugees and de-facto category were taken away. In particular, applicants can be recognized as refugees even if they originated from safe countries.	SOPEMI 2003b: 275; Mayda 2004: 13	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
6951	Sweden	more appeal opportunities for asylum seekers	1997	1996 amendments to the Aliens Act entered into force in 1997 - gave more opportunities to appeal asylum decisions	SOPEMI 1998: 168	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Access to justice and political rights	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
6952	Sweden	family reunification restricted	1997	1996 amendments to the Aliens Act entered into force in 1997 -  restricts the immigration of relatives to married couples, cohabitants and unmarried children under the age of 18.	SOPEMI 1998: 168	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
6953	Sweden	Dublin entered into force in SE	1997	On 1 October 1997, the Dublin Convention entered into force in Sweden - determining the state responsible for assessing asylum claims of third country nationals	http://www.fdcw.unimaas.nl/staff/files/users/215/Dublin%20System_EGHM.pdf [accessed on 23.07.2013]	Major change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
6954	Sweden	Readmission agreement with Romania	1997	Romania has concluded a readmission agreement with Sweden	SOPEMI 1999: 200	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Exit	Readmission agreements	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	Those transiting through or originating from Romania	More restrictive		
6955	Sweden	National Integration Office created	1998	The National Integration Board was set up in June 1998 -  responsible for implementing measures designed to attain the objectives of integration policy, to monitor and assess developments concerning ethnic and cultural plurality in the community as a whole. > A Swedish Integration Board was set up to monitor integration policy. It was closed down in 2007.	SOPEMI 2001a: 258	Major change	National policy	Integration	Institutional capacities	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
6956	Sweden	new integration strategy	1998	New integration policy Sweden, the future and a pluralist society  From immigration policy to integration policy' adopted by Parliament in December 1998 - to ensure equal rights and opportunities for all, regardless of ethnic or cultural origin, and to promote social cohesion and development in an atmosphere of tolerance and mutual respect.  > The integration policy meant that immigrant policy and immigration policy were separated.	SOPEMI 2001a: 246	N/A	N/A	Integration	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
6957	Sweden	expulsion not any more executed by police, but by Migration Board	1999	In January 1999, the Migration Board became the executive authority for carrying out expulsion orders - taking over from the police though their assistance is still available when force may be required.	SOPEMI 2001a: 257	Minor change	National policy	Exit	Institutional capacities	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Change in restrictiveness cannot be assessed		
6958	Sweden	citizenship granted to long term residents with difficulties to prove their identity	1999	Amendment to citizenship law in 1999 - granting people who are unable to prove their identity the possibility to obtain Swedish citizenship if they have resided in Sweden for at least eight years and can provide some evidence that their declared identity is correct.	SOPEMI 2001a: 257	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
6959	Sweden	Report on how to increase labour immigration and subsequent policy debate	2000	Joint report of the Swedish Migration Board and the Labour Market Board to suggest mechanisms for increasing labour immigration - projected labour shortages in a number of sectors and proposed bilateral agreements with sending countries for recruitment for skilled occupations, which was not followed up. The proposals led to changes in the Aliens Act granting exemptions from labour permits for certain artists and athletes, as well as specialists within international corporations working in Sweden for a maximum of one year. These changes took effect on 1 April 2002. > From the start, the social partners staked out positions regarding reform. While the trade union confederation LO expressed its determination to maintain an influential voice in any labour migration system, the employers' federation SN presented its own proposal for a job-search visa with no union control over hiring decisions or work permits. The SN proposal included full labour market mobility for those who found a job in Sweden. The SN proposed opening the Swedish labour market to future EU member countries in 2003, even before their accession, and the creation of a three-month job-search visa for third-country nationals. The LO policy paper noted that even with full implementation of activation policies, demographic pressure and rising dependency ratios would still make international recruitment necessary. LO, however, wanted to ensure that international recruitment did not lead to unfair competition, by guaranteeing that immigrants were protected on the labour market through indefinite contracts, mobility and safety of status even if unemployed, access to training, and oversight. LO also proposed a labour market opinion, to be provided by the county LMB, with approval contingent not just on a job offer but on a judgement that the occupation was in shortage.	OECD 2011: 59, 60	N/A	N/A	Legal entry and stay	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
6960	Sweden	dual citizenship allowed	2001	New Citizenship Law was enacted in July 2001 - recognising dual nationality in every situation > Dual nationality is only possible if it is legally accepted by both states concerned.	SOPEMI 2003b: 275	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All	All	N/A	Less restrictive		
6961	Sweden	children of swedish fathers now also swedish by birth	2001	New Citizenship Law was enacted in July 2001  -facilitating the acquisition of Swedish nationality for children of Swedish fathers > According to the principle of the right to citizenship based on parentage (ius sanguinis), if a Swedish woman gives birth to a child, then that child automatically receives Swedish citizenship. If a Swedish man has a child by a foreign woman, then that child, too, is automatically a Swede, providing the child is born inside Sweden or the parents are married.	SOPEMI 2003b: 275	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All	Citizens	N/A	Less restrictive		
6962	Sweden	clarification of naturalisation process	2001	New Citizenship Law was enacted in July 2001 - reiterates the naturalisation process > Any foreigner resident in Sweden for at least five years who is of full legal age, possesses a permanent residence permit and has committed no criminal act can apply for Swedish citizenship. Language skills or special knowledge of the state and social systems are not required. There are even exceptions applicable to the minimum residence period of five years: stateless persons or recognised refugees can apply for Swedish citizenship after four years in Sweden. Danes, Finns, Icelanders and Norwegians can even become Swedes after two years of residence.	Focus Migration 2009: 5	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	No change		
6963	Sweden	Schengen implemented by SE	2001	Schengen Agreement implemented on 25 March 2001 (signed in 1996) - abolishing border controls within EU member states	http://people.exeter.ac.uk/watupman/undergrad/rich/time.htm [accessed on 24.07.2013]	Major change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Border and land control	Free mobility rights/agreements	All	EU citizens	EU member states at that time	Less restrictive		
6964	Sweden	Commission set up to investigate migrants access to power	2001	In 2001, the government set up a commission to investigate migrant communities' access to power and influence.  > In 2003, however, two members of the commission's scientific committee publicly criticized the commission, claiming it discriminated against its non-Swedish members. The government discontinued the commission and set up a new commission to investigate integration in relation to structural discrimination.	MPI 2006	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Institutional capacities	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
6965	Sweden	eased entry for high skilled	2002	Amendment to the Alien Act enters into effect on 1 April 2002 - implementing the proposals of the 2000 report and granting exemptions from labour permits for certain artists and athletes, as well as specialists within international corporations working in Sweden for a maximum of one year.	SOPEMI 2005: 274	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
6966	Sweden	report and debate about free movement of new EU MS after 2004	2003	The Swedish government in February 2002 appointed a special inquiry to study EU enlargement and the free movement of labour - The recommendation of the Commission, in January 2003, was not to implement transitional measures.  > While the ruling Social Democrats favoured a transitional permit regime  a one-year permit after which those with employment would receive the same treatment as old EU citizens  it was unable to achieve a majority in Parliament and Sweden ended up as one of the very few EU members which applied no transitional measures.	OECD 2011: 60	N/A	N/A	Legal entry and stay	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	All migrant workers	EU citizens	Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, Poland, Slovakia and Slovenia	N/A		
6967	Sweden	support to central and eastern european countries to develop modern migration policy	2003	Sweden is providing development co-operation within the area of migration to several countries such as Estonia, Lithuania and Latvia as well as to Russia, Belarus, Ukraine and most of the accession countries in Central and Eastern Europe - This co-operation aims at helping to develop a migration policy that conforms to international standards.	SOPEMI 2003b: 275	N/A	N/A	N/A	Contextual elements	N/A	N/A	N/A	N/A		
6968	Sweden	strenghtening of anti-discrimination law	2003	On 1 July 2003 a new law prohibiting discrimination entered into force - strengthening protection against discrimination with respect to labour market activities, starting and running business operations, carrying on a trade or profession and commercial provision of goods, services or housing.	SOPEMI 2005: 274	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to justice and political rights	All	All	N/A	Less restrictive		
6969	Sweden	EU enlargement no restriction to labour market access	2004	2004 EU enlargement - In May 2004 Sweden was one of only three Member States (along with the UK and Ireland) that allowed citizens of the ten new Eastern European Member States to work without formally requesting a permit.	Focus Migration 2009: 1	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Free mobility rights/agreements	All migrant workers	EU citizens	Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, Poland, Slovakia and Slovenia	Less restrictive		
6970	Sweden	temporary permit for THB victims	2004	On 1 October 2004 the Bill Human trafficking and time-limited residence permit for plaintiffs and witnesses etc. entered into force - granting a time limited residence permit to victims or witnesses, inter alia victims, of trafficking in human beings, if deemed necessary in order to conclude a preliminary investigation or a trial.  > Health care and medical attention, as well as social welfare, will be provided during the stay in Sweden.	EMN 2005: 10	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
6971	Sweden	trafficking in human beings sanctioned	2004	On 1 October 2004 the Bill Human trafficking and time-limited residence permit for plaintiffs and witnesses etc. entered into force - Any person who intentionally helps an alien to unlawfully enter or pass through Sweden, another EU Member State, Norway or Iceland, shall be sentenced for human trafficking to imprisonment for maximum two years.  > If the crime is serious, imprisonment for at least six months and at most six years shall be imposed. The same penal sanctions apply for a person who, for profit, plans or organizes activities designed to enable aliens to travel to Sweden without passports or other permits required for entry into Sweden. Also, any person who, by hiding an alien or by any other such measure, intentionally assists aliens to unlawfully reside in Sweden, another EU Member State, Norway or Iceland, shall be sentenced to imprisonment for maximum two years, or in mitigating circumstances a fine, if the offence was committed for profit (financial gain).	EMN 2005: 10	Mid-level change	National policy	Border and land control	Other sanctions	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
6972	Sweden	reduction of allowances permitted if migrant hinders clarification of identity	2004	Bill Measures to clarify the identity of asylum seekers, etc entered into force on 1 July 2004 -  allowed to partially reduce or entirely remove the daily allowance and housing allowance of an alien over the age of 18 under the Act on the Reception of Asylum Seekers and Others Act (1994) if she or he hinders the investigation of a case concerning a residence permit by not assisting in clarifying his or her identity.	EMN 2005: 10	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Access to social benefits and socio-economic rights	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
6973	Sweden	creation of KAKI commission to investigate admission policy for non EU citizens	2004	The Committee for Migrant Workers KAKI was constituted by government directive in February 2004.  > The centre-right parties, along with the Greens, pushed to create a Parliamentary Committee to examine and propose reform of the policies for admission of non-EU workers, for both short- and long-term labour needs. While the Social Democrats, who were governing in minority, had wished to limit the mandate of the inquiry to whether or not additional labour needs existed, the Committee was charged with recommending a policy to create broader labour migration from outside the EU/EEA.	OECD 2011: 61	Minor change	N/A	Legal entry and stay	Institutional capacities	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Change in restrictiveness cannot be assessed		
6974	Sweden	integration report released suggesting affirmative action to counteract discrimination	2005	The new commission set up in 2004 to investigate integration in relation to structural discrimination released a report in 2005 - suggesting to introduce affirmative action on a broad scale to counteract structural discrimination. > Affirmative action, the commission stated, should not only apply to ethnic or migrant minorities but also to other social categories. The commission even proposed that categories of people in a low socioeconomic position (including native Swedes) should enjoy the benefits of affirmative action.	MPI 2006	N/A	N/A	Integration	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	All	All	N/A	N/A		
6975	Sweden	scope of expulsion of certain asylum seekers extended	2005	As a result of a decision on 7 July 2005, the Government has extended the scope for issuing expulsion orders to apply to asylum seekers who make no attempt to help clarify their identity during the asylum procedure.	EMN 2005: 7	Minor change	National policy	Exit	Expulsion	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
6976	Sweden	programmes to integrate migrants into the labour market	2005	A number of measures have been introduced in 2005 to facilitate the integration of immigrants into the labour market - Among these is a form of job practice called trial opportunity to give (three-month) work experience to persons who lack work experience in Sweden.  > In addition, immigrants with skills from abroad are offered a three-week apprenticeship in their profession to demonstrate their skills on the job, after which they may receive a certificate as proof.	SOPEMI 2006: 216	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Work visa/permit	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
