6997	Sweden	two-year work visa linked to employer demand, no skills selection	2008	2008 Immigration Act entered into force on 15 December 2008 - changing the Swedish immigration policy into a demand-driven system.  > The 2008 law allows employers to recruit for any occupation, and grants renewable permits to all incoming labour migrants: There is no numerical limit, no occupational restriction, no educational minimum. The absence of a cap on entries or sector restrictions, and the nominal nature of the labour market test, make Swedens new policy more open than those of most other OECD countries. The trade unions provide an opinion on whether the job offer conforms to the prevailing Swedish wage and conditions, but they no longer hold a veto over the employer request. The employee must also earn a sufficient income by Swedish standards from the offered employment, with the effective minimum wage is at least SEK 13 000/month (ca. EUR 1 420). This wage is below the lowest collective agreement and would only be accepted if the applicant has a part-time employment.  The only requirement is that the position be listed with the EURES system for 10 days, and provide the same working conditions and salary as for Swedes. The initial permit is valid for up to 2 years, but can be converted into a permanent permit after 4 years. Workers who lose their job while holding a work permit have three months to find a new job; their new employer must be approved through the same process as a recruitment from abroad (i.e. advertisement and verification of contract conditions). If they do not find a job within three months, or if they have no offer of employment when their permit expires, they must leave Sweden.	SOPEMI 2010: 242; OECD 2011: 55	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
6998	Sweden	immediate family reunification for all workers	2008	2008 Immigration Act entered into force on 15 December 2008 - allows labour migrants to be accompanied by their family from the outset	SOPEMI 2010: 242	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
6999	Sweden	work permit granted to family members	2008	2008 Immigration Act entered into force on 15 December 2008 - family members are given free access to the labour market > This is a formalisation of previous policy, under which family members of work-permit holders were generally granted labour market access even if this was not guaranteed by the legislation. However, if the primary permit-holder loses his or her permit through unemployment, so do all dependents. If a dependent is employed, he or she may become the primary permit-holder, subject to minimum income requirements.	OECD 2011: 64	Major change	National policy	Integration	Work visa/permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
