7002	Sweden	students have access to work after six months of studies	2008	2008 Immigration Act entered into force on 15 December 2008 - Students may switch into the work-permit category once they have completed the equivalent of six months university credit.  > There are no special provisions for graduating students, who must comply with the same conditions as any other applicant, although in-country status changes are allowed.	OECD 2011: 65	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Work visa/permit	International students	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7003	Sweden	rejected asylum seekers can apply as labour migrants	2008	2008 Immigration Act entered into force on 15 December 2008 - gives Asylum-seekers whose applications have been refused the opportunity to look for a job in Sweden within a certain time period before having to leave the country and, if they are successful, apply for admission as labour migrants.	Focus Migration 2009: 4	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7004	Sweden	very low requirements for entrepreneurs	2008	2008 Immigration Act entered into force on 15 December 2008 - did not change the policy for self-employment and entrepreneurs with the possibility of permanent residence after two years for those whose businesses support them and their families.  >  Sweden maintains one of the most open policies for those wishing to start a business. Capital requirements and job-creation requirements are modest.	OECD 2011: 70	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to permanent residency	Investors, entrepreneurs and business people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	No change		
7005	Sweden	liberal policy towards iraqi refugees ends	2008	In 2008, due to the large number of immigrants, the Migration Board changed its liberal line - classifying certain parts of Iraq as safe internal flight alternatives and rejecting more Iraqi refugees.  > Background: In 2007, the Migrationsverket registered a total of 36,207 applications for asylum, more than any other EU state. Although Germany has nine times as many inhabitants as Sweden, there were only half the number of asylumseekers. Around 48 per cent of asylum-seekers whose applications were considered by the Migrationsverket during the course of 2007 were granted a residence permit. For comparison, the protection rate in Germany in the year 2007 was 27.5 per cent. The high figures experienced by Sweden can be explained above all by a significant increase in the flow of refugees from Iraq since 2006. Around half of the applications for asylum registered in 2007 came from Iraqis. The authorities granted about 72 per cent of them a residence permit as refugees. As a result, Sweden took in more Iraqi refugees than all the other industrialised countries in Europe and the Americas combined.	Focus Migration 2009: 6	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	Specific nationalities	Iraq	More restrictive		
