7021	Sweden	Extension of the stricter control measures with regard to the issuing of work permits	2013	Extension of the stricter control measures with regard to the issuing of work permits in place since 2011 - employers are required to prove that wages have been paid and to provide evidence concerning salaries, insurances and income taxes paid	EMN factsheet p.1	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Employer liabilities	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
7022	Sweden	Implementation of the EU Blue Card Directive on 1 August 2013	2013	Implementation of the EU Blue Card Directive on 1 August 2013  introduced a new residence and work permit for highly-skilled labour immigrants, called EU Blue Card . To be granted such a permit, a third-country national has to earn a salary which is at least one-and-a-half times as high as the average gross annual wage in Sweden. He or she also has to hold a higher education degree or possess five years of relevant professional experience. Blue Card holders have the right to be joined by family members.	EMN p.19/20	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
7023	Sweden	Establishment of the University and Higher Education Council on 1 January 2013	2013	Establishment of the University and Higher Education Council on 1 January 2013  aims to create a more coherent validation chain and help skilled immigrant to find employment in their respective professional fields	EMN p.22	N/A	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Institutional capacities	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
7024	Sweden	Extension of the Swedish Migration Boards possibilities to assign UAMs	2013	Extension of the Swedish Migration Boards possibilities to assign UAMs seeking asylum to municipalities, even in the absence of a reception agreement between the Board and a municipality	EMN factsheet p.2	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7025	Sweden	Amendment of the Aliens Act, in force since 1 August 2013	2013	Amendment of the Aliens Act, in force since 1 August 2013  provided that any person who employs a third-country national is obliged to notify the Swedish Tax Agency no later than on the 12th day of the month, following the calendar month when the employment started	EMN factsheet p.3	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Employer liabilities	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
7026	Sweden	new unit for migration intelligence within the Swedish Migration Board	2013	Establishment of a new unit for migration intelligence within the Swedish Migration Board in January 2013 - the main task is to estimate, analyse and forecast migration inflows	EMN factsheet p.3	N/A	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Institutional capacities	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
7027	Sweden	presentation of Action Plan to counter child trafficking	2014	Presentation of Action Plan to counter child trafficking - An Action Plan against Trafficking, Exploitation and Sexual Abuse of Children for the period 2014 -2015 was presented to the Parliament in February 2014. The aim of the plan is to ensure that no child becomes a victim of trafficking, exploitation or sexual abuse. The Action Plan also aims to improve the protection of children in particularly vulnerable situations.	EMN 2014: 3	N/A	N/A	Border and land control	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A	To check how that develops	
7028	Sweden	access for refugees and those eligible for subsidiary protection to long-term residence status since 1st May 2014	2014	Access for refugees and those eligible for subsidiary protection to long-term residence status since 1st May 2014 - refugees and persons eligible for subsidiary protection may be granted a long-term resident status in Sweden if they apply for and fulfil the conditions for such status. This also gives them the right to free movement within the European Union.	EMN 2014: 1	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Access to permanent residency	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7029	Sweden	wording changed of Aliens Act to allow for better protection of children	2014	Amendment to Aliens Act of July 2014 - to allow children to be granted a residence permit in cases of particularly distressing circumstances (instead of exceptionally distressing circumstances). The new wording widens the scope of the provision. Protection due to such circumstances is a national form of protection on humanitarian grounds; under this provision, the state of health, the level of integration, and the situation in the country of origin of a child are taken into consideration.	EMN 2014: 1	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7030	Sweden	establishment of Migration Intelligence Unit	2014	Establishment of Migration Intelligence Unit - A Migration Intelligence Unit was established by the Migration Agency. The main task of the new unit is to coordinate and ensure high quality of the Agencys intelligence work. The unit monitors relevant world circumstances and changes, and analyses their possible consequences for migration to Sweden.	EMN 2014: 3	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Institutional capacities	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Change in restrictiveness cannot be assessed		
7031	Sweden	development of national strategic paper on border control	2014	A national strategic paper on border control was developed - within the Central Border Management Division and adopted by the Swedish Police involved in border control issues and the Coast Guard. The plan aims to ensure an effective flow of travellers and to detect and prevent irregular migration.	EMN 2014: 3	N/A	N/A	Border and land control	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
7032	Sweden	control measures to counter abuse of labour migration and exploitation	2014	New control measures to prevent abuse of the labour immigration system of 1st August 2014 - add control measures to curb abuse of the labour immigration system and to prevent exploitation of migrant workers from non-EU/EEA countries. Under the new rules, the Swedish Migration Agency can undertake follow-up checks on employers who have recruited from third-countries and to revoke work permits, whenever the agreed working conditions are not met or the third-country national has not started working. Furthermore, employers have now the obligation to provide written information at the request of the Migration Agency.	SOPEMI 2014: 300; EMN 2014: 2	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Border and land control	Employer liabilities	Low-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
7033	Sweden	new arrivals obliged to accept job offer	2014	Government initiatives to promote integration, changes to the 2010 introduction act - obliges new arrivals with an introduction plan to accept an appropriate job offer	SOPEMI 2014: 300	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Work visa/permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
7034	Sweden	lead time prior to commencing introduction plan reduced	2014	Government initiatives to promote integration - The starting point of the introduction period has been put forward so that it starts when the individual is settled in a municipality, rather than within two months after the individual has been granted a residence permit. The purpose is that individuals with residence permits, who are waiting in reception facilities, should not use up part of their introduction period before they are actually settled.	SOPEMI 2014: 300; EMN Sweden Annual report 2014: 35	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Language, housing and cultural integration programmes	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7035	Sweden	introduction allowance can now be combined with salaried work for 6 months	2014	Government initiatives to promote integration - The rules regarding the introduction allowance were changed in order to encourage newly arrived immigrants to combine introduction activities with employment. An individual covered by the Introduction Act can now have a salaried job as part of the introduction plan and still receive introduction benefits up to six months without incurring income loss	EMN Sweden Annual report 2014: 35	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to social benefits and socio-economic rights	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7036	Sweden	SFI bonus discontinued	2014	SFI bonus discontinued in June 2014 - the Swedish parliament discontinued the language proficiency-training (SFI)-bonus that was introduced in 2009/2010 after evaluation had shown only a limited effect on the performance of SFI students.	SOPEMI 2015: 250	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Language, housing and cultural integration programmes	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Change in restrictiveness cannot be assessed		
7037	Sweden	family members of immigrant business owners allowed to join and receive work permit	2014	It was clarified that immigrant business-owners (self-employed persons) may be accompanied by family members, provided that they can support them. Since 1st July 2014, family members of self-employed persons may also receive a work permit.	EMN 2014: 2	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Work visa/permit	Family members of high-skilled workers, investors or students	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7038	Sweden	UAM's can be assigned to municipalities without a prior agreement	2014	Change in distribution of UAM's - In 2014, due to an increasing caseload regarding unaccompanied minors as well as Dublin cases, the Migration Agency opened new units particularly for Dublin cases and for unaccompanied minors. Up to January 2014, the Swedish Migration Agency was able to assign unaccompanied minors (UAMs) to municipalities only on the basis of voluntary agreements between individual municipalities and the Migration Agency. However, due to the high increase in the number of UAMs, the Migration Agency is now able to assign a UAM to a municipality even when there is no agreement.	EMN 2014: 1-2	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Border and land control	Institutional capacities	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
7039	Sweden	new stay visas for those who graduated Swedish university	2014	New rules introduced to remove obstacles to circular migration and enhance the positive effects of migration on development of July 2014 - international students who graduated from a Swedish university or college may remain for up to six months to look for work or set up their own business.	SOPEMI 2015: 250	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Work visa/permit	International students	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7040	Sweden	access to permanent residency for doctoral students	2014	New rules introduced to remove obstacles to circular migration and enhance the positive effects of migration on development of July 2014 - International doctoral students qualify for permanent residence in Sweden, provided they have held a study permit in Sweden for four out of the prior seven years.	SOPEMI 2015: 250	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Access to permanent residency	International students	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7041	Sweden	migrants with a permanent residence able to keep visa for 2 years after moving out of Sweden	2014	New rules introduced to remove obstacles to circular migration and enhance the positive effects of migration on development of July 2014 - the possibility for third-country nationals (TCNs) with a permanent resident permit in Sweden, to keep the permit for two years after moving out from Sweden (provided TCNs inform the authorities of their willingness to keep the permit)	EMN 2014: 2	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Access to permanent residency	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7042	Sweden	labour migrants and doctoral students allowed to interrupt residency while retaining right to permanent residence permit	2014	New rules introduced to remove obstacles to circular migration and enhance the positive effects of migration on development of July 2014 - labour migrants and doctoral students may now interrupt their residency in Sweden for shorter or longer periods of time while retaining their right to be granted a permanent residence permit. Such permits can be now granted if a TCN has had a residence permit for a total of four years in the last seven years	EMN 2014: 2	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to permanent residency	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7043	Sweden	prolonged temporary work visas for labour migrants	2014	New rules introduced to remove obstacles to circular migration and enhance the positive effects of migration on development of July 2014 - labour migrants have now the possibility to be granted a temporary work permit for a total time of six years (previously four years);	EMN 2014: 2	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7044	Sweden	eased conditions for work permits for rejected asylum seekers	2014	New rules introduced to remove obstacles to circular migration and enhance the positive effects of migration on development of July 2014 - a rejected asylum seeker can apply for a residence permit for work purposes, if the person has been working in Sweden for at least four months (previously six months) before rejection, on the condition that the employer agrees to continued employment.	EMN 2014: 2	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7045	Sweden	applications for residence permits made by parents of children can be done from inside of Sweden	2014	Amendment to Aliens Act of August 2014 - aims at guaranteeing the best interest of the child and clarifies the Swedish rules applicable to parents that are the caregivers of a child with legal residence status in Sweden and that live together with the child. As a result, a parent can now lodge an application for a residence permit while in Sweden, if there is a strong relationship with the child and it is unreasonable to demand that the parent leaves Sweden before applying. (Normally, residence permits have to be applied for from abroad.)	EMN 2014: 2	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7046	Sweden	Sweden joins EUROSUR	2014	Sweden joins EUROSUR on 1st December 2014 - Sweden joined the European Border Surveillance System (Eurosur) and a National Coordination Centre has also been established.	EMN 2014: 3	Minor change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Border and land control	Institutional capacities	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
7047	Sweden	Introduction Act of 2010 changes	2014	Introduction Act of 2010 changes included: The target group for introduction activities has been widened to cover more family members of refugees with a good start in Sweden. The time limit within which a family member needs to apply for a residence permit to be covered by the Introduction Act has also been extended from two to six years.	EMN 2014 p.35	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members of irregular migrants or refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7048	Sweden	EU Visa Code and the Visa Information System (VIS)	2014	Sweden implements the EU Visa Code and the Visa Information System (VIS) where the VIS has been rolled out. The VIS allows Schengen States to exchange visa data. It consists of a central IT system and of a communication infrastructure that links this central system to national systems.	EMN 2014 p.26	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
7049	Sweden	Action Plan against Trafficking, Exploitation and Sexual Abuse of Children	2014	Action Plan against Trafficking, Exploitation and Sexual Abuse of Children for the period 2014-2015 was presented to the Parliament in February 2014. The aim of the plan is to ensure that no child becomes a victim of trafficking, exploitation or sexual abuse. The Action Plan also aims to improve the protection of children in particularly vulnerable situations	EMN 2014 p.39	N/A	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
7050	Sweden	introduction guide mission discontinued	2015	Introduction guide mission discontinued in February 2015 - the Public Employment Service decided to discontinue the introduction guide mission (Etableringslots) for newly arrived migrants. The programme was cancelled after an increasing number of complaints about inefficiencies, poor quality of assistance and abuse. A review of the introduction guide mission by The National Audit Office pointed to similar problems	SOPEMI 2015: 250	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Language, housing and cultural integration programmes	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
7051	Sweden	introduction of 'supported accomodation' for UAMs	2015	Introduction of 'supported accomodation' for UAMs - The government also adopted a number of measures and initiatives to support municipalities in their work of supporting and integrating unaccompanied minors. Among other measures, it introduced a new form of accommodation for children and young people, called supported accommodation which can be provided from 1st January 2016. The level of supervision and care provided in supported accommodation is somewhat lower than in other types of facilities for UAMs.	EMN 2015: 2	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Border and land control	Institutional capacities	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
7052	Sweden	new standards in relation to UAM	2015	the Migration Agency developed new standards in relation to UAM. A new standard on registration of age at the time of application foresees that the age that a child states should generally be registered in the system. However, if it is obvious that the person is not a child, the Agency can register the person as above 18 years. Another standard, on medical age assessment, means that the Migration Agency no longer initiates any medical age assessments, but is obliged to inform the UAM about the option to undergo a medical age assessment and hand it in to the Migration Agency as evidence to support the stated age.	EMN 2015 factsheet p.2	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
7053	Sweden	symbolic value of Swedish citizenship increased	2015	Amendment to citizenship law entered into force in April 2015 - increases the symbolic value of Swedish citizenship. The Citizenship Act now includes a preamble stating that Swedish citizenship stands for affinity with Sweden and links all citizens. It also states that Swedish citizenship consists of rights and responsibilities. In addition, all Swedish municipalities are now obliged to hold annual citizenship ceremonies for new citizens in order to celebrate their new citizenship. This change to the nationality law was intended to emphasize the symbolic value of becoming a Swedish citizen.	SOPEMI 2015: 250; https://www.bpb.de/gesellschaft/migration/laenderprofile/58636/citizenship [accessed on 23.02.2021]	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
7054	Sweden	eased access to citizenship for young people	2015	Amendment to citizenship law entered into force in April 2015 - makes it easier for children and young persons to apply for Swedish citizenship. Children of foreign citizens can now become Swedish citizens if they are under 18 years old and have resided in Sweden for at least three years with a permanent residence permit. Young people between 18 and 21 years can acquire Swedish citizenship if they have resided in Sweden with permanent residence since the age of 13.	SOPEMI 2015: 250; https://www.bpb.de/gesellschaft/migration/laenderprofile/58636/citizenship [accessed on 23.02.2021]	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Integration	Access to citizenship	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7055	Sweden	introduction plan for parents on part-time parental leave prolonged	2015	Introduction plan for parents prolonged - The Swedish government has prolonged the introduction plan for parents on part-time parental leave in order to make it easier for them to combine parenthood with participation in introduction activities.	SOPEMI 2015: 250	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Integration	Language, housing and cultural integration programmes	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7056	Sweden	national committee on labour migration appointed	2015	National committee on labour migration appointed in July 2015 - a national committee on labour migration was appointed to survey the extent of abuse and exploitation of labour migrants in Sweden, and to propose measures to counteract such exploitation.	SOPEMI 2016: 304	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Institutional capacities	Low-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7057	Sweden	introduction of new method to process asylum cases	2015	Changes to asylum procedure of 2015 - introduces a new method to process asylum cases. At the time of the application, each case will be categorized into one of six different tracks. The aim of the categorization is to be able to adjust the handling of an asylum application according to the needs of the particular case.	EMN 2015: 1	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Institutional capacities	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
7058	Sweden	speedier asylum procedure for Syrians and Eritreans	2015	Changes to asylum procedure of 2015 - introduction of temporary simplified operation modes during the last quarter of 2015, primarily to Syrians, stateless persons from Syria and Eritreans. This meant that no initial interviews were held with adult asylum seekers or families. However, the asylum seekers had to leave their fingerprints and had their photographs taken. Moreover, appointments for asylum interviews were not scheduled at the time of registration but at a later stage. The aim of these measures was to speed up the registration of asylum applicants and to quickly include them into the reception system.	EMN 2015: 1	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	Specific nationalities	Syria and Eritrea	Less restrictive		
7059	Sweden	Fast-tracks refugees into the labour market for shortage occupations	2015	Amendments to Introduction Act - The aim is to create more opportunities in terms of access to work for recognized refugees. For instance, following talks with social partners, the Public Employment Service and other agencies, fast tracks into the labour market were opened for shortage professions such as: cooks, butchers, teachers and health care sector workers such as doctors, nurses and dentists. A new Fast Track initiative began operating in early 2016 to speed up the entry of skilled immigrants into shortage occupations. The sector-specific initiatives begin by mapping, validating and bridging the skills of programme participants in their mother tongue, offering language tuition alongside these activities. Swedish language skills will not be required prior to the commencement of validation and bridging efforts.	EMN 2015: 2-3, SOPEMI 2016: 304; EMN Sweden Annual Report 2015: 31; https://www.eurofound.europa.eu/publications/article/2016/sweden-fast-track-initiative-to-help-asylum-seekers-enter-labour-market [accessed 22.02.2021]	Mid-level change	National policy	Integration	Work visa/permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7060	Sweden	temporary border and ID controls introduced	2015	Temporary border and ID controls introduced in November 2015 - This decision was made due to the risk for public order and internal security posed by the very high inflow of irregular migrants seeking asylum experienced during the year, especially during the months of October and November. However, asylum seekers were allowed to apply for international protection at the border. In addition, new legislation (effective since 4 January 2016) was prepared, according to which identity controls are carried out of all persons crossing the Swedish border by bus, train or boat. This means that persons without any ID-documents have not been able to travel to Sweden by such means of transport since early January 2016.	SOPEMI 2017: 234; EMN 2015: 1	Major change	National policy	Border and land control	Surveillance technology/control powers	All	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
7061	Sweden	actions against social dumping	2015	In the framework of actions against social dumping, the Swedish Government has appointed a Committee on labour migration. The committee will investigate the extent of exploitation of labour migrants in Sweden and suggest measures to counteract such phenomenon.	EMN 2015 factsheet p. 2	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Institutional capacities	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
7062	Sweden	revised Asylum Procedures Directive implemented	2016	Revised Asylum Procedures Directive implemented on 1st January 2016 - the related legal changes to the Swedish Aliens Act included more specific rules regarding manifestly unfounded asylum applications and regarding the right to remain until a court has ruled on inhibition during the appeal of clearly unfounded decisions (and of subsequent applications)	EMN 2016: 1	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
7063	Sweden	more rights for UAMs	2016	Revised Asylum Procedures Directive implemented on 1st January 2016 - the related legal changes to the Swedish Aliens Act included more specific rules providing that unaccompanied minors (UAMs) always have a right to legal representation in the asylum procedure.	EMN 2016: 1	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Access to justice and political rights	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7064	Sweden	creation of introduction package to promote integration	2016	The government has launched an introduction package to speed up the labour market integration of newly arrived immigrants - This initiative aims at accelerating the transition to gainful employment through language courses, training, skills validation and accommodation; increasing the support to municipalities to provide newly arrived children and young people a good education in preschools and schools; and strengthening the reception and integration of refugees all over the country. It also prescribes regulations on the organisational form of introductory classes and on the number of teaching hours for newly arrived students. The overall aim is to improve the quality of education for newly arrived students The government also proposed to increase the flat-rate reimbursement to municipalities for schooling of asylum-seeking minors by 50%.	SOPEMI 2016: 304, EMN 2016: 2	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Language, housing and cultural integration programmes	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
7065	Sweden	solidarity-based refugee reception system enforced	2016	Act for an effective and solidarity-based refugee reception system entered into force on 1st March 2016 - It foresees that all municipalities within Sweden can be required to receive newly-arrived refugees and other beneficiaries of protection, as well as their family members, for settlement and integration.	EMN 2016: 1	Major change	National policy	Border and land control	Institutional capacities	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
7066	Sweden	Action Plan for 2016-2018 to protect children from human trafficking, exploitation and sexual abuse	2016	Action Plan for 2016-2018 to protect children from human trafficking, exploitation and sexual abuse of May 2016 - This matches the goals of the 2030 United Nations Agenda for Sustainable Development, which foresees the elimination of abuse, exploitation, human trafficking and all forms of violence or torture against children, and the abolition of all forms of violence against women and girls in public and private spheres	EMN 2016: 3	N/A	N/A	Legal entry and stay	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
7067	Sweden	suspension of right to accomodation and daily allowance for those ordered to leave the country	2016	Suspension of right to accomodation and daily allowance for those ordered to leave the country of 2016 - Return activities are being stepped up and since June 2016 asylum seekers who have received a deportation order no longer have the right to accommodation or a daily allowance from the Swedish Migration Agency. This does not apply to adults living with their children.	SOPEMI 2017: 234; EMN 2016: 1	Mid-level change	National policy	Exit	Access to social benefits and socio-economic rights	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
7068	Sweden	Sweden joins EURLO project to increase returns of rejected asylum seekers	2016	The Swedish Migration Agency joined the EURLO project (EU Return Liaison Officers) in 2016 - The aim is to reinforce and facilitate returns and to increase the number of returns amongst difficult cases, particularly to Morocco and Afghanistan, as well as to other third countries where other Member States have deployed EURLO officers.	EMN 2016: 3	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Exit	Institutional capacities	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	Specific nationalities	Morocco, Afghanistan, and other countries where EURLO officers are deployed	More restrictive		
7069	Sweden	Sweden joins ERIN to step up reintegration support for rejected asylum seekers	2016	The Swedish Migration Agency joined the European Reintegration Network (ERIN) as a privileged partner in June 2016 - As a result, the Migration Agency will provide a broad range of reintegration measures to people returning to Afghanistan, Nigeria, Pakistan, Iraq, Iran, Russia, Morocco and Somalia. Throughout 2017, Sweden anticipates to increase the number of countries in which reintegration support for rejected asylum seekers who have returned is provided.	EMN 2016: 3	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Exit	Reintegration/return programmes	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	Specific nationalities	Afghanistan, Nigeria, Pakistan, Iraq, Iran, Russia, Morocco and Somalia	Less restrictive		
7070	Sweden	EU Council Decision on resettlement of refugees	2016	EU Council Decision on the obligations to relocation of 9th June 2016 - the Council of the EU decided that the obligations of Sweden shall be suspended until 16th June 2017. Sweden did therefore not receive any asylum seekers relocated from Italy or Greece in 2016. However, Sweden continued its resettlement efforts, finalising the resettlement of the 491 individuals pledged in the framework of a Council decision.	EMN 2016: 1	Fine-tuning change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Resettlement programmes	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7071	Sweden	temporary halt on permanent residence permits given out to refugees	2016	Temporary law in response to large numbers of asylum seekers arriving in 2016 - A temporary law, to last three years, was introduced in late July 2016 to limit access by quota refugees to permanent resident permits. Refugees are now granted a 3-year temporary permit; those with subsidiary protection status are granted a one year residence permit.	SOPEMI 2017: 234	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to permanent residency	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
7072	Sweden	restricted access to family unification for refugees and subsidiary protection status	2016	Temporary law in response to large numbers of asylum seekers arriving in 2016 - It will restrict the access to family reunification for third-country nationals granted international protection. Those granted subsidiary protection will not have a right to family reunification if their asylum application was submitted after the 24th November 2015. Refugees will still have access to family reunification with their spouse, cohabitant or minor children.	EMN 2015: 2	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members of irregular migrants or refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
7073	Sweden	higher maintainance requirements for family reunification	2016	Temporary law in response to large numbers of asylum seekers arriving in 2016 - introduces tougher maintenance requirements for Swedish nationals and EU citizens that want to be joined by family members from third countries.	EMN 2015: 2	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
7074	Sweden	working holiday agreement with Chile	2016	Working Holiday Agreement with Chile > promote cultural exchange and mobility among youth aged 18-30 by enabling them to travel for a year and engage in temporary employment to supplement their travel funds.	SOPEMI 2018: 278	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Low-skilled workers	Specific nationalities	Chile	Less restrictive		
7075	Sweden	bilateral Memorandum of Understanding with Afghanistan on cooperation in the field of migration	2016	Sweden signed a bilateral Memorandum of Understanding with Afghanistan on cooperation in the field of migration of 5th October 2016 - It aims at facilitating the return of Afghans who do not have a right to stay in Sweden and makes it possible for Sweden to carry out forced as well as voluntary returns to Afghanistan.	EMN 2016: 3	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Exit	Reintegration/return programmes	Irregular migrants	Specific nationalities	Afghanistan	More restrictive		
7076	Sweden	extension of border and ID controls	2016	Extension of the temporary border and ID controls introduced in November 2015 and a new legislation in force since 4th January 2016 - requires identity controls to be performed on all persons crossing the Swedish border by bus, train or boat.	SOPEMI 2017: 234	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Border and land control	Surveillance technology/control powers	All	All foreign nationalities	N/A	No change		
7077	Sweden	AMs will be appointed a legal counsel	2016	all UAMs will be appointed a legal counsel in the first days of their asylum process. The legal counsels are instructed to meet the minors before further steps are taken in the asylum process, in the best interest of the minors.	EMN 2016 factsheet p.2	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Access to justice and political rights	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7078	Sweden	internal border controls extended, but suspension of ID checks	2017	Adaptations made to internal border controls of May 2017 - the Swedish Government decided to prolong the Swedish Polices internal border controls, which have been in force since November 2015, but decided to end ID checks across the Öresund Strait	SOPEMI 2018: 278	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Border and land control	Surveillance technology/control powers	All	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7079	Sweden	changes to age determination of unaccompanied minors	2017	Changes to age determination for unaccompanied minors of May 2017- the Migration Agency is able to assess the age of a minor at the outset of the asylum procedure instead of, as previously, only in connection with the final decision. Furthermore, since March 2017 asylum seeking minors will be offered the possibility to undergo a voluntary medical age assessment in support of their age determination decision.	SOPEMI 2018: 278	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
7080	Sweden	refugees on temporary permit allowed access to health care and welfare benefits	2017	Changes to temporary law in response to large numbers of asylum seekers arriving in 2016 - new legislation introduced in August 2017 ensures that these individuals are able to maintain health care and welfare benefits if they apply for an extension before their temporary permit expires.	SOPEMI 2018: 278	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Integration	Access to social benefits and socio-economic rights	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7081	Sweden	working holiday agreement with Hong Kong, China and with Argentina	2017	Working Holiday Agreement with Hong Kong and Argentina > promote cultural exchange and mobility among youth aged 18-30 by enabling them to travel for a year and engage in temporary employment to supplement their travel funds.	SOPEMI 2018: 278	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Low-skilled workers	Specific nationalities	Hong Kong and Argentina	Less restrictive		
7082	Sweden	prolongation of border controls	2017	Prolongation of internal border controls - the internal border controls, which have been in force since 2015, were once again prolonged.	SOPEMI 2019: 278	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Border and land control	Surveillance technology/control powers	All	All foreign nationalities	N/A	No change		
7083	Sweden	increased resettlement places	2017	Resettlement program increased - Swedish resettlement program extended from 1900 places in 2016 to 3400	EMN 2017: 1	Fine-tuning change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Resettlement programmes	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7084	Sweden	cooperation improved between authorites responsible for returns	2017	Improved cooperation between authorities in charge of returns of November 2017 - legislative and regulatory changes entered into force that will streamline co-operation between the authorities responsible for voluntary return (the Swedish Migration Agency) and those in charge of forced return (the Police Authorities) and clarify their respective tasks and responsibilities.	SOPEMI 2019: 278	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Exit	Institutional capacities	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
7085	Sweden	residence permit for work purposes no longer revoked in the case of deviations from legal requirements	2017	Amendment to the rules on labour migration from 1 December 2017 - gave the possibility to the Swedish Migration Agency to not revoke a residence permit for work purposes in cases where the employer corrected earlier deviations from the legal requirements (eg in terms of salary or insurance of employees). According to the Swedish Aliens Act, a residence permit for work purposes can be revoked if the requirements for such a permit have not been fulfilled	EMN 2017: 2	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Employer liabilities	Low-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7086	Sweden	increased funds for municipalities and social partners for receiving asylum seekers	2017	Increased funds made available to municipalities and social partners to receive asylum seekers - Sweden increased funding to municipalities and county councils receiving the largest numbers of asylum seekers and newly arrived migrants. It also increased resources to social partners' work on fast tracks for newly arrived refugees, with education, training or work experience in areas for which there is demand for labour in Sweden.	SOPEMI 2019: 278	Minor change	National policy	Border and land control	Institutional capacities	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7087	Sweden	appeals, new legislative amendments entered into force on 1 January 2017	2017	To improve the migration courts ability to deal with a rising caseload, new legislative amendments entered into force on 1 January 2017. The amendments have made it possible for the migration courts to hand open appeal cases over to other administrative courts.	EMN 2017 report p. 33-34	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Access to justice and political rights	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7088	Sweden	introduced a new support function for the handling of LGBTI-cases.	2017	September 2017, the Migration Agency introduced a new support function for the handling of LGBTI-cases. The function consists of an operational coordinator responsible of coordinating the work of LGBTI-specialists within the Agency. Representatives from the Agencys Quality Department, the Legal Department, the Department for Country of origin information and Human Resources are also part of this new function. Its purpose is to secure the quality and efficiency of the management and decision-making in LGBTI-cases through coordination and support.	EMN 2017 report p.36	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7089	Sweden	National Council of Swedish Youth Organisations coordinated and educated youth organizations	2017	During 2017, the National Council of Swedish Youth Organisations coordinated and educated youth organizations and provided contacts between organizations with regard to activities directed towards asylum seekers and young newly arrived im-migrants. The aim is to promote meeting places, networks and mentorship between newly arrived youths and other youths	EMN 2017 report p. 43	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Access to social benefits and socio-economic rights	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7090	Sweden	grants young people (aged 17 to 24), who study at upper secondary level (gymnasium), a right to a residence permit	2017	June 2017, new legislation entered into force that grants young people (aged 17 to 24), who study at upper secondary level (gymnasium), a right to a residence permit. The legislation covers individuals who were at some point granted a temporary residence permit after an asylum application, whether or not the grounds for that permit have remained valid. The respective individuals can be granted a permit with a duration of 13 months to 4 years at a time, and they can apply for an extension if they have reasons for not finishing their upper secondary level education according to their individual study plan. The aim of this legal amendment was to make it possible for young asylum seekers, including young people that were considered unaccompanied minors when they came to Sweden, to finalise an education in Sweden even in the event of their temporary asylum-related residence permit expiring and not being extended.	EMN 2017 report p.32	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7091	Sweden	amendments were been made to the Aliens Act,	2017	In 2017, amendments were been made to the Aliens Act, entailing that the Swedish Migration Agency now assesses an aliens age earlier in the asylum process. The law now states that a temporary age assessment should be carried out immediately, and that a temporary (appealable) decision regarding the age of an asylum applicant should be taken in the initial phase of the asylum procedure. There are various methods  both medical and non-medical  that can be used to assess the age of a young applicant	EMN 2017 report p.48	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
7092	Sweden	time limit for the temporary placement of a detainee	2017	In 2017, the time limit for the temporary placement of a detainee in a correctional facility, a remand prison or a police custody (while arrangements are made for his or her transportation to one of the Migration Agencys detention centres), has been ex-plicitly codified, and extended to three days. Before this change, the authorities often found it difficult to carry out transports of detainees within the given (shorter) time frames, due to e.g., geographic and practical factors	EMN 2017 report p.51-52	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Detention	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
7093	Sweden	new authority has been set up in Sweden, the Delegation against segregation (Delmos)	2018	As of 1 January 2018, a new authority has been set up in Sweden, the Delegation against segregation (Delmos). The Authority will work to improve the situation in areas with socioeconomic challenges and counter structural causes of segregation. Delmos shall promote increased cooperation between authorities, county councils, municipalities, civil society organizations, industry, researchers and other relevant actors; contribute to the exchange of knowledge and experience between relevant actors and support them in conducting a strategic and knowledge-based work; and follow research and contribute to knowledge-development on segregation issues. The Authority will also analyse the underlying causes of segregation and disseminate knowledge about methods and actions that can help reduce and counter segregation. Furthermore, it shall assist the Government with analyses, investigations and follow-ups on segregation issues, and distribute state grants.	EMN 2017 report p. 43	N/A	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Institutional capacities	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
7094	Sweden	introduction of referral to labour market policy programme	2018	The 2010 introduction law was repealed in 2017 by the Law on Newly Arrived Immigrants, which entered into effect on 1 January 2018 - the regulatory change aligns support provided to newcomers to that provided to Swedish jobseekers. As a result, the right to an introduction plan was removed and replaced with a referral to a labour market policy programme	EMN 2017: 3	Major change	National policy	Integration	Access to social benefits and socio-economic rights	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
7095	Sweden	new regulatory framework for Introduction programme obliging education and training	2018	The 2010 introduction law was repealed in 2017 by the Law on Newly Arrived Immigrants, which entered into effect on 1 January 2018 - It aims to enhance results through reduced administration and increased flexibility in the system. As part of the new framework, an education and training obligation for newly arrived immigrants was introduced. All newly arrived immigrants, involved in the Public Employment Services introduction measures and who are considered in need of education and training to find work, may be instructed to apply for and undertake such education and training.	SOPEMI 2019: 278	Major change	National policy	Integration	Language, housing and cultural integration programmes	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
7096	Sweden	increased power for police to conduct workplace inspections	2018	Legislative change in July 2018 increased the power of the Police Authorities to conduct workplace inspections based on risk assessments to ensure that employers are not hiring individuals who do not have the right to stay in Sweden.	SOPEMI 2019: 278	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Border and land control	Employer liabilities	Low-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
7097	Sweden	regularise situation of former UAMs	2018	New temporary legislative amendment of July 2018 - aimed to regularise the legal situation of several thousand young unaccompanied migrants who had been rejected as asylum seekers in Sweden following long waiting times	EMN 2018: 1	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Regularisation	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7098	Sweden	Prolongation of internal border controls	2018	Prolongation of internal border controls - the internal border controls, which have been in force since 2015, were once again prolonged.	SOPEMI 2020: 238	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Border and land control	Surveillance technology/control powers	All	All foreign nationalities	N/A	No change		
7099	Sweden	young people allowed to stay in order to finish upper secondary school	2018	Amendments to temporary act previously restricting the possibility of being granted a residence permit for protection purposes and family reunification of June 2018 -  amendments were made to ensure that, under certain conditions, those aged between 18 and 25 are able to extend their temporary residence permit for the duration of their upper secondary school studies. The legislation covers those (in most cases former unaccompanied minor asylum seekers) who at some point had been granted a temporary residence permit after an asylum application, whether or not the grounds for that permit remained valid	SOPEMI 2018: 278; EMN 2017: 2	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7100	Sweden	resettlement program increased	2018	Resettlement program increased - Swedish resettlement program extended to 5000 places	EMN 2018: 2	Fine-tuning change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Resettlement programmes	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7101	Sweden	teachers encouraged to teach Swedish language courses	2018	Initiatives to increase no. of Swedish language teachers - Sweden has launched several initiatives to increase the number of teachers of the Swedish language for immigrants. For example, teachers may receive 80 per cent of their salary during a leave of absence for studies as they develop skills in the subject of teaching Swedish as a second language.	SOPEMI 2019: 278	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Language, housing and cultural integration programmes	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
7102	Sweden	working holiday agreement with Uruguay	2018	Working Holiday Agreement with Uruguay > promote cultural exchange and mobility among youth aged 18-30 by enabling them to travel for a year and engage in temporary employment to supplement their travel funds.	SOPEMI 2019: 278	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Low-skilled workers	Specific nationalities	Uruguay	Less restrictive		
7103	Sweden	system of subsidised employment was reformed,	2018	The system of subsidised employment was reformed, and now includes the employment support measures introductory jobs and extra jobs for those with the greatest need, in particular longterm unemployed and newlyarrived immigrants. The measures were implemented together with employers in the public, municipal and nonprofit sectors, with wage subsidies of up to 100 % in some cases for employers offering additional jobs	EMN 2018 report p. 45	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7104	Sweden	budget bill for 2018, several new measures for labour market integration of foreign-born women introduced	2018	In the budget bill for 2018, several new measures for labour market integration of foreign-born women were introduced and others received additional funding. These measures included funding to municipalities to offer newly arrived migrants on parental leave language and introduction courses with child care; increased funding to Swedish from day 1, an initiative aimed at the Study associations to offer guidance about the Swedish labour market to asylum seeking women as well as motivational activities for employment to both asylum seekers and newly arrived immigrants.	EMN 2018 report p.46	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7105	Sweden	ew Swedish Gender Equality Agency	2018	Since 1 January 2018, the responsibility to coordinate the work of Swedish authorities against prostitution and trafficking in human beings for sexual and other purposes was permanently transferred to the new Swedish Gender Equality Agency	EMN 2018 report p.50-51	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Institutional capacities	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
7106	Sweden	Swedish Migration Agency also became a partner in the European Return and Reintegration Network (ERRIN).	2018	The Swedish Migration Agency also became a partner in the European Return and Reintegration Network (ERRIN). The programme, which is funded by AMIF until July 2020, aims to strengthen, facilitate and streamline the return process in the EU through common initiatives, and to promote a durable and efficient reintegration in countries outside the EU.	EMN 2018 report p.52	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Exit	Reintegration/return programmes	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
7107	Sweden	revised return process for handling individual cases	2019	Implementation of revised return process of January 2019 - to improve efficiency in the handling of return cases. The new process is intended to be more flexible, with greater discretion given to case officers to undertake the correct measures in light of eacht individual case	EMN 2019: 3	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Exit	Institutional capacities	Irregular migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
7108	Sweden	working holiday agreement with Japan	2019	Working Holiday Agreement with Japan > promote cultural exchange and mobility among youth aged 18-30 by enabling them to travel for a year and engage in temporary employment to supplement their travel funds.	EMN 2019: 1	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Low-skilled workers	Specific nationalities	Japan	Less restrictive		
7109	Sweden	temporary cap on permanent residence permits for refugees prolonged	2019	The temporary law passed in July 2016 was prolonged - limiting access by quota refugees to permanent resident permits.	SOPEMI 2020: 238	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Integration	Access to permanent residency	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	No change		
7110	Sweden	restricted access to family unification for refugees and subsidiary protection status prolonged	2019	The temporary law passed in July 2016 was prolonged - restricting the access to family reunification for third-country nationals granted international protection.	SOPEMI 2020: 238	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members of irregular migrants or refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	No change		
7111	Sweden	higher maintainance requirements for family reunification prolonged	2019	The temporary law passed in July 2016 was prolonged - keeping tougher maintenance requirements for Swedish nationals and EU citizens that want to be joined by family members from third countries.	SOPEMI 2020: 238	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	No change		
7112	Sweden	appointent of cross-party commission to examine future Swedish migration policy design	2019	Appointment of cross-party commission of inquiry to examine Sweden's future migration policy - the inquiry will consider the design of migration policy, with the aim of establishing a system that is sustainable in the long-term. The government stated that in a changing world, migration policy should reduce the need for temporary solutions and ensure a permanent system that enjoys broad support in the Swedish Riksdag. Any migration policy must be humane, legally secure and effective	EMN 2019: 1	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Institutional capacities	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Change in restrictiveness cannot be assessed		
7113	Sweden	residence permits for those born in Sweden but stateless since birth	2019	Adoption of provision to allow permanent residence permit to be issued to some persons born in Sweden who have been stateless since birth	EMN 2019: 2	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Integration	Access to permanent residency	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7114	Sweden	Prolongation of internal border controls	2019	Prolongation of internal border controls - the internal border controls, which have been in force since 2015, were once again prolonged.	SOPEMI 2020: 238	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Border and land control	Surveillance technology/control powers	All	All foreign nationalities	N/A	No change		
7115	Sweden	restriction of daily allowance for asylum seekers choosing to live in socio-economically disadvantaged areas	2020	An amendment to restrict daily allowances for asylum seekers choosing to live in areas with socio-economic challenges entered into force in January 2020 - The Swedish Migration Agency started to list those areas in July 2020.	SOPEMI 2020: 238	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Access to social benefits and socio-economic rights	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
7116	Sweden	extra funding for language training for parents	2020	Funding for language training for parents - The government has allocated new funding for Swedish language training for immigrant parents who are away from the labour market taking care of children.	SOPEMI 2020: 238	Fine-tuning change	National policy	Integration	Language, housing and cultural integration programmes	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7117	Sweden	proposal to change conditions for acquiring citizenship	2020	The government decided that they want to make the acquisition of Swedish citizenship will be conditional on passing a Swedish language test, as well as a test on basic knowledge of Swedish society - Civic orientation courses are organised by the municipalities and now have a minimum duration of 100 hours, instead of 60 hours previously. This is currently only a proposal.	SOPEMI 2020: 238	N/A	N/A	Integration	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
7118	Sweden	new residence permits for students following EU Directive	2020	New law for students, researchers and au-pairs following transposition of EU-Directive -  New rules on residence permits for research and higher education studies, as well as for trainees and au pairs, now apply following the transposition of an EU Directive. Residence permits should be granted to students for at least one year, or for the time of conducting studies (renewable, with possibility of extending their stay to look for a job or set up a business).	SOPEMI 2020: 238	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	International students	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7119	Sweden	entry ban following COVID-19 measures	2020	Measures against the spread of COVID-19 - Due to the pandemic, the Swedish Government decided in mid-March to stop temporarily non-essential travel to Sweden from countries outside the EEA and Switzerland. Due to the entry ban, the Migration Agency decided that visa applications should, as a rule, be rejected.	SOPEMI 2020: 238	Major change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Travel visa/permit	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
7120	Sweden	exemptions for residents and certain professions	2020	Measures against the spread of COVID-19 - Exemptions from the entry ban include Swedish citizens, foreigners with a residence permit returning to their homes and certain health care professionals and seasonal workers.	SOPEMI 2020: 238	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Low-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
7121	Sweden	resettlement of refugees suspended following COVID-19 measures	2020	Measures against the spread of COVID-19 - The Migration Agency also suspended resettlement of refugees during the spring.	SOPEMI 2020: 238	Fine-tuning change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Resettlement programmes	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
7122	Sweden	Sweden as emigration country	1900s	For a long time, Sweden was primarily an emigration country - Between 1850 and 1930, about 1.5 million people left Sweden.	Brochmann and Hagelund 2012: 33	N/A	N/A	Exit	Contextual elements	All migrants	Citizens	N/A	N/A		
7123	Sweden	no guest worker policy, but recruitment with direct integration	1960s	In the 1960s and early 1970s, labour migrants were actively recruited. But unlike countries such as Germany and the Netherlands, the Swedish government did not pursue a guest worker policy, but rather assumed from the outset that the immigrant workers would stay and become integrated. Sometimes industry provided them with accommodation and the employee organisations helped with integration. In school, children from foreign families had the right to be taught in their mother tongue for a certain number of hours a week. Municipal libraries were also given the financial means to purchase lexicons, newspapers and books in the major immigrant languages.	Focus Migration 2009: 2; MPI 2006	N/A	N/A	Integration	Language, housing and cultural integration programmes	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
7124	Sweden	Migration Intelligence Unit		A Migration Intelligence Unit was established by the Migration Agency. The main task of the new unit is to coordinate and ensure high quality of the Agencys intelligence work. The unit monitors relevant world circumstances and changes, and analyses their possible consequences for migration to Sweden.	EMN 2014 factsheet p. 3	N/A	National policy	Border and land control	Institutional capacities	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
