7255	Switzerland	refugees from Balkans	1990	Between 1990 and 2002, Switzerland received a total of 146,587 asylum applications from the war-torn Balkans - About 10,000 people were granted asylum, and 62,000 received temporary or subsidiary protection over the course of several years, according to the Swiss Federal Office for Migration.  > In the 1990s, war in the former Yugoslavia prompted a massive influx of asylum seekers from Bosnia and Kosovo, many of whom had family ties in Switzerland because of labor migration since the 1960s.	MPI 2005	N/A	N/A	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	Specific nationalities	Balkans	N/A		
7256	Switzerland	safe country of origin rule introduced	1990	Decision of 22 June 1990 - introduces the safe country rule according to which asylum seekers from safe countries cannot apply for asylum > Algeria, Angola and India are for instance on this list.	http://www.woz.ch/0633/asylgesetz/tradition-der-verschaerfung [accessed on 19.12.2013]	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	Specific nationalities	Those on the safe country of origin list	More restrictive		
7257	Switzerland	work for asylum seekers possible after 6 monts	1990	Decision of 22 June 1990 - prolongs the three months working ban for asylum seekers to six months	http://www.woz.ch/0633/asylgesetz/tradition-der-verschaerfung [accessed on 19.12.2013]	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Work visa/permit	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	More restrictive		
7258	Switzerland	Trainee agreement with Australia	1991	CH-Australia trainee agreement of 13 November 1991  > young professionals between 20 and 30 years old, who want to improve their professional and linguistic skills, can obtain a residence and work permit for maximum 12 months. The traineeship has to be done in an area close to the education of the trainee.	http://www.bfm.admin.ch/content/bfm/de/home/themen/auslandaufenthalt/stagiaires.html [accessed on 08.07.2013]	Mid-level change	Multi- or bilateral policy	Legal entry and stay	Work visa/permit	Skilled/high-skilled workers	Specific nationalities	Australia	Less restrictive		
7259	Switzerland	preferential treatment of EU citizens	1991	Introduction of the Three-Circle immigration model - which regulated the admission of migrants based on their country of origin: People from EU and EFTA countries belonged to the First Circle and granted facilitated opportunities for immigration.	Focus Migration 2012: 3	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	All migrants	Specific nationalities	EU and EFTA countries at that time	Less restrictive		
