7318	Switzerland	non-EU migration restricted to high-skilled	2008	In September 2006, the new Federal Act on Foreign Nationals (Bundesgesetz über die Ausländerinnen und Ausländer; AuG) was approved in a referendum and came into force in January 2008, replacing the 1931/1934 law - restricting work-related immigration of non-EEA nationals to qualified labour, subject to a quota > A permit may only be issued if the wage and employment conditions meet standards and if no qualified domestic or EU worker willing to work under those conditions can be found. Work permits are granted only to executives, specialists, and other highly qualified workers from outside the EU/European Free-Trade Association (EFTA). The permit is initially valid for one year and can be renewed every year indefinitely; after 10 years the person may receive permanent residence. The number of first-time, year-round, renewable residence permits, which include working rights, is limited to 4,000, and the number of non-renewable, one-year residence permits to 5,000.	SOPEMI 2007: 286; MPI 2005	Mid-level change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Quota/target	Skilled/high-skilled workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Change in restrictiveness cannot be assessed		
