7322	Switzerland	integration enshrined in law for first time	2008	In September 2006, the new Federal Act on Foreign Nationals (Bundesgesetz über die Ausländerinnen und Ausländer; AuG) was approved in a referendum and came into force in January 2008, replacing the 1931/1934 law - created the basis for a nationwide Swiss policy of integration.  > In Switzerland, as far as the integration of the foreign population is concerned, up until the end of the 20th century a policy of laissez-faire was practiced. The 2008 law for the first time embodied the concept of integration, while nonetheless foregoing a practical definition of the concept.	Focus Migration 2012: 6	Minor change	National policy	Integration	Language, housing and cultural integration programmes	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	No change		
7323	Switzerland	family reunification for short term workers	2008	In September 2006, the new Federal Act on Foreign Nationals (Bundesgesetz über die Ausländerinnen und Ausländer; AuG) was approved in a referendum and came into force in January 2008, replacing the 1931/1934 law -  improves family reunication: There is now the possibility for relatives to join short-term permit holders in Switzerland. > The foreign spouses and single offspring below the age of 18 of short-term residence permit holders may also be granted a short-term residence permit. This is possible on condition that they share a household with the holder of the short-term residence permit already in Switzerland.  Furthermore, appropriate accommodation must be available and the family must produce proof that they are not recipients of welfare assistance.	FOM 2007: 12	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Entry visa/stay permit	Family members	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive		
