7472	United Kingdom	introduction of a five-tier economic migration points-based system by influential report	2006	'A Points-Based System: Making Migration Work for Britain' - introduced a five-tier economic migration system with the following categories: (1) high skilled, (2) skilled with job offer, (3) low skilled, (4) students, and (5) miscellaneous, which will be implemented gradually between 2008 and 2009 > The underlying idea is to move away from the two-step process in which an employer obtains a work permit and the worker applies for entry or stay clearance. Work permits will be abolished and the role of the employer will be limited to the interview/job offer process. The first two tiers would have a route to  permanent residence subject to meeting five years residence and other requirements. According to tier, migrants would have different entitlements to work or to be joined by their immediate family. Tier 3 for low-skilled workers was never implemented	SOPEMI 2006: 222; MPI 2009	N/A	N/A	Legal entry and stay	Action Plan, Strategy, Report	All migrant workers	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
