7527	United Kingdom	2013 immigration bill introduced	2013	In October 2013, amendments to the Immigration Act were introduced in Parliament - with far-reaching consequences for appeals and expulsion procedures, as well as border controls and entry rules > Some sugestion are:  * to give further powers to immigration and police officers to search individuals and premises, enlarge the states powers to record, use and retain biometrics. * to remove the existing right of appeal against 17 or so immigration decisions such as refusal of leave to enter or remain, a decision to deport or a decision to remove.  They are to be replaced by new rights of appeal against refusal of a protection claim (i.e. a claim for refugee status or humanitarian protection), refusal of a human rights claim or a decision to revoke a persons protection status.   * to make it unlawful to rent accommodation to a person who requires but does not have leave to enter or remain or a person who has leave subject to a condition preventing him or her from renting.  * to introduce an immigration status requirements for the issue of a driving licence  * to facilitate border control and expulsion activities	http://www.freemovement.org.uk/2013/10/11/new-immigration-bill-summary-of-clauses/?utm_source=feedburner&utm_medium=email&utm_campaign=Feed%3A+FreeMovement+%28Free+Movement%29 [accessed on 14.10.2013]	N/A	N/A	N/A	Contextual elements	All migrants	All foreign nationalities	N/A	N/A		
