7629	United Kingdom	Amendment to section 67 of the Immigration Act on 1 October 2019	2019	Amendment to section 67 of the Immigration Act on 1 October 2019 - provided that from 1 October 2019, those transferred to the UK under section 67 will be granted 'section 67 leave' shortly after arrival and upon receipt of a short application and not if their asylum application is unsuccessful like previously > This form of leave allows them to study, work, access public funds and healthcare, and is a route to settlement which they would not ordinarily have had. This does not prevent the child from claiming asylum should they wish to do so. If they chose to do so, they will still retain their section 67 leave whilst their claim for asylum is considered.	https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/947900/sect-67-of-the-immigration-act-2016-leave-v3.0ext.pdf	Minor change	National policy	Legal entry and stay	Access to social benefits and socio-economic rights	Refugees, asylum seekers and other vulnerable people	All foreign nationalities	N/A	Less restrictive	Before the 1 October 2019, those transferred under section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016 claimed asylum once transferred from a participating state. If their claim was successful, they received refugee status. If the individuals asylum claim was unsuccessful, they would receive section 67 leave.	
